INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Introduction', 'EECS 485 Web Systems Introduction Prof. Almomani Announcements • Please read the syllabus and eecs485.org • Lab starts this week. • Project 1 due soon. 2 About Almomani • Prof. Almomani. • Ph.D. in CS (Computer Vision). • Taught EECS 484 & 485 multiple times. 3 3 Big Questions of EECS 485 • How do websites work? • How do search engines work? • How can we build website to handle millions/billions of users? 4 Some things you''ll build • Instagram • 3 different ways • Projects 1-3 • MapReduce • Project 4 • Search engine • Project 5 5 Some technologies you’ll use • HTML/CSS • Shell scripting • SQL • SQLite database • Python • Flask web framework •JavaScript • React/JS framework • Hadoop. 6 Agenda • What is EECS 485 about? • Logistics • How the web works • Python 7 Course format • Lectures • In-person, recorded • No attendance required • Labs • In-person • One lab will be recorded • No attendance required • Attend any section at any time • Office hours • In-person and Remote • See calendar on eecs485.org 8 Getting help • eecs485.org • Links to all course resources • edstem.org • Best for technical questions and project updates • eecs485staff@umich.edu • Best for non-technical questions • almomani@umich.edu (individual professor email addresses) • Best for confidential matters 9 Projects and Collaboration • You can modify your group between projects • For those retaking the course: you may work in a group, or you may reuse your old code, but not both. • We can help you find a group (optional). Watch for email. 10 Task Collaboration Project 1 No Projects 2-5 Groups of 2 - 3 Lab • YES we have lab this week • If you''re on the waitlist, attend any lab, or watch the recording. • Materials are posted on eecs485.org • Expect first segment project intro and lecture review • Second segment hands-on help with projects 11 Exams • Put the dates in your calendar • See eecs485.org • No make-up exam • In-person, paper • Cheat sheet OK • Format • Part multiple choice • Part code and free response • Content • Concepts from lecture • Code from projects 12 Grades • Draft letter grade after the midterm 13 Projects (5 x 10%) 50% Midterm 25% Final 25% Agenda • What is EECS 485 about? • Logistics • How the web works • Python 14 How the web works • You click a link on a website. What do you think happens next? A. Your computer asks another computer for information B. The page is already saved on your computer C. A picture of the page is sent to you D. Something else? 15 How the web works 1.The client asks the server for a page 2.The server sends files back 3.The client’s browser displays the page • This is called request response cycle. 16 internet client server How the web works 17 internet Client:');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Introduction', 'sheet OK • Format • Part multiple choice • Part code and free response • Content • Concepts from lecture • Code from projects 12 Grades • Draft letter grade after the midterm 13 Projects (5 x 10%) 50% Midterm 25% Final 25% Agenda • What is EECS 485 about? • Logistics • How the web works • Python 14 How the web works • You click a link on a website. What do you think happens next? A. Your computer asks another computer for information B. The page is already saved on your computer C. A picture of the page is sent to you D. Something else? 15 How the web works 1.The client asks the server for a page 2.The server sends files back 3.The client’s browser displays the page • This is called request response cycle. 16 internet client server How the web works 17 internet Client: You Server: Amazon.com How the web works 18 internet Client: You Server: amazon.com Request: What’s at amazon.com? How the web works 19 internet Client: You Server: amazon.com Request: What’s at amazon.com? Response: Files (HTML, CSS) How the web works 20 internet Client: You Server: amazon.com Request: What’s at amazon.com? Response: Files (HTML, CSS)Client’s browser renders the Files What does a server respond with? •A server might respond with different kinds of files. • HTML • CSS • JavaScript •We''ll talk about JavaScript later in the semester 21 HTML: HyperText Markup Language • HTML describes the content on a page • Example index.html <!DOCTYPE html> <html lang="en"> <body> Hello world! </body> </html> • The browser does not show the tags but uses them them to decide how to display the content. 22 HTML: HyperText Markup Language • HTML describes the content on a page • Example index.html <!DOCTYPE html> <html lang="en"> <body> Hello world! </body> </html> • The browser does not show the tags but uses them them to decide how to display the content. 23 Open tag Close tag Attribute CSS: Cascading Style Sheets • CSS describes the layout or style of a page. • Example: style.css body { background: pink; } 24 CSS : Cascading Style Sheets • CSS describes the layout or style of a page. • Example style.css body { background: pink; } • Link to CSS in HTML 25 <html lang="en"> <head> <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/style.css"> </head> <body> Hello world! </body> </html> HTML: Example • How can I color each <p> element a different color in index.html? <html lang="en"> <body> <P>Hello</P> <P>World!</P> </body> </html> 26 HTML: Example • How can I color each <p> element a different color in index.html? <html lang="en"> <body> <P class=“first“>Hello</P> <P class=“second“>World! </P> </body> </html> 27 CSS: Example style.css .first { color: red; } .second { color: blue; } 28 <html lang="en"> <head> <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/style.css"> </head> <body> <P class=”first”>Hello</P> <P class=”second”>world!</P> </body> </html> Static pages • A static page doesn’t change • Often HTML,CSS, Images files • Every user sees the same page •Example: Server responds with the same');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Introduction', 'pink; } 24 CSS : Cascading Style Sheets • CSS describes the layout or style of a page. • Example style.css body { background: pink; } • Link to CSS in HTML 25 <html lang="en"> <head> <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/style.css"> </head> <body> Hello world! </body> </html> HTML: Example • How can I color each <p> element a different color in index.html? <html lang="en"> <body> <P>Hello</P> <P>World!</P> </body> </html> 26 HTML: Example • How can I color each <p> element a different color in index.html? <html lang="en"> <body> <P class=“first“>Hello</P> <P class=“second“>World! </P> </body> </html> 27 CSS: Example style.css .first { color: red; } .second { color: blue; } 28 <html lang="en"> <head> <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/style.css"> </head> <body> <P class=”first”>Hello</P> <P class=”second”>world!</P> </body> </html> Static pages • A static page doesn’t change • Often HTML,CSS, Images files • Every user sees the same page •Example: Server responds with the same files for each request. 29 <html lang="en"> <body> Hello world! </body> </html> body { background: pink; } Static page server • A static file server sends files that don''t change • HTML, CSS, images, etc. • Server loads the file from disk and sends to client • You''ll use a static file server in project 1 30 <html lang="en"> <body> Hello world! </body> </html> body { background: pink; } How a static page is served • Client requests a page • Static file server find the files • Server sends the file back • Client’s browser displays the page 31 <html lang="en"> <body> Hello world! </body> </html> body { background: pink; } Exercise Overview • We will • Create a static page • Run a static file server • View the page in a client’s browser 32 Step 1: Create a static page 33 internet Client Server <html lang="en"> <body> Hello from EECS 485! </body> </html> • Create mysite folder for your website • This folder will contain your static files. • Inside the folder, create a file that is called index.html Step 2: Start a static file server • Start the server from inside the folder > python3 -m http.server Serving HTTP on 0.0.0.0 port 8000 ... • Python is now acting as a static file server 34 internet Client Server <html lang="en"> <body> Hello from EECS 485! </body> </html> > python3 -m http.server Step 3: Visit the page 35 internet Client Server <html lang="en"> <body> Hello from EECS 485! </body> </html> > python3 -m http.server • Open your browser and go to: • or • Hello from EECS 485! Agenda • What is EECS 485 about? • Logistics • How the web works • Python 36 Why Python • Easy to read and write • Great for scripting and servers • Python will be our main backend (server) language 37 Running Python Code • Create a file called add.py • Run it in the terminal $ python3 add.py 1 38 x = 0 x = x + 1 print(x) Python Interactive Mode • You can also run Python');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Introduction', 'http.server Serving HTTP on 0.0.0.0 port 8000 ... • Python is now acting as a static file server 34 internet Client Server <html lang="en"> <body> Hello from EECS 485! </body> </html> > python3 -m http.server Step 3: Visit the page 35 internet Client Server <html lang="en"> <body> Hello from EECS 485! </body> </html> > python3 -m http.server • Open your browser and go to: • or • Hello from EECS 485! Agenda • What is EECS 485 about? • Logistics • How the web works • Python 36 Why Python • Easy to read and write • Great for scripting and servers • Python will be our main backend (server) language 37 Running Python Code • Create a file called add.py • Run it in the terminal $ python3 add.py 1 38 x = 0 x = x + 1 print(x) Python Interactive Mode • You can also run Python interactively $ python3 > x = 0 > x = x + 1 > x 1 39 Python Variables • No type declarations • Types are inferred automatically • Example: > x = 10 > Y = 3 > Print (x+y) 13 40 Python Blocks • Python uses indentation • Bolacks are defined by whitespace • No { } like C/C++ • Example: > If x > 10: > print(“x is large”) 41 Python Lists • A list store multiple values >numbers = [10,20,30] • Loop through a list >for n in numbers: > print(n) 42 Python Dictionaries • Dictionaries store key-value pairs: student = { ”name": ”john", ”umid": ”123" } • Access values: >print(student[”name"]) 43 Python functions • Functions group reusable code >def increment(x): > return x + 1 >print(increment(5)) 6 44 Python standard library • Python ships with a huge standard library (Built-in tools) • • Python includes many useful libraries: • pathlib: filename manipulations • sys: system functions, e.g., exit • json: read/write JSON files • shutil: file manipulations • You will use these in Project 1. 45 Python third party libraries • Some libraries are not built in, but you will need them for project 1 • jinja2: HTML template • click: command-line tools and argument parsing • Install with $ pip install jinja2 click 46 Best Python documentation • Python.org 47 Summary • Please read syllabus and eecs485.org • How the web works (Request response cycle): client requests and server responds • Static page is the same every time the page is loaded • Static file server sends a copy of a file from disk • Python programs are run by an interpreter 48 Your to-do list • Learn HTML • • Learn (a little) CSS • • Learn Python • • Get started on Project 1 • Link on eecs485.org 49 Waitlist • Wolverine Access handles the waitlist automatically • When one enrolled student drops, Wolverine Access issues permission via email to one waitlisted student • Follow the instructions in the email • Unfortunately, it''s hard to predict how many students will drop 50');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Introduction', '• jinja2: HTML template • click: command-line tools and argument parsing • Install with $ pip install jinja2 click 46 Best Python documentation • Python.org 47 Summary • Please read syllabus and eecs485.org • How the web works (Request response cycle): client requests and server responds • Static page is the same every time the page is loaded • Static file server sends a copy of a file from disk • Python programs are run by an interpreter 48 Your to-do list • Learn HTML • • Learn (a little) CSS • • Learn Python • • Get started on Project 1 • Link on eecs485.org 49 Waitlist • Wolverine Access handles the waitlist automatically • When one enrolled student drops, Wolverine Access issues permission via email to one waitlisted student • Follow the instructions in the email • Unfortunately, it''s hard to predict how many students will drop 50');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Static Pages', 'Static Pages Agenda • Review • HTML • CSS • The request response cycle • URL encoding • HTTP 2 Review: how the web works • The client asks the server for a page • The server sends files back • The client’s browser displays the page • This is called request response cycle. 3 internet client server Review: The request response cycle 4 internet Client: You Server: amazon.com Request: What’s at amazon.com? Response: Files (HTML, CSS)Client’s browser renders the Files Review: static pages • A static page doesn’t change • Often HTML,CSS, Images files • Every user sees the same page 5 body { background: pink; } <html lang="en"> <body> Hello world! </body> </html> Agenda • Review • HTML • CSS • The request response cycle • URL encoding • HTTP 6 HTML: HyperText Markup Language • How many tags are needed to create the following HTML page? 7 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: HyperText Markup Language <!DOCTYPE html> 8 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: HyperText Markup Language <!DOCTYPE html> 9 Localhost:8000\index.html I’m html HTML: HyperText Markup Language <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> • HTML tags to determine structure and presentation; but only displays the content inside them. • Not all HTML tags require closing tags, e.g. <br> <img src=“..”> 10 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: HyperText Markup Language <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> • HTML tags to determine structure and presentation; but only displays the content inside them. • Not all HTML tags require closing tags, e.g. <br> <img src=“..”> 11 Localhost:8000\index.html Title HTML: HyperText Markup Language <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> • HTML tags to determine structure and presentation; but only displays the content inside them. • Not all HTML tags require closing tags, e.g. <br> <img src=“..”> 12 Localhost:8000\index.html Close tag Open tag HTML: HyperText Markup Language <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> <body> Hello world! </body> 13 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: HyperText Markup Language <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> <body> Hello world! </body> 14 Body Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: <h1> through <h6> • <h1> … <h6>: define headings. • <h1> represents the highest-level. • <h6> represents the lowest-level. <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> <body> <h1>Hello world!</h1> </body> 15 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: <p> • <p>: Paragraph, start new line <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> <body> <h1>Hello world!</h1> <p> Hello in other languages: </p> </body> 16 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: <ul> and <li> <ul> and <li>: List of items. <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> <body> <h1>Hello world!</h1> <p> Hello in other languages: </p> <ul> <li>Bonjour</li> <li>Ciao</li> </ul> </body> 17 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: <ul> and <li> <a> : create a hyperlink that navigates to another webpage. <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> <body> <h1>Hello world!</h1> <p> Hello in other languages: </p> <ul> <li>Bonjour</li> <li>Ciao</li> </ul> <a href="index2.html"> More </a> </body> 18 Localhost:8000\index.html Escape strings in HTML • Some characters have special meaning in an application context • Example: “<“ in HTML • What if you want to communicate such a character as an ordinary character? • Example: “I < 3 chickens” • Need an escape string • Example:');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Static Pages', '<body> <h1>Hello world!</h1> </body> 15 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: <p> • <p>: Paragraph, start new line <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> <body> <h1>Hello world!</h1> <p> Hello in other languages: </p> </body> 16 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: <ul> and <li> <ul> and <li>: List of items. <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> <body> <h1>Hello world!</h1> <p> Hello in other languages: </p> <ul> <li>Bonjour</li> <li>Ciao</li> </ul> </body> 17 Localhost:8000\index.html HTML: <ul> and <li> <a> : create a hyperlink that navigates to another webpage. <!DOCTYPE html> <head> <title>Web page</title> </head> <body> <h1>Hello world!</h1> <p> Hello in other languages: </p> <ul> <li>Bonjour</li> <li>Ciao</li> </ul> <a href="index2.html"> More </a> </body> 18 Localhost:8000\index.html Escape strings in HTML • Some characters have special meaning in an application context • Example: “<“ in HTML • What if you want to communicate such a character as an ordinary character? • Example: “I < 3 chickens” • Need an escape string • Example: “I &lt; 3 chickens” 19 Escape strings in URLS • Some characters have special meaning in an application context • Example: “ “ (a space) in a URL • What if you want to communicate such a character as an ordinary character? • Example: hello world.jpg • Need an escape string • Example: hello%20world.jpg 20 Document Object Model (DOM) • In addition to rendering the webpage, the browser will create the DOM. • HTML tags form a tree that is called the Document Object Model (DOM). <html> <head></head> <body> <p>Hello world!</p> <p>I &lt;3 chickens</p> </body> </html> Document Object Model (DOM) • Inspect the DOM with • Chrome developer tools • Firefox developer tools Agenda • Review • HTML • CSS • The request response cycle • URL encoding • HTTP 23 CSS • Cascading Style Sheets • Add style to web pages: • Colors • Layout 24 CSS – how to link an HTML with a CSS file. • HTML for content <!-- index.html --> <html> <head> </head> <body> <p>Hello world!</p> </body> </html> 25 CSS – how to link an HTML with a CSS file. • HTML for content <!-- index.html --> <html> <head> <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="style.css"> </head> <body> <p>Hello world!</p> </body> </html> 26 CSS – how to link an HTML with a CSS file. • CSS for layout /* style.css */ body { background-color: lightblue; } p { margin-left: 20px; } 27 HTML: Example • Color each <p> element in a different color? <html lang="en"> <body> <p>Hello</p> <p>World!</p> </body> </html> 28 HTML: Example <html lang="en"> <body> <p class="first">Hello</p> <p class="second">World! </p> </body> </html> 29 HTML: Example <html lang="en"> <body> <p class="first">Hello</p> <p class="second">World!</p> </body> </html> 30 CSS: Example style.css .first { color: red; } .second { color: blue; } 31 CSS: Example style.css .first { color: red; } .second { color: blue; } 32 <html lang="en"> <head> <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/style.css"> </head> <body> <p class=“first”>Hello</p> <p class=“second”>world!</p> </body> </html> Agenda • Review • HTML • CSS • The request response cycle • URL encoding • HTTP 33 Uniform Resource Locator (URL) • The client requests a web page');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Static Pages', '<p>Hello world!</p> </body> </html> 26 CSS – how to link an HTML with a CSS file. • CSS for layout /* style.css */ body { background-color: lightblue; } p { margin-left: 20px; } 27 HTML: Example • Color each <p> element in a different color? <html lang="en"> <body> <p>Hello</p> <p>World!</p> </body> </html> 28 HTML: Example <html lang="en"> <body> <p class="first">Hello</p> <p class="second">World! </p> </body> </html> 29 HTML: Example <html lang="en"> <body> <p class="first">Hello</p> <p class="second">World!</p> </body> </html> 30 CSS: Example style.css .first { color: red; } .second { color: blue; } 31 CSS: Example style.css .first { color: red; } .second { color: blue; } 32 <html lang="en"> <head> <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/style.css"> </head> <body> <p class=“first”>Hello</p> <p class=“second”>world!</p> </body> </html> Agenda • Review • HTML • CSS • The request response cycle • URL encoding • HTTP 33 Uniform Resource Locator (URL) • The client requests a web page by typing “ in the browser''s address bar 34 URL: Protocol • • Protocol: what "language" is used for request-response cycle • HTTP • HTTPs – Secure version of HTTP 35 URL: Server • • Which computer we are communicating with • localhost or 127.0.0.1 means the same computer as the web browser 36 URL: Port • • More than one program is running on the server computer, and the port number specifies which program to communicate with. • Port can be implied • HTTP: 80 • HTTPS: 443 37 URL: Port • • More than one program is running on the server computer, and the port number specifies which program to communicate with. • Port can be implied • HTTP: 80 • HTTPS: 443 38 80 443 Program - HTTP Program-HTTPS amazon.com URL: Path • • Like a file path • If no file is specified, default is index.html • is the same as 39 Absolute vs. Relative paths • Absolute path • Always starts from the root directory ( / ) of the website. • Starts with a slash (/) – root directory. • Examples: <img src="/uploads/image.jpg"> • No matter where the current page is: /index.html /users/profile.html /admin/settings.html • The browser always goes to (/uploads/image.jpg) 40 Absolute vs. Relative paths • Relative path • The location of a file based on the directory you are currently in. • Doesn’t start with a slash (/) • Example, if current page is: /users/awdeorio/profile.html And you write: <img src="uploads/image.jpg"> Browser goes to: /users/awdeorio/uploads/image.jpg 41 URL: Query •Parameters sent to the server inside the URL •Key-value form •We won''t use these much in 485 42 URL: Fragment •Only used by web browser, not server •We won''t use these much in 485 •Example: navigate directly to the section labeled "Linking" 43 Agenda • Review • HTML • CSS • The request response cycle • URL encoding • HTTP 44 Details of the Request/ Response > GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* 45 < HTTP/1.1 200 OK < Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2017 20:04:20 GMT < Server: Apache/2.2.15');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Static Pages', '• The browser always goes to (/uploads/image.jpg) 40 Absolute vs. Relative paths • Relative path • The location of a file based on the directory you are currently in. • Doesn’t start with a slash (/) • Example, if current page is: /users/awdeorio/profile.html And you write: <img src="uploads/image.jpg"> Browser goes to: /users/awdeorio/uploads/image.jpg 41 URL: Query •Parameters sent to the server inside the URL •Key-value form •We won''t use these much in 485 42 URL: Fragment •Only used by web browser, not server •We won''t use these much in 485 •Example: navigate directly to the section labeled "Linking" 43 Agenda • Review • HTML • CSS • The request response cycle • URL encoding • HTTP 44 Details of the Request/ Response > GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* 45 < HTTP/1.1 200 OK < Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2017 20:04:20 GMT < Server: Apache/2.2.15 (Red Hat) < Accept-Ranges: bytes < Connection: close < Transfer-Encoding: chunked < Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8 request response Details of the Request > GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* > • Type of HTTP request methods: • GET: Ask for data. Example: Open a webpage • HEAD: Ask for page info only (no content) Example: Check if a page has changed • POST: Send data to the server Example: Submit a login form 46 Details of the Request > GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* > • The path portion of the URL being requested. • Slash (/) means the main page/homepage of the server. 47 HTTP: Hypertext Transfer Protocol ➢ GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* > • Request/response protocol • Client (your browser) opens connection to server and writes a request • Server responds appropriately • Connection is closed • That’s it • Server can''t open connection to client. • HTTP is stateless: the server does not remember previous requests from the same client. 48 Details of the Request > GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* > • Which server we are communicating with cse.engin.umich.edu. 49 Details of the Request > GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* > • Which browser is making the request. E.g. Chrome/Safari 50 Details of the Request > GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* > • Which file types the client will accept. 51 Details of the Response < HTTP/1.1 200 OK < Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2017 20:04:20 GMT < Server: Apache/2.2.15 (Red Hat) < Accept-Ranges: bytes < Connection: close < Transfer-Encoding: chunked < Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8 52 Details of the Response – Status Code < HTTP/1.1 200 OK < Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2017 20:04:20 GMT < Server: Apache/2.2.15 (Red Hat) < Accept-Ranges: bytes < Connection: close < Transfer-Encoding: chunked < Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8 • Status Code meanings: 1XX: Informational 2XX: Successful, e.g. 200 OK 3XX:');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Static Pages', '*/* > • Which server we are communicating with cse.engin.umich.edu. 49 Details of the Request > GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* > • Which browser is making the request. E.g. Chrome/Safari 50 Details of the Request > GET / HTTP/1.1 > Host: cse.engin.umich.edu > User-Agent: Chrome/7.54.0 > Accept: */* > • Which file types the client will accept. 51 Details of the Response < HTTP/1.1 200 OK < Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2017 20:04:20 GMT < Server: Apache/2.2.15 (Red Hat) < Accept-Ranges: bytes < Connection: close < Transfer-Encoding: chunked < Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8 52 Details of the Response – Status Code < HTTP/1.1 200 OK < Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2017 20:04:20 GMT < Server: Apache/2.2.15 (Red Hat) < Accept-Ranges: bytes < Connection: close < Transfer-Encoding: chunked < Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8 • Status Code meanings: 1XX: Informational 2XX: Successful, e.g. 200 OK 3XX: Redirection error 4XX: Client error, e.g. 404 Not Found 500: Server error 53 Details of the Response: Headers < HTTP/1.1 200 OK < Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2017 20:04:20 GMT < Server: Apache/2.2.15 (Red Hat) < Accept-Ranges: bytes < Connection: close < Transfer-Encoding: chunked < Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8 •Most are optional and describe how the data will be transferred 54 Details of the Response: Content-Type < HTTP/1.1 200 OK < Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2017 20:04:20 GMT < Server: Apache/2.2.15 (Red Hat) < Accept-Ranges: bytes < Connection: close < Transfer-Encoding: chunked < Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8 • Content-type: what kind of file it is text/html image/png • Character encoding UTF-8 most common – it''s like ASCII from C++ but with support for non-English languages 55 Summary • A static page produces the same content every time • Often just HTML/CSS • HTML is for data presentation • How does it look? • CSS defines presentation. • HTTP is a request/response detail. 1. Client opens connection to server and writes a request 2. Server responds 3. Connection is closed 56');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Serverside Dynamic Pages', 'Server-side Dynamic Pages These static web pages are so dull… Agenda • Static pages vs. dynamic pages • Server-side dynamic pages • Dynamic page URL routing • Python decorators 2 Static vs. dynamic content • Static Pages • Show the same content every time. • Example: Wikipedia article pages • Dynamic Pages • Content changes based on user or data • Example: Gmain • Things that are impossible with simple static pages • Web search • Current time • # visitors to page 3 Project 1 = Static content • Pages are static • Pages only change rarely via a manual process • You manually update data, templates (with a text editor) • Run insta485generator to produce new pages • Templates are a way to reduce the work of editing • Everyone sees the same content • Content is not generated per request • Pages stay the same until the next manual update 4 Agenda • Static pages vs. dynamic pages • Server-side dynamic pages • Dynamic page URL routing • Python decorators 5 Server-side dynamic pages • Key idea: The response is the output of a function. 1. Client sends a request 2. Server runs a function 3. The function generates HTML 4. Server sends that HTML back as the response 6 Server-side dynamic pages • Key idea: The response is the output of a function. 1. Client sends a request 2. Server runs a function 3. The function generates HTML 4. Server sends that HTML back as the response 7 Client (Browser) HTML Call a Python function to create HTML and return it Database Request Server Info Server-side dynamic pages example • Flask(Python) generates web pages dynamically on the server # hello.py from flask import Flask app =Flask(__name__) @app.route("/hello") def hello_world(): return "<html><body>Hello World!</body></html>" 8 Server-side dynamic pages example • Flask(Python) generates web pages dynamically on the server # hello.py from flask import Flask app = Flask(__name__) @app.route("/hello") def hello_world(): return "<html><body>Hello World!</body></html>" 9 Flask library for dynamic web pages Server-side dynamic pages example • Flask(Python) generates web pages dynamically on the server # hello.py from flask import Flask app = Flask(__name__) @app.route("/hello") def hello_world(): return "<html><body>Hello World!</body></html>" 10 Call hello_world() when client requests URL /hello Flask library for dynamic web pages Server-side dynamic pages example • Flask(Python) generates web pages dynamically on the server # hello.py from flask import Flask app =Flask(__name__) @app.route("/hello") def hello_world(): return "<html><body>Hello World!</body></html>" 11 Call hello_world() when client requests URL /hello Function returns HTML as the response Flask library for dynamic web pages Server-side dynamic pages example • Start the server $ python3 hello.py Running on • Browse to • localhost is the same as 127.0.0.1 (your own computer) 12 Templating • Templates are a common way to generate server-side dynamic pages. • Example: Python''s jinja2 library • Templets let you mix: • HTML structure • Dynamic data 13 Template example • Template is an HTML file containing jinja2 syntax #hello.html <html> <head><title>Hello world</title></head> <body> {% for word in words %} {{word}}');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Serverside Dynamic Pages', 'Flask app = Flask(__name__) @app.route("/hello") def hello_world(): return "<html><body>Hello World!</body></html>" 10 Call hello_world() when client requests URL /hello Flask library for dynamic web pages Server-side dynamic pages example • Flask(Python) generates web pages dynamically on the server # hello.py from flask import Flask app =Flask(__name__) @app.route("/hello") def hello_world(): return "<html><body>Hello World!</body></html>" 11 Call hello_world() when client requests URL /hello Function returns HTML as the response Flask library for dynamic web pages Server-side dynamic pages example • Start the server $ python3 hello.py Running on • Browse to • localhost is the same as 127.0.0.1 (your own computer) 12 Templating • Templates are a common way to generate server-side dynamic pages. • Example: Python''s jinja2 library • Templets let you mix: • HTML structure • Dynamic data 13 Template example • Template is an HTML file containing jinja2 syntax #hello.html <html> <head><title>Hello world</title></head> <body> {% for word in words %} {{word}} {% endfor %} </body> </html> 14 Rendering templates with Flask # hello.py from flask import Flask app =Flask(__name__) @app.route("/hello") def hello_world(): return "<html><body>Hello World!</body></html>" context = {"words": ["Hello", "World!"]} return flask.render_template( "hello.html", **context) 15 Input: Template + Data Output: Final HTML page Run Flask example • Start the server $ python3 hello.py • Open in browser • Flask: Runs Python function; Renders template and Returns HTML 16 Project 2 = Server-side dynamic content Client requests a URL • Looks like a file path • But server runs a function • How does function generate content? • Data is stored in a database (SQLite) • Queries database to get relevant data • Builds Python object • Renders template using object • Returns resulting HTML • Content is generated specifically for each request 17 Agenda • Static pages vs. dynamic pages • Server-side dynamic pages • Dynamic page URL routing • Python decorators 18 URL routing • Which URLs map to which functions? • This is called URL routing • When a client requests a URL, how does a server know which function to call? • What about routes like a user page, where the function could have an input? 19 Routes with inputs from flask import Flask app = Flask(__name__) @app.route(''/u/<username>'') def show_user(username): return "hello " + username + "!" @app.route(''/p/<postid>'') def show_post(postid): return "post "+ postid + "!" 20 Static routes vs. dynamic routes • Static pages: one URL maps to one file • Example: /index.html • Dynamic pages: many URLs map to one function • Example: calls show_user("John") • Example: calls show_user("smith") 21 @app.route(''/u/<username>'') def show_user(username): return "hello " + username + "! " URL routing • Which URLs map to which functions? • This is called URL routing • Routing table mapping URL to function-reference • /u/ show_user • /p/ show_post • When a request comes in, Flask: • Finds the matching pattern • Gets the function • Calls the function 22 Routing (Decorators) • Flask uses a Python decorator to describe routing • A decorator is a higher order function @app.route(''/u/<username>'') def show_user(username): return "hello “ +');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Serverside Dynamic Pages', 'with inputs from flask import Flask app = Flask(__name__) @app.route(''/u/<username>'') def show_user(username): return "hello " + username + "!" @app.route(''/p/<postid>'') def show_post(postid): return "post "+ postid + "!" 20 Static routes vs. dynamic routes • Static pages: one URL maps to one file • Example: /index.html • Dynamic pages: many URLs map to one function • Example: calls show_user("John") • Example: calls show_user("smith") 21 @app.route(''/u/<username>'') def show_user(username): return "hello " + username + "! " URL routing • Which URLs map to which functions? • This is called URL routing • Routing table mapping URL to function-reference • /u/ show_user • /p/ show_post • When a request comes in, Flask: • Finds the matching pattern • Gets the function • Calls the function 22 Routing (Decorators) • Flask uses a Python decorator to describe routing • A decorator is a higher order function @app.route(''/u/<username>'') def show_user(username): return "hello “ + username +”!" 23 Why this works: First Class Functions • In Python, functions are first class objects • Recall from EECS 280, that first class objects can be: • Passed as input • Returned as output • Created at runtime • Destroyed at runtime 24 Create Function at runtime • Function object contains function execution "code“ created when function is declared def show_user(username): return "hello "+username+ "!" output = show_user("John") print(output) 25 Pass a function as input def show_user(username): return "hello”+ username+ ”!" def show_post(postid): return "post”+ postid+ ”!" def show(func, var): print(func(var)) show(show_user, “Smith") show(show_post, 1) 26 Pass a function as input def show_user(username): return "hello " + username+ "!" def show_post(postid): return "post "+ postid+ "!" def show(func, var): print(func(var)) show(show_user, "Smith") show(show_post, 1) 27 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! post 1! Return a function as output def get_view(url): if url.startswith("/u"): return show_user elif url.startswith("/p"): return show_post else: return None def view(baseurl, slug): func = get_view(baseurl) print(func(slug)) view("/u", "Smith") 28 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! def show_user(username): return "hello ..." def show_post(postid): return "post ..." Return a function as output def get_view(url): if url.startswith("/u"): return show_user elif url.startswith("/p"): return show_post else: return None def view(baseurl, slug): func = get_view(baseurl) print(func(slug)) view("/u", "Smith") 29 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! def show_user(username): return "hello ..." def show_post(postid): return "post ..." /u /Smith Return a function as output def get_view(url): if url.startswith("/u"): return show_user elif url.startswith("/p"): return show_post else: return None def view(baseurl, slug): func = get_view(baseurl) print(func(slug)) view("/u", "Smith") 30 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! def show_user(username): return "hello ..." def show_post(postid): return "post ..." /u /Smith /u Return a function as output def get_view(url): if url.startswith("/u"): return show_user elif url.startswith("/p"): return show_post else: return None def view(baseurl, slug): func = get_view(baseurl) print(func(slug)) view("/u", "Smith") 31 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! def show_user(username): return "hello ..." def show_post(postid): return "post ..." /u /Smith /u Return a function as output def get_view(url): if url.startswith("/u"): return show_user elif url.startswith("/p"): return show_post else: return None def view(baseurl, slug): func = get_view(baseurl) print(func(slug)) view("/u", "Smith") 32 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! def show_user(username): return');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Serverside Dynamic Pages', 'get_view(baseurl) print(func(slug)) view("/u", "Smith") 29 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! def show_user(username): return "hello ..." def show_post(postid): return "post ..." /u /Smith Return a function as output def get_view(url): if url.startswith("/u"): return show_user elif url.startswith("/p"): return show_post else: return None def view(baseurl, slug): func = get_view(baseurl) print(func(slug)) view("/u", "Smith") 30 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! def show_user(username): return "hello ..." def show_post(postid): return "post ..." /u /Smith /u Return a function as output def get_view(url): if url.startswith("/u"): return show_user elif url.startswith("/p"): return show_post else: return None def view(baseurl, slug): func = get_view(baseurl) print(func(slug)) view("/u", "Smith") 31 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! def show_user(username): return "hello ..." def show_post(postid): return "post ..." /u /Smith /u Return a function as output def get_view(url): if url.startswith("/u"): return show_user elif url.startswith("/p"): return show_post else: return None def view(baseurl, slug): func = get_view(baseurl) print(func(slug)) view("/u", "Smith") 32 $ python3 test.py hello Smith! def show_user(username): return "hello ..." def show_post(postid): return "post ..." /u /Smith /u Show_user Connecting to routing • Flask routing is conceptually: • Routing table mapping URL to function-reference • /u/ show_user • /p/ show_post func = routing_table[url] func(parameter) • Routing = choose a function based on the URL, then call it. 33 Agenda • Static pages vs. dynamic pages • Server-side dynamic pages • Dynamic page URL routing • Python decorators 34 Decorator • Flask routing uses decorators to connect URLs to functions. • A decorator is a function that takes a function and returns a function • It wraps another function to add or modify behavior 35 @app.route(''/u/<username>'') def show_user(username): return "hello " + username + "! " Simple decorators def register(func): print("registered ” + func.__name__) return func def show_user(username): return "hello " + username + "!" show_user = register(show_user) print(show_user(“smith")) 36 What is the output? Simple decorators def register(func): print("register ” + func.__name__) return func def show_user(username): return "hello “ + username +”!" # "Manual" decorator happens here show_user = register(show_user) print(show_user(“smith")) 37 $ python3 test.py Register show_user hello smith! Decorator syntactic sugar def register(func): print("register” + func.__name__) return func @register # Python decorator syntax def show_user(username): return "hello “ + username +”!" show_user = register(show_user) print(show_user(“smith")) 38 $ python3 test.py Register show_user hello smith! Summary • Static pages: Server response is the same every time • Server-side dynamic pages: Server response is the output of a function • URL routing: When a client requests a server-side dynamic pages URL, server routes the request to a function • Decorator is a function that transforms another function and used by Python/Flask for URL routing 39');
