must wait • Problem: synchronous requests are slow • Can''t send the second request until the first response has arrived 26 function showPosts() { post1 = fetchJSONSync("/api/v1/posts/1/"); updateDOM(post1); post2 = fetchJSONSync("/api/v1/posts/2/"); updateDOM(post2); } Solution: asynchronous requests • Problem: synchronous requests are slow • Solution: send both requests right away without waiting for the response •fetchJSON is a simplified version of the Fetch API 28 function showPosts() { const post_promise1 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") const post_promise2 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") // Wait for responses ... updateDOM(post1); updateDOM(post2); } Asynchronous programming • Asynchronous programming: interleave tasks • Requests run in the background while the program keeps going. • Programmer controls when tasks take turns 29 Async timing diagram 30 function showPosts() { const postPromise1 = fetchJSON(".../1/"); const postPromise2 = fetchJSON(".../2/"); // Wait for responses* ... updateDOM(post1); updateDOM(post2); } *This code is incomplete. We still need to connect postPromise1 to post1. Async timing diagram 31 function showPosts() { const postPromise1 = fetchJSON(".../1/"); const postPromise2 = fetchJSON(".../2/"); // Wait for responses* ... updateDOM(post1); updateDOM(post2); } *This code is incomplete. We still need to connect postPromise1 to post1. Client Server wait fetch update fetch update Solution: asynchronous requests • Problem: If we send both requests right away, the response might not be ready yet. What should fetchJSON()return? 32 function showPosts() { const post_promise1 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") const post_promise2 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") // Wait for responses ... updateDOM(post1); updateDOM(post2); } Solution: asynchronous requests • Problem: If we send both requests right away, the response might not be ready yet. What should fetchJSON()return? • Answer: Promises that will eventually hold the post 33 function showPosts() {