INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Asynchronous Programming', '} *This code is incomplete. We still need to connect postPromise1 to post1. Async timing diagram 31 function showPosts() { const postPromise1 = fetchJSON(".../1/"); const postPromise2 = fetchJSON(".../2/"); // Wait for responses* ... updateDOM(post1); updateDOM(post2); } *This code is incomplete. We still need to connect postPromise1 to post1. Client Server wait fetch update fetch update Solution: asynchronous requests • Problem: If we send both requests right away, the response might not be ready yet. What should fetchJSON()return? 32 function showPosts() { const post_promise1 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") const post_promise2 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") // Wait for responses ... updateDOM(post1); updateDOM(post2); } Solution: asynchronous requests • Problem: If we send both requests right away, the response might not be ready yet. What should fetchJSON()return? • Answer: Promises that will eventually hold the post 33 function showPosts() { const post_promise1 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") const post_promise2 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") // Wait for responses ... updateDOM(post1); updateDOM(post2); } Review: Promises • A Promise represents a value that will be available in the future • A Promise controls the flow of asynchronous operations • fetchJSON() sends a request • fetchJSON()returns a Promise 34 function showPosts() { const postPromise1 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/"); const postPromise2 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/"); // Wait for responses ... } Review: Promise handler (callback) • Promise handler runs when Promise is fulfilled • Handler is a function provided by .then() 35 function showPosts() { const postPromise1 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/"); postPromise1.then(post => { updateDOM(post); }); } Review: Refactor • If we refactor, will the output change? • No. The handler runs when the response arrives. 36 function showPosts() { const prom1 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/"); const prom2 = fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/"); prom1.then(post => { updateDOM(post); }); prom2.then(post => { updateDOM(post); }); } function showPosts() { fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post); }); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post); }); } Agenda • Synchronous requests • Asynchronous requests • Promise review • Asynchronous requests with ordered page updates • Closures • Idiomatic asynchronous requests with Promise chains 37 Problem with asynchronous requests • What happens if responses arrive out of order? • E.g., varying network conditions • Let''s modify our REST API to randomly delay some responses • Some responses are fast, some are slow INFO in app: Request /api/v1/posts/1/ received INFO in app: Request /api/v1/posts/1/ delayed INFO in app: Request /api/v1/posts/2/ received INFO in app: Response /api/v1/posts/2/ INFO in app: Response /api/v1/posts/1/ 38 Timing diagram with delayed response 39 Client Server wait fetch update fetch update Ordering problem • Problem: different response order -> different page display order 40 function updateDOM(post) { // Append post to DOM. } Solution: ordered placeholders • Problem: different response order -> different page display order • Solution: placeholders 1. Create placeholder div nodes in the right order 2. Send requests 3. When response arrives, update the right placeholder 41 Placeholders • Replace single DOM entry node with several placeholder nodes • You could also do this with JavaScript 42 <html> <div id="JSEntry1">Loading post 1 ...</div> <div id="JSEntry2">Loading post 2 ...</div> <!-- ... --> </html> <html> <div id="JSEntry">Loading posts ...</div> <!-- ... --> </html>');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Asynchronous Programming', 'are fast, some are slow INFO in app: Request /api/v1/posts/1/ received INFO in app: Request /api/v1/posts/1/ delayed INFO in app: Request /api/v1/posts/2/ received INFO in app: Response /api/v1/posts/2/ INFO in app: Response /api/v1/posts/1/ 38 Timing diagram with delayed response 39 Client Server wait fetch update fetch update Ordering problem • Problem: different response order -> different page display order 40 function updateDOM(post) { // Append post to DOM. } Solution: ordered placeholders • Problem: different response order -> different page display order • Solution: placeholders 1. Create placeholder div nodes in the right order 2. Send requests 3. When response arrives, update the right placeholder 41 Placeholders • Replace single DOM entry node with several placeholder nodes • You could also do this with JavaScript 42 <html> <div id="JSEntry1">Loading post 1 ...</div> <div id="JSEntry2">Loading post 2 ...</div> <!-- ... --> </html> <html> <div id="JSEntry">Loading posts ...</div> <!-- ... --> </html> Aside: helper function • Helper function updates DOM at a specific div 43 function updateDOM(post, div) { const t = document.createTextNode(post.owner); div.appendChild(t); const br = document.createElement(''br''); div.appendChild(br); const img = document.createElement(''img''); img.setAttribute(''src'', post.imgUrl); div.appendChild(img); } Placeholders • When response 1 arrives, callback updates first placeholder div • When response 2 arrives, callback updates second placeholder div • Order of responses does not matter 44 <html> <div id="JSEntry1">Loading post 1 ...</div> <div id="JSEntry2">Loading post 2 ...</div> <!-- ... --> </html> function showPosts() { const div1 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry1''); const div2 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry2''); // Send requests, update the right div fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div1); }); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div2); }); } Ordered page from unordered responses Page always looks like this, even if response 2 arrives first Page never looks like this 45 Agenda • Synchronous requests • Asynchronous requests • Promise review • Asynchronous requests with ordered page updates • Closures • Idiomatic asynchronous requests with Promise chains 46 Inner functions • An inner function is a function defined inside a function • Our previous example used (anonymous) inner functions 47 function showPosts() { const div1 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry1''); const div2 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry2''); // Send requests, update the right div fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div1); }); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div2); }); } Access outer function''s variable • The inner function has access to the outer function''s variables 48 function showPosts() { const div1 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry1''); const div2 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry2''); // Send requests, update the right div fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div1); }); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div2); }); } Outer function returns first • The outer function returns first • The inner function runs later 49 function showPosts() { const div1 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry1''); const div2 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry2''); // Send requests, update the right div fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div1); }); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div2); }); } Closure • An inner function has access to an outer function''s variables • Lexically scoped name binding • This is called a closure • What happens to the outer function variables when the outer function');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Asynchronous Programming', 'div fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div1); }); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div2); }); } Access outer function''s variable • The inner function has access to the outer function''s variables 48 function showPosts() { const div1 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry1''); const div2 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry2''); // Send requests, update the right div fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div1); }); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div2); }); } Outer function returns first • The outer function returns first • The inner function runs later 49 function showPosts() { const div1 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry1''); const div2 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry2''); // Send requests, update the right div fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div1); }); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div2); }); } Closure • An inner function has access to an outer function''s variables • Lexically scoped name binding • This is called a closure • What happens to the outer function variables when the outer function returns? • The activation record sticks around 50 function showPosts() { const div1 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry1''); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div1); }); } Agenda • Synchronous requests • Asynchronous requests • Promise review • Asynchronous requests with ordered page updates • Closures • Idiomatic asynchronous requests with promise chains 51 Simplifications • Hardcoded HTML placeholders for 2 posts 52 <html> <div id="JSEntry1">Loading post 1 ...</div> <div id="JSEntry2">Loading post 2 ...</div> <!-- ... --> </html> Simplifications • Hardcoded JavaScript for 2 posts 53 function showPosts() { const div1 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry1''); const div2 = document.getElementById(''JSEntry2''); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/1/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div1); }); fetchJSON("/api/v1/posts/2/") .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div2); }); } Simplification: fetchJSON() • Non-idiomatic fetch wrapper function • Non-idiomatic because it hides the Promise chain 54 function fetchJSON(url) { // Asynchronous GET request to url, // decode JSON, and return Promise. return fetch(url) .then(response => { return response.json(); }); } Promise chain refactor • Idiomatic Promise chain • Explicit Promise variables 55 const p1 = fetch(url); const p2 = p1.then(response => { return response.json(); }); const p3 = p2.then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); fetch(url) .then(response => { return response.json(); }) .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); Loop • We''ll hardcode the URL list • In a real app, get URL list from REST API 56 function showPosts() { const urls = [ "/api/v1/posts/1/", "/api/v1/posts/2/", ] // ... urls.forEach((url) => { // ... } } Single JavaScript entry point • Avoid hardcoding number of posts in HTML and JavaScript 57 function showPosts() { const urls = [ /*...*/ ]; const entry = document.getElementById(''JSEntry''); urls.forEach((url) => { // ... } } <html> <div id="JSEntry">Loading posts ...</div> <!-- ... --> </html> JavaScript creates placeholders • Create placeholder div nodes in JavaScript loop 58 function showPosts() { const urls = [/* ... */]; const entry = document.getElementById(''JSEntry''); urls.forEach((url) => { const div = document.createElement(''div''); entry.appendChild(div); // ... } } Native fetch API • Use the native JavaScript fetch API 59 function showPosts() { const urls = [/* ... */]; const entry = document.getElementById(''JSEntry''); urls.forEach((url) => { const div = document.createElement(''div''); entry.appendChild(div); fetch(url) .then(response => {');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Asynchronous Programming', 'URL list • In a real app, get URL list from REST API 56 function showPosts() { const urls = [ "/api/v1/posts/1/", "/api/v1/posts/2/", ] // ... urls.forEach((url) => { // ... } } Single JavaScript entry point • Avoid hardcoding number of posts in HTML and JavaScript 57 function showPosts() { const urls = [ /*...*/ ]; const entry = document.getElementById(''JSEntry''); urls.forEach((url) => { // ... } } <html> <div id="JSEntry">Loading posts ...</div> <!-- ... --> </html> JavaScript creates placeholders • Create placeholder div nodes in JavaScript loop 58 function showPosts() { const urls = [/* ... */]; const entry = document.getElementById(''JSEntry''); urls.forEach((url) => { const div = document.createElement(''div''); entry.appendChild(div); // ... } } Native fetch API • Use the native JavaScript fetch API 59 function showPosts() { const urls = [/* ... */]; const entry = document.getElementById(''JSEntry''); urls.forEach((url) => { const div = document.createElement(''div''); entry.appendChild(div); fetch(url) .then(response => { return response.json(); }) .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); } } Chained promises • Chained promises form a sequence of asynchronous events 1. Send GET request 2. Parse JSON 3. Update DOM 60 fetch(url) .then(response => { return response.json(); }) .then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); Chained promises • Fulfilled value of Promise p1 is the input to handler provided to p1.then() • Fulfilled value of Promise p2 is the input to handler provided to p2.then() •Promise p3 resolves immediately because updateDOM doesn''t return a Promise • Like the null pointer at the end of a linked list 61 const p1 = fetch(url); const p2 = p1.then(response => { return response.json(); }); const p3 = p2.then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); Fetch API •fetch() is an API provided by the browser •fetch() returns a Promise • Fulfilled value is a Response • Fulfilled when when HTTP headers arrive • Handler executes with fulfilled value Response as input 62 const p1 = fetch(url); const p2 = p1.then(response => { return response.json(); }); const p3 = p2.then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); Response.json() •json() is a method of Response •json() returns a Promise • Fulfilled value is an object • Fulfilled when HTTP Response body arrives and JSON is parsed • Handler executes with fulfilled value object as input •object is a post from the REST API in this example 63 const p1 = fetch(url); const p2 = p1.then(response => { return response.json(); }); const p3 = p2.then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); Promise chain diagram • Imagine a Promise chain as a linked list of function objects 64 P1 P2 P3 const p1 = fetch(url); const p2 = p1.then(response => { return response.json(); }); const p3 = p2.then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); Promise chain diagram 65 P1 P2 P3 Summary • Synchronous programming: one task at a time • Problem: synchronous requests are slow • Can''t send the second request until the first response has arrived • Solution: asynchronous requests • Send requests right away without waiting for the response • Asynchronous programming: interleave tasks 66 Summary • A Promise');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Asynchronous Programming', 'HTTP Response body arrives and JSON is parsed • Handler executes with fulfilled value object as input •object is a post from the REST API in this example 63 const p1 = fetch(url); const p2 = p1.then(response => { return response.json(); }); const p3 = p2.then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); Promise chain diagram • Imagine a Promise chain as a linked list of function objects 64 P1 P2 P3 const p1 = fetch(url); const p2 = p1.then(response => { return response.json(); }); const p3 = p2.then(post => { updateDOM(post, div); }); Promise chain diagram 65 P1 P2 P3 Summary • Synchronous programming: one task at a time • Problem: synchronous requests are slow • Can''t send the second request until the first response has arrived • Solution: asynchronous requests • Send requests right away without waiting for the response • Asynchronous programming: interleave tasks 66 Summary • A Promise represents a value that will be available in the future • A Promise controls the flow of asynchronous operations • Placeholders create an ordered page from unordered asynchronous responses • Chained promises form a sequence of asynchronous events 67');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'MapReduce', 'MapReduce Some slides by Andrew DeOrio Agenda • Distributed systems introduction • MapReduce motivation • MapReduce programming model • MapReduce execution model • Example • Fault tolerance 2 Distributed systems • Distributed system: Multiple computers cooperating on a task • MapReduce: Distributed system for compute • Run a program that would be too slow on one computer • Today • Google File System: Distributed system for storage • Store more data than fits on one computer • Next time 3 Big program examples • Counting the number of words in 1 TB of text files • Count number of requests to each web page, given a log • Building a search index over large amount of files 4 Not a distributed system • Write a program to count the frequency of words using Python $ cat input.txt Hello World Bye World Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop $ cat input.txt | python3 wc.py Hello 2 World 2 Bye 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 5 Not a distributed system import sys import collections word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: words = line.split() for word in words: word_count[word] += 1 for word, count in word_count.items(): print(word + "\t" + count) 6 defaultdict automatically initializes values to zero MapReduce model • Three phases • Map: turn input into (key, value) pairs • Group: put entries with the same key together • Reduce: combine adjacent (key, value) pairs into a final answer 7 MapReduce picture 8 MapReduce picture 9 Map Map Map Map reduce reduce reduce reduce Group Output Output Output Output 1/#mapers 1/#mapers 1/#mapers 1/#mapers Input MapReduce: Map import sys import collections word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: words = line.split() for word in words: word_count[word] += 1 for word, count in word_count.items(): print(word + "\t" + count) 10 defaultdict automatically initializes values to zero MapReduce: Map • Split input into two files • Run same program on two computers • Problem: Two computers can''t share a data structure 11 word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: words = line.split() for word in wors: word_count[word] += 1 input01.txt Hello World Bye World word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: words = line.split() for word in wors: word_count[word] += 1 input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: words = line.split() for word in wors: word_count[word] += 1 MapReduce: Map • Two computers, two data structures, two outputs • Problem: need to “put together” the output 12 input01.txt Hello World Bye World word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: words = line.split() for word in wors: word_count[word] += 1 output Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 output Hello 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop map map MapReduce: Group • Problem: need to "put together" the output • Insight: output of first program(s) is in the form <key> <value> • Solution: every line with the same key is in the same group • This is called grouping 13 Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 Hello 1 Hadoop');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'MapReduce', '= collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: words = line.split() for word in wors: word_count[word] += 1 input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: words = line.split() for word in wors: word_count[word] += 1 MapReduce: Map • Two computers, two data structures, two outputs • Problem: need to “put together” the output 12 input01.txt Hello World Bye World word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: words = line.split() for word in wors: word_count[word] += 1 output Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 output Hello 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop map map MapReduce: Group • Problem: need to "put together" the output • Insight: output of first program(s) is in the form <key> <value> • Solution: every line with the same key is in the same group • This is called grouping 13 Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 Hello 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 Bye 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 2 Hello 1 Hello 1 World 2 input01.txt Hello World Bye World input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop map map group MapReduce: Reduce • After we have groups, we can "put together the output" • This is called reducing • Runs in parallel, just like map • Write this program 14 Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 Hello 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 Bye 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 2 Hello 1 Hello 1 World 2 input01.txt Hello World Bye World input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Hello 2 World 2 Bye 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 2map map group reduce reduce MapReduce: Reduce • In this example, the second program is very similar to the first • No shared data structures 15 word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: word, count = line.split() word_count[word] += count for word, count in word_count.items(): print(word + "\t" + count) Bye 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 2 Hello 1 Hello 1 World 2 word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: word, count = line.split() word_count[word] += count for word, count in word_count.items(): print(word + "\t" + count) Hello 2 World 2 Bye 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 2 New application: Web access log stats • Count the number of visits to each page in TBs of server logs • Solution is a lot like the previous word count example 16 server1-nginx.log 2021-05-10 09:51 141.213.74.63 index.html 200 2021-05-10 09:52 35.7.44.69 index.html 403 server2-nginx.log 2021-05-10 10:05 141.213.74.63 syllabus.html 200 2021-05-10 11:19 35.7.44.69 p1-insta485-static.html 403 New application and old application • Old application: word count • New application: web page access count • Some code will be different • Read input format • Some code will be identical • The communication and coordination between machines • We''d have to solve all the same parallelization problems again! • Enter MapReduce 17 MapReduce • MapReduce Framework handles • Parallelization over many machines • Segment and distribute input • Fault tolerance • MapReduce provides a clean abstraction for programmers • Programmer writes two programs • Map • Reduce 18 Agenda • Distributed systems introduction • MapReduce motivation');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'MapReduce', 'access log stats • Count the number of visits to each page in TBs of server logs • Solution is a lot like the previous word count example 16 server1-nginx.log 2021-05-10 09:51 141.213.74.63 index.html 200 2021-05-10 09:52 35.7.44.69 index.html 403 server2-nginx.log 2021-05-10 10:05 141.213.74.63 syllabus.html 200 2021-05-10 11:19 35.7.44.69 p1-insta485-static.html 403 New application and old application • Old application: word count • New application: web page access count • Some code will be different • Read input format • Some code will be identical • The communication and coordination between machines • We''d have to solve all the same parallelization problems again! • Enter MapReduce 17 MapReduce • MapReduce Framework handles • Parallelization over many machines • Segment and distribute input • Fault tolerance • MapReduce provides a clean abstraction for programmers • Programmer writes two programs • Map • Reduce 18 Agenda • Distributed systems introduction • MapReduce motivation • MapReduce programming model • MapReduce execution model • Example • Fault tolerance 19 MapReduce programming model • Our examples will use the Hadoop MapReduce streaming interface • Map is a program • Each line of input is from an input file • Each line of output is <key>\t<value> • Group is provided by MapReduce framework • Reduce is a program • Each line of input is <key>\t<value> • Each line of output is up to the programmer 20 A second look at word count • Count the number of occurrences of each word in a collection of documents • We''ll solve the same problem in a slightly different way 21 input01.txt Hello World Bye World input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Bye 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 2 Hello 2 World 2 output Word count map • A mapper doesn''t count words, it just splits them up 22 input01.txt Hello World Bye World map input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Hello 1 World 1 Bye 1 World 1 map Hello 1 Hadoop 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 1 import sys for line in sys.stdin: line = line.strip() words = line.split() for word in words: print(word + "\t" + "1") Intermediate key value pairs • Map output is in the form of key value pairs • Separated by a TAB in the Hadoop streaming interface • What to put here is up to the programmer 23 input01.txt Hello World Bye World map input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Hello 1 World 1 Bye 1 World 1 map Hello 1 Hadoop 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 1 Word count group • Group is provided by the MapReduce framework • Group by key 24 Hello 1 World 1 Bye 1 World 1 Hello 1 Hadoop 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 1 group Bye 1 Hadoop 1 Hadoop 1 World 1 World 1 Hello 1 Hello 1 Goodbye 1 Word count reduce 25 Bye 1 Hadoop 1 Hadoop 1 World 1 World 1 Hello 1 Hello 1 counts = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: line = line.strip() word, count = line.split("\t") counts[word] += int(count) for word, count in counts.items(): print(word');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'MapReduce', '• Map output is in the form of key value pairs • Separated by a TAB in the Hadoop streaming interface • What to put here is up to the programmer 23 input01.txt Hello World Bye World map input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Hello 1 World 1 Bye 1 World 1 map Hello 1 Hadoop 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 1 Word count group • Group is provided by the MapReduce framework • Group by key 24 Hello 1 World 1 Bye 1 World 1 Hello 1 Hadoop 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 1 group Bye 1 Hadoop 1 Hadoop 1 World 1 World 1 Hello 1 Hello 1 Goodbye 1 Word count reduce 25 Bye 1 Hadoop 1 Hadoop 1 World 1 World 1 Hello 1 Hello 1 counts = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: line = line.strip() word, count = line.split("\t") counts[word] += int(count) for word, count in counts.items(): print(word + "\t" + str(count)) reduce reduce reduce reduce reduce Bye 1 Hadoop 2 World 2 Hello 2 Goodbye 1Goodbye 1 Intermediate data size • Isn''t the intermediate data size large? • Option 1: a "local reducer" called a Combiner at each map • Compresses data between map and reduce • Option 2: a different map implementation 26 Word count • Option 2: map sums the words in each doc • This is our previous implementation import collections import sys word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: line = line.strip() words = line.split() for word in words: word_count[word] += 1 for word, count in word_count.items(): print(word + "\t" + str(count)) 27 Word count 28 input01.txt Hello World Bye World map input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 map Hello 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 word_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: line = line.strip() words = line.split() for word in words: word_count[word] += 1 for word, count in word_count.items(): print(word + "\t" + str(count)) Bye 1 Hadoop 2 World 2 Hello 1 Hello 1 Goodbye1 reduce reduce reduce reduce reduce Bye 1 Hadoop 2 World 2 Hello 2 Goodbye1 group same answer Agenda • Distributed systems introduction • MapReduce motivation • MapReduce programming model • MapReduce execution model • Example • Fault tolerance 29 MapReduce execution model • Segment input • Map stage • Group stage • Reduce stage 30 Manager Worker 0 Worker 1 Worker 2 Worker 3 Worker 4 Worker 5 MapReduce machines 31 • Client is the programmer • Manager coordinates workers • Some texts use outdated "master" • Workers do actual computation Manager Worker 0 Worker 1 Worker 2 Worker 3 Worker 4 Worker 5 1. Client submits word count job, indicating map code, reduce code and input files Job processing 32 { "mapper": "wc_map.sh", "reducer": "wc_reduce.sh" } Manager Worker 0 Worker 1 Worker 2 Worker 3 Worker 4 Worker 5 1. Client submits word count job, indicating map code, reduce code and input files 2. Manager breaks input file into k chunks, (in this case 6). Assigns work to workers. Job processing');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'MapReduce', '• MapReduce motivation • MapReduce programming model • MapReduce execution model • Example • Fault tolerance 29 MapReduce execution model • Segment input • Map stage • Group stage • Reduce stage 30 Manager Worker 0 Worker 1 Worker 2 Worker 3 Worker 4 Worker 5 MapReduce machines 31 • Client is the programmer • Manager coordinates workers • Some texts use outdated "master" • Workers do actual computation Manager Worker 0 Worker 1 Worker 2 Worker 3 Worker 4 Worker 5 1. Client submits word count job, indicating map code, reduce code and input files Job processing 32 { "mapper": "wc_map.sh", "reducer": "wc_reduce.sh" } Manager Worker 0 Worker 1 Worker 2 Worker 3 Worker 4 Worker 5 1. Client submits word count job, indicating map code, reduce code and input files 2. Manager breaks input file into k chunks, (in this case 6). Assigns work to workers. Job processing 33 Manager Worker 0 Worker 1 Worker 2 Worker 3 Worker 4 Worker 5 1. Client submits word count job, indicating map code, reduce code and input files 2. Manager breaks input file into k chunks, (in this case 6). Assigns work to workers. 3. After map(), workers exchange map-output to produce groups Job processing 34 Manager Worker 0 Worker 1 Worker 2 Worker 3 Worker 4 Worker 5 1. Client submits word count job, indicating map code, reduce code and input files 2. Manager breaks input file into k chunks, (in this case 6). Assigns work to workers. 3. After map(), workers exchange map-output to produce groups 4. Manager reduce() keyspace into m chunks (in this case 6). Assigns work. Job processing 35 Manager Worker 0 Worker 1 Worker 2 Worker 3 Worker 4 Worker 5 1. Client submits word count job, indicating map code, reduce code and input files 2. Manager breaks input file into k chunks, (in this case 6). Assigns work to workers. 3. After map(), workers exchange map-output to produce groups 4. Manager breaks reduce() keyspace into m chunks (in this case 6). Assigns work. 5. reduce() output may go to shared drive Job processing 36 Same key, same group • MapReduce framework provides grouping functionality • All values for the same key must be in the same group 37 input01.txt Hello World Bye World map input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 map Hello 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 Bye 1 Hadoop 2 World 2 Hello 1 Hello 1 Goodbye1 reduce reduce reduce reduce reduce Bye 1 Hadoop 2 World 2 Hello 2 Goodbye 1 group Same key, same group • Could a group have more than 1 key? Yes. • In the Hadoop streaming interface 38 input01.txt Hello World Bye World map input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 map Hello 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 Bye 1 Goodbye1 Hadoop 2 Hello 1 Hello 1 World 2 reduce reduce group Bye 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 2 Hello 2 World 2 Project 4 • You''ll write');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'MapReduce', '36 Same key, same group • MapReduce framework provides grouping functionality • All values for the same key must be in the same group 37 input01.txt Hello World Bye World map input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 map Hello 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 Bye 1 Hadoop 2 World 2 Hello 1 Hello 1 Goodbye1 reduce reduce reduce reduce reduce Bye 1 Hadoop 2 World 2 Hello 2 Goodbye 1 group Same key, same group • Could a group have more than 1 key? Yes. • In the Hadoop streaming interface 38 input01.txt Hello World Bye World map input02.txt Hello Hadoop Goodbye Hadoop Hello 1 World 2 Bye 1 map Hello 1 Hadoop 2 Goodbye 1 Bye 1 Goodbye1 Hadoop 2 Hello 1 Hello 1 World 2 reduce reduce group Bye 1 Goodbye 1 Hadoop 2 Hello 2 World 2 Project 4 • You''ll write a MapReduce framework in EECS 485 Project 4 • We''ll provide the MapReduce programs 39 Agenda • Distributed systems introduction • MapReduce motivation • MapReduce programming model • MapReduce execution model • Example • Fault tolerance 40 Web access logs • Input: many TBs of server logs • Output: Which IPs got 403 responses? How many? • Input • Output 41 2021-05-10 09:51 141.213.74.63 index.html 200 2021-05-10 09:52 35.7.44.69 index.html 403 2021-05-10 10:05 141.213.74.63 syllabus.html 200 2021-05-10 11:19 35.7.44.69 p1-insta485-static.html 403 2021-10-05 09:33 35.7.44.21 p3-clientside.html 403 35.7.44.21 1 35.7.44.69 2 Web access log code • Map for line in sys.stdin: date, time, ip, path, code = line.strip().split() if code == "403": print(f"{ip}\t1") • Reduce ip_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: ip, count = line.strip().split("\t") ip_count[ip] += int(count) for ip, count in ip_count.items(): print(f"{ip}\t{count}") 42 Web access log diagram 43 2021-05-10 09:51 141.213.74.63 index.html 200 2021-05-10 09:52 35.7.44.69 index.html 403 2021-05-10 10:05 141.213.74.63 syllabus.html 200 2021-05-10 11:19 35.7.44.69 p1-insta485-static.html 403 2021-10-05 09:33 35.7.44.21 p3-clientside.html 403 35.7.44.69 1 map.py for line in sys.stdin: date, time, ip, path, code = line.strip().split() if code == "403": print(f"{ip}\t1") reduce.py ip_count = collections.defaultdict(int) for line in sys.stdin: ip, count = line.strip().split("\t") ip_count[ip] += int(count) for ip, count in ip_count.items(): print(f"{ip}\t{count}") map map reduce reduce group 35.7.44.69 1 35.7.44.21 1 35.7.44.69 1 35.7.44.69 1 35.7.44.21 1 35.7.44.69 2 35.7.44.21 1 Agenda • Distributed systems introduction • MapReduce motivation • MapReduce programming model • MapReduce execution model • Example • Fault tolerance 44 Fault tolerance • How do we know if a machine goes down? • Workers send periodic heartbeat messages to Manager • Manager keeps track of which workers are up 45 Fault tolerance • What happens when a machine dies? • Without MapReduce • Program (or query) is restarted • Not so hot if your job is in hour 23 • With MapReduce • If map worker dies • Just restart that task on a different box • You lose the map work, but no big deal • If reduce worker dies • Restart the reducer, using output from source mappers 46 Fault tolerance nice');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'MapReduce', 'ip, count in ip_count.items(): print(f"{ip}\t{count}") map map reduce reduce group 35.7.44.69 1 35.7.44.21 1 35.7.44.69 1 35.7.44.69 1 35.7.44.21 1 35.7.44.69 2 35.7.44.21 1 Agenda • Distributed systems introduction • MapReduce motivation • MapReduce programming model • MapReduce execution model • Example • Fault tolerance 44 Fault tolerance • How do we know if a machine goes down? • Workers send periodic heartbeat messages to Manager • Manager keeps track of which workers are up 45 Fault tolerance • What happens when a machine dies? • Without MapReduce • Program (or query) is restarted • Not so hot if your job is in hour 23 • With MapReduce • If map worker dies • Just restart that task on a different box • You lose the map work, but no big deal • If reduce worker dies • Restart the reducer, using output from source mappers 46 Fault tolerance nice side effects • What about slow, not dead, machines? • Speculative execution for stragglers • Kill the 2nd-place finisher 47 Further reading • Nice explanation from UC Berkeley • d-data-processing • Some researchers disagree with MapReduce''s popularity: “MapReduce: A Major Step Backwards” • kwards.html • Paper on Google''s MapReduce framework "MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters" by Jeffrey Dean and Sanjay Ghemawat • ve/mapreduce-osdi04.pdf 48');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Google File System', 'Google File System Slides by Raed Almomani Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • Consistency • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 2 Review: Distributed systems • Distributed system: Multiple computers cooperating on a task • MapReduce: Distributed system for compute • Run a program that would be too slow on one computer • Last time • Google File System (GFS): Distributed system for storage • Store more data than fits on one computer • Today 3 Big storage examples • When do we need storage that''s too big for one computer? • Store server logs from thousands ~ millions of servers • Store a copy of the entire web • Needed to build a search engine inverted index ("look up table") • Several PB of HTML files • Archive social media data • For millions ~ billions of users 4 Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • Consistency • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 5 Google File System (GFS) • Google File System: 2003 • Problem: • Store enormous amount of data • Don''t lose data when a server fails • Solution: • Store multiple copies of everything • Keep track of where those copies are 6 GFS design solution • Files stored as series of chunks • Reliability through replication • Each chunk replicated across 3+ servers • Single main server coordinates access, metadata 7 GFS design solution • Files stored as series of chunks • Reliability through replication • Each chunk replicated across 3+ servers • Single main server coordinates access, metadata 8 Chunkservers 9 Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • Consistency • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 10 GFS file read • Client asks Main for filename info • Main responds with chunklist, and location(s) for each chunk • Client fetches each chunk from a chunkserver 11 GFS file read example • One read • One file crawl.txt • 2 chunks • 3 chunk servers • 2 copies of each chunk (replicas) 12 Read 13 File crawl.txt comprises two chunks: c100 and c101 Read 14 c100 copies on chunkserver 1 and 2 c101 copies on chunkserver 2 and 3 Read 15 Client requests file info from Main server for crawl.txt Read 16 Client selects chunk servers and requests c100 and c101 Read 17 Chunk servers respond with copies of c100 and c101 Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • GFS Consistency • GFS Defined • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 18 GFS file write • A write would work just like a read if • Clients take turns; and • There are no errors • Serial, successful writes • Spoiler alert: these assumptions break down 19 One write • One write • All chunkservers');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Google File System', 'crawl.txt • 2 chunks • 3 chunk servers • 2 copies of each chunk (replicas) 12 Read 13 File crawl.txt comprises two chunks: c100 and c101 Read 14 c100 copies on chunkserver 1 and 2 c101 copies on chunkserver 2 and 3 Read 15 Client requests file info from Main server for crawl.txt Read 16 Client selects chunk servers and requests c100 and c101 Read 17 Chunk servers respond with copies of c100 and c101 Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • GFS Consistency • GFS Defined • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 18 GFS file write • A write would work just like a read if • Clients take turns; and • There are no errors • Serial, successful writes • Spoiler alert: these assumptions break down 19 One write • One write • All chunkservers get the same value for the same chunk • We''ll start with a very small example • One file crawl.txt • One chunk • Two chunk servers 20 One write 21 One write 22 One write 23 One write 24 Same final value, consistent Serial writes • Two serial writes • First write • All chunkservers get the same value for the same chunk • Second write • All chunkservers get the same new value for the same chunk 25 Serial writes 26 Serial writes 27 Serial writes 28 Same final value, consistent Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • GFS Consistent • GFS Defined • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 29 Concurrent writes • Two writes from two clients happen at (almost) the same time • Problem: two different values on two different chunkservers for the same chunk • Inconsistent 30 Concurrent writes 31 Concurrent writes 32 Concurrent writes 33 Concurrent writes 34 Concurrent writes 35 Concurrent writes 36 GFS write forwarding • Consistent in GFS: Every chunkserver has the same value for the same chunk • To guarantee consistency, writes need to be coordinated: replicas receive updates in the same order • GFS calls this write forwarding • One chunkserver is designated as primary for each chunk id • Primary forwards writes to replica chunkservers* 37*This is a simplification, see the paper for full details. Write forwarding 38 Write forwarding 39 Write forwarding 40 Write forwarding 41 Write forwarding 42 Write forwarding 43 Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • GFS Consistent • GFS Defined • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 44 Properties: consistent, defined • GFS Consistent: Every chunk server eventually has the same value for the same chunk (updates in same order) • GFS Defined: changes to different chunks of the same file from different writers did not get mixed together • How do undefined values happen? Simultaneous writes to different chunks in the same region of one file 45');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Google File System', 'receive updates in the same order • GFS calls this write forwarding • One chunkserver is designated as primary for each chunk id • Primary forwards writes to replica chunkservers* 37*This is a simplification, see the paper for full details. Write forwarding 38 Write forwarding 39 Write forwarding 40 Write forwarding 41 Write forwarding 42 Write forwarding 43 Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • GFS Consistent • GFS Defined • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 44 Properties: consistent, defined • GFS Consistent: Every chunk server eventually has the same value for the same chunk (updates in same order) • GFS Defined: changes to different chunks of the same file from different writers did not get mixed together • How do undefined values happen? Simultaneous writes to different chunks in the same region of one file 45 Undefined 46 Simplification: one chunk server. Undefined file regions can happen with- or without replicas. Undefined 47 Client 1 and client 2 modify a file across a chunk boundary Undefined 48 Undefined 49 Undefined 50 Sequential consistency • How do we fix consistent but undefined values? • Option 1: Main server coordinates writes • Easy to implement • Slow • Option 2: Distributed write coordination • Really, really hard to implement • Kinda slow • Sequential consistency: Concurrent writes get the same answer as sequential writes, every time 51 Relaxed consistency • How do we fix consistent but undefined values? • Another solution: Don''t bother • Relaxed consistency: Sacrifice some correctness for performance 52 Relaxed consistency and GFS • GFS made a deliberate design decision not to implement sequential consistency • GFS provides relaxed consistency • What should the programmer using GFS do? • Option 1: Application detects and corrects undefined file regions • Option 2: GFS Atomic Record Append 53 Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • Consistency • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 54 Record append • Append: Add to the end of the file 55 Atomic operation • An atomic operation appears to the rest of the system as if it happened instantaneously • Avoid consistency problems 56 GFS atomic record append • Insight: Record append only modifies one chunk • Already solved the problem of consistency for one chunk • Write forwarding • Record append uses a similar strategy as write forwarding • One chunkserver is designated as primary for each chunk id • Primary forwards appends to replica chunkservers* 57*This is a simplification, see the paper for full details. One record append 58 Concurrent record appends 59 Concurrent record appends 60 Concurrent record appends 61 Concurrent record appends 62 Concurrent record appends 63 GFS record append subtleties • What if the new data is bigger than one chunk? • Not allowed • What if the new data would cross a chunk boundary? • Pad the last chunk to "fill it up" •');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Google File System', '55 Atomic operation • An atomic operation appears to the rest of the system as if it happened instantaneously • Avoid consistency problems 56 GFS atomic record append • Insight: Record append only modifies one chunk • Already solved the problem of consistency for one chunk • Write forwarding • Record append uses a similar strategy as write forwarding • One chunkserver is designated as primary for each chunk id • Primary forwards appends to replica chunkservers* 57*This is a simplification, see the paper for full details. One record append 58 Concurrent record appends 59 Concurrent record appends 60 Concurrent record appends 61 Concurrent record appends 62 Concurrent record appends 63 GFS record append subtleties • What if the new data is bigger than one chunk? • Not allowed • What if the new data would cross a chunk boundary? • Pad the last chunk to "fill it up" • Reply to the client to try again 64 Optimize for append • GFS is optimized for fast, atomic append • Unique to GFS • Google applications that use GFS optimized to use append • Example: Web crawling • Download a page and append it to crawl.txt 65 Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • GFS design • Read • Write • Consistency • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 66 Fault tolerance • Things that can go wrong • Chunkserver failure • Master failure 67 Chunkserver failure • Chunkservers report to master server every few seconds • Heartbeat message • If the master loses the heartbeat, marks the server as down • Master asks chunkservers to reduplicate data • Typically 3 copies of every chunk 68 Master failure • Master maintains critical data structures • filename -> chunkid map • chunkid -> location map • Master writes a log to disk when data structures change • Shadow Main consumes log and keeps copies of these data structures up-to-date • If Main goes down, Shadow Main provides read-only access until Main restarts 69 Agenda • Review: Distributed systems introduction • Google File System motivation • Read • Consistency • Write • Consistency • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 70 GFS strengths • Store lots of data • Fault tolerant • Too big to back up! • High throughput • Can read lots of data from many chunkservers at same time 71 GFS weaknesses • Bad for small files • Chunks are ~64MB • Master node single point of failure • High latency • Talk to two servers to fetch any data, might need multiple chunks 72 Further reading • The Google File System by Sanjay Ghemawat, Howard Gobioff, and Shun-Tak Leung • ve/gfs-sosp2003.pdf • Storage Architecture and Challenges • 73');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Google File System', '• Consistency • Write • Consistency • Append • Fault tolerance • Summary 70 GFS strengths • Store lots of data • Fault tolerant • Too big to back up! • High throughput • Can read lots of data from many chunkservers at same time 71 GFS weaknesses • Bad for small files • Chunks are ~64MB • Master node single point of failure • High latency • Talk to two servers to fetch any data, might need multiple chunks 72 Further reading • The Google File System by Sanjay Ghemawat, Howard Gobioff, and Shun-Tak Leung • ve/gfs-sosp2003.pdf • Storage Architecture and Challenges • 73');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'OS and Parallelism', 'OS and Parallelism Slides by Raed Almomani and Andrew DeOrio Agenda • Motivation • Processes • Threads • Synchronization • Atomic operations • Summary 2 Running Multiple Tasks • How to run multiple things at the same time? • A web server may need to handle multiple user requests at the same time (e.g., many users loading a webpage simultaneously). • Threads and processes for parallelization • Today • Network for communication • Next Time 3 Not parallel: Sequential program • The Flask development server is a sequential program • Handles one request at a time • First, we''ll look at a one request from one client 4 @app.route("/") def index(): context = # slow database read return flask.render_template("index.html", **context) $ curl localhost:5000 <html><body>Hello World!</body></html> One request 5 @app.route("/") def index(): context = # slow database read return flask.render_template( "index.html", **context ) Note: Server must finish the database read before responding. Problem: Server is idle while waiting for the database Time Client Server Serial requests • Two serial requests from two clients • Request from client 1 • Start client 1 database read • Wait for database • Render client 1 template • Response to client 1 • Request from client 2 • Start client 2 database read • Wait for database • Render client 2 template • Response to client 2 6 Serial requests 7 Time Client1 Server Client2 Concurrent requests, sequential program • Two concurrent requests from two clients handled by a sequential program • Request from client 1 • Request from client 2 • Start client 1 database read • Wait for database • Render client 1 template • Response to client 1 • Start client 2 database read • Wait for database • Render client 2 template • Response to client 2 8 Concurrent requests, sequential program 9 Time Client1 Server Client2 Concurrent requests, sequential program 10 Client1 Server Client2 Time Concurrent requests, sequential program 11 Client1 Server Client2 Time Problem with sequential programs • Problem with sequential programs when: • Multiple things happening at once • Two concurrent requests in this example • Slow resource • Database read in this example • Our program spends a lot of time waiting • Solution: Work on both requests at the same time • Later today, we''ll solve this problem with threads, but first we need to learn about processes 12 Agenda • Motivation • Processes • Threads • Synchronization • Atomic operations • Summary 13 Processes • A process is a running program 14 The process abstraction • The Process is an OS abstraction for execution • Also sometimes called a job or a task • A process is a program in execution • Programs are static entities with potential for execution • Process consists of: • A unique process ID: PID • An address space: Memory • One or more threads: Sequences of computation • Some other resources: File handles, open sockets, etc. 15 Process address space • Each process gets its own address space •');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'OS and Parallelism', '• Database read in this example • Our program spends a lot of time waiting • Solution: Work on both requests at the same time • Later today, we''ll solve this problem with threads, but first we need to learn about processes 12 Agenda • Motivation • Processes • Threads • Synchronization • Atomic operations • Summary 13 Processes • A process is a running program 14 The process abstraction • The Process is an OS abstraction for execution • Also sometimes called a job or a task • A process is a program in execution • Programs are static entities with potential for execution • Process consists of: • A unique process ID: PID • An address space: Memory • One or more threads: Sequences of computation • Some other resources: File handles, open sockets, etc. 15 Process address space • Each process gets its own address space • Process can only write to its own address space 16 Stack Static AKA Globals Heap Code AKA Text Operating system process scheduling • Each CPU core can run one process at a time • Every ~1-10ms, the OS can switch 17 Process’s Perspective CPU Core’s Perspective Process abstraction • On a single-core machine • Processes take turns • On a multi-core machine • Processes run in parallel • Processes still take turns because there are usually many more processes than cores • Recall that the Process is an OS abstraction for execution • A process is an illusion of parallelism provided by OS 18 When are processes useful? • Processes are most useful when: • Multiple things happening at once • Different programs running on the same machine • Same program running on different machines 19 When are processes NOT useful? • Back to our problem with sequential programs • Two concurrent requests with slow database operations • Two processes can handle two requests concurrently • Problem: Higher memory overhead • Copy of entire address space • They don''t really need separate code, etc. 20 Stack Static Heap Code Stack Static Heap Code Agenda • Motivation • Processes • Threads • Synchronization • Atomic operations • Summary 21 Threads • Threads are multiple functions in one process running simultaneously • Separate stacks • Share heap, static data, code • Lower overhead than processes 22 Thread 1 Stack Static Data Heap Thread 2 Stack Code Thread example 23 from threading import Thread def hello(): print("hello world") t = Thread(target=hello) t.start() t.join() Main Thread t time Thread example 24 from threading import Thread def hello(): print("hello world") t = Thread(target=hello) t.start() t.join() • t.join() waits for hello() to return • t.join() does not interrupt hello() Main Thread t time Operating system thread scheduling • Each CPU core can run one thread at a time • Every ~1-10ms, the OS can switch 25 Thread’s Perspective CPU Core’s Perspective Thread abstraction • On a single-core machine • Threads take turns • On a multi-core machine • Threads run in parallel • Threads still take');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'OS and Parallelism', '• Synchronization • Atomic operations • Summary 21 Threads • Threads are multiple functions in one process running simultaneously • Separate stacks • Share heap, static data, code • Lower overhead than processes 22 Thread 1 Stack Static Data Heap Thread 2 Stack Code Thread example 23 from threading import Thread def hello(): print("hello world") t = Thread(target=hello) t.start() t.join() Main Thread t time Thread example 24 from threading import Thread def hello(): print("hello world") t = Thread(target=hello) t.start() t.join() • t.join() waits for hello() to return • t.join() does not interrupt hello() Main Thread t time Operating system thread scheduling • Each CPU core can run one thread at a time • Every ~1-10ms, the OS can switch 25 Thread’s Perspective CPU Core’s Perspective Thread abstraction • On a single-core machine • Threads take turns • On a multi-core machine • Threads run in parallel • Threads still take turns because there are usually more threads than cores • Threads have a lot in common with Processes • Both provide an illusion of parallelism • Both can provide true parallelism on the right hardware • Threads share memory • Less overhead • Possible security risk, depending on the application 26 Recall: Concurrent requests with 1 thread 27 Concurrent requests with multiple threads • Two concurrent requests from two clients to server with two threads • Request from client 1, assign to thread 1 • Request from client 2, assign to thread 2 • Start client 1 database read • Start client 2 database read • Wait for client 1 database read • Wait for client 2 database read • Render client 1 template • Response to client 1 • Render client 2 template • Response to client 2 28 Note: Other interleavings are possible Concurrent requests with multiple threads 29 Client1 Client2 Server t1 Server t2 Server Main Thread Concurrent requests with multiple threads 30 Client1 Client2 Server t1 Server t2 Server Main Thread Concurrent requests with multiple threads 31 Client1 Client2 Server t1 Server t2 Server Main Thread Concurrent requests with multiple threads 32 Client1 Client2 Server t1 Server t2 Server Main Thread *New thread for each request is optional design decision. When are threads useful? • Multiple things happening at once • Within one program • May need to share data in memory • Usually some slow resource • Network response • Disk I/O • Reading a sensor • Human input 33 Benefits of threads • Simpler programming model • The illusion of a dedicated CPU per thread • State for each thread (local variables) • OS takes care of CPU sharing • Other threads can progress while one thread waits for I/O 34 Processes vs. threads • Processes have separate address spaces • Useful when there is not complete trust • Limit the damage caused by buggy code • Required to run different programs on the same computer • Required to run the same program on different computers • Threads share an address space • Lower');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'OS and Parallelism', 'Server t2 Server Main Thread *New thread for each request is optional design decision. When are threads useful? • Multiple things happening at once • Within one program • May need to share data in memory • Usually some slow resource • Network response • Disk I/O • Reading a sensor • Human input 33 Benefits of threads • Simpler programming model • The illusion of a dedicated CPU per thread • State for each thread (local variables) • OS takes care of CPU sharing • Other threads can progress while one thread waits for I/O 34 Processes vs. threads • Processes have separate address spaces • Useful when there is not complete trust • Limit the damage caused by buggy code • Required to run different programs on the same computer • Required to run the same program on different computers • Threads share an address space • Lower memory overhead • Faster context switches (threads taking turns) • Can share data • Both implement concurrency • Both are illusions of parallelism • Both can provide true parallelism with the right hardware 35 Agenda • Motivation • Processes • Threads • Synchronization • Atomic operations • Summary 36 Cooperating threads • What happens when threads cooperate? • What are these threads sharing? The output stream. • What is the output of this code? 37 def hello(): print("hello") print("world") t1 = Thread(target=hello) t2 = Thread(target=hello) t1.start() t2.start() t1.join() t2.join() Cooperating threads 38 def hello(): print("hello") print("world") t1 = Thread(target=hello) t2 = Thread(target=hello) t1.start() t2.start() t1.join() t2.join() Cooperating threads 39 def hello(): print("hello") print("world") t1 = Thread(target=hello) t2 = Thread(target=hello) t1.start() t2.start() t1.join() t2.join() Multiple ways to interleave the operations from t1 and t2 Many possible outputs • Possible outputs • Impossible outputs 40 def hello(): print("hello") print("world") t1 = Thread(target=hello) t2 = Thread(target=hello) t1.start() t2.start() hello world hello world hello hello world world world hello world hello world world hello hello Unpredictable order • When threads share data, the output can be unpredictable • OS decides when threads take turns • Different timing -> different thread order - > different output 41 Shared data • Insight: Shared data • The output buffer in this example • Ordering within a thread is sequential • Many ways to merge multiple threads together into global order • Problem: Some global orderings may produce incorrect results • Solution: Locks 42 def hello(): print("hello") print("world") t1 = Thread(target=hello) t2 = Thread(target=hello) t1.start() t2.start() t1.join() t2.join() Agenda • Motivation • Processes • Threads • Synchronization • Atomic operations • Summary 43 Atomic operations • An atomic operation appears to the other threads as if it happened instantaneously • No code from other threads can occur in between • In our previous example, print() behaved atomically* 44 *The print() output was line buffered, which means different lines of output cannot be interleaved (more detail). Locks • How can we make sure "hello world" is printed by each thread? • Limit when threads can take turns • A');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'OS and Parallelism', 'output 41 Shared data • Insight: Shared data • The output buffer in this example • Ordering within a thread is sequential • Many ways to merge multiple threads together into global order • Problem: Some global orderings may produce incorrect results • Solution: Locks 42 def hello(): print("hello") print("world") t1 = Thread(target=hello) t2 = Thread(target=hello) t1.start() t2.start() t1.join() t2.join() Agenda • Motivation • Processes • Threads • Synchronization • Atomic operations • Summary 43 Atomic operations • An atomic operation appears to the other threads as if it happened instantaneously • No code from other threads can occur in between • In our previous example, print() behaved atomically* 44 *The print() output was line buffered, which means different lines of output cannot be interleaved (more detail). Locks • How can we make sure "hello world" is printed by each thread? • Limit when threads can take turns • A Lock is for mutual exclusion • Also called a mutex • A Lock lets the programmer limit when threads take turns 45 Locks • How can we make sure "hello world" is printed by each thread? • Limit when threads can take turns 46 import time import random from threading import current_thread, Thread, Lock def hello(lock): name = current_thread().name lock.acquire() print("{name} hello") print("{name} world") lock.release() lock = Lock() t1 = Thread(target=hello, args=(lock,)) t2 = Thread(target=hello, args=(lock,)) t1.start() t2.start() t1.join() t2.join() Locks 47 Agenda • Motivation • Processes • Threads • Synchronization • Atomic operations • Summary 48 Next time • How to run multiple things at the same time? • Threads and processes for parallelization • Today • Networking for communication • Next time 49 Summary • Parallelization is important for implementing distributed systems • Processes and threads are used to write parallel programs • With parallel programs, need to think about synchronization of data • To synchronize data, we use atomic operations 50');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Networking', 'Networking Slides by Raed Almomani and Andrew DeOrio Agenda • Motivation • IP: Internet Protocol • TCP: Transmission Control Protocol • Flow control and congestion control • UDP: User Datagram Protocol • Sockets • Summary 2 Distributed systems • Distributed system: Multiple computers cooperating on a task • MapReduce: Distributed system for compute • Run a program that would be too slow on one computer • Google File System: Distributed system for storage • Store more data than fits on one computer 3 Distributed system implementation • How are distributed systems implemented? • Threads and processes for parallelization • Last time • Networking for communication • Today 4 Agenda • Motivation • IP: Internet Protocol • TCP: Transmission Control Protocol • Flow control and congestion control • UDP: User Datagram Protocol • Sockets • Summary 5 IP: Internet Protocol IP • How to get a message from one computer to another computer? • Solution: Internet Protocol (IP) • Examples of messages • MapReduce Manager server assigns task to Worker • Google File System chunkserver tells Main server "I''m alive" • GET request from a client web browser to an HTTP server 6 Example message from client to server 7 IP Address • There are lots of computers connected to the internet • Problem: How to tell them apart? • Solution: IP Address • Every computer on the Internet has an address • Google 172.217.5.14 • Amazon 205.251.242.103 • My laptop 35.7.33.89 • Newer version: longer addresses • IPv4: 32 bits is 4 billion computers • IPv6: 128 bits is way more 8 What is my IP address? • Your internet service provider gives you an IP address when you connect to the wifi (or wired) network • Popular search engines provide your externally visible IP address • If you''re on a home network, this is likely the IP address of your router 9 What is Amazon''s IP address? • How do you turn aws.amazon.com into an IP address? • Domain Name Service (DNS) • Covered later this semester 10 Routers • How do we connect all the computers on the internet? • Routers • A router forwards data from one network to the next • Usually a purpose-built Linux computer with multiple network connections 11 Routers 12 Routing • A router is connected many other routers • Problem: Where to send new data? • Solution: One step closer to the destination • Each router has a routing table • Map groups of IP addresses to destination • Destination could be another router 13 Packets • Message broken down into packets by sender • ~1,000 – 1,500 B each 14 Why packets? • Multiple programs on one computer can share one connection 15 Why packets? • Multiple computers can share one connection 16 IP summary • How to get a message from one computer to another computer? • Internet Protocol (IP) • How to tell computers connected to the internet apart? • IP Address • How are computers connected? • Routers');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Networking', 'internet? • Routers • A router forwards data from one network to the next • Usually a purpose-built Linux computer with multiple network connections 11 Routers 12 Routing • A router is connected many other routers • Problem: Where to send new data? • Solution: One step closer to the destination • Each router has a routing table • Map groups of IP addresses to destination • Destination could be another router 13 Packets • Message broken down into packets by sender • ~1,000 – 1,500 B each 14 Why packets? • Multiple programs on one computer can share one connection 15 Why packets? • Multiple computers can share one connection 16 IP summary • How to get a message from one computer to another computer? • Internet Protocol (IP) • How to tell computers connected to the internet apart? • IP Address • How are computers connected? • Routers • How are long messages broken up? How do multiple computers share one network link? • Packets 17 Agenda • Motivation • IP: Internet Protocol • TCP: Transmission Control Protocol • Flow control and congestion control • UDP: User Datagram Protocol • Sockets • Summary 18 IP is not reliable • Problems with IP • Packets may arrive out of order • Packets may disappear • Packets may be repeated • TCP: Abstraction to make it look like these problems don''t exist • TCP/IP: TCP along with IP 19 Packets may arrive out of order • Problem: Packets may arrive out of order • Solution: 1. Sender assigns a sequence number to each packet 2. Receiver reassembles packets in order by sequence number 3. Receiver gives data to application (e.g. browser) in order 20 Out of order packets example 21 Out of order packets example 22 Out of order packets example 23 Out of order packets example 24 Application receives packets in order 25 Application receives packets in order 26 Application receives packets in order 27 Application receives packets in order 28 Application receives packets in order 29 Application receives packets in order 30 Packets may disappear • Problem: Packets may disappear • Solution: Sender stores data in buffer until receiver ACK 1. Sender stores a copy of each packet 2. Sender sets a timer for each packet when it goes out 3. Receiver sends an acknowledgement (ACK) for each packet 4. Sender resends the packet if the timer expires 1. Delete the packet upon receiving ACK 31 Packet acknowledgement example 32 Packet acknowledgement example 33 Packet acknowledgement example 34 Disappearing packet • What happens if the packet disappears? • Sender resends the packet if the timer expires 35 Disappearing packet example 36 Disappearing packet example 37 Disappearing packet example 38 Disappearing packet example 39 Packets may be repeated • Problem: Packets may be repeated • Solution: Receiver ignores sequence numbers it has seen before • Why would a packet be repeated? • ACK is dropped • Packet is slow • Let''s look at an example of a slow packet');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Networking', 'may disappear • Solution: Sender stores data in buffer until receiver ACK 1. Sender stores a copy of each packet 2. Sender sets a timer for each packet when it goes out 3. Receiver sends an acknowledgement (ACK) for each packet 4. Sender resends the packet if the timer expires 1. Delete the packet upon receiving ACK 31 Packet acknowledgement example 32 Packet acknowledgement example 33 Packet acknowledgement example 34 Disappearing packet • What happens if the packet disappears? • Sender resends the packet if the timer expires 35 Disappearing packet example 36 Disappearing packet example 37 Disappearing packet example 38 Disappearing packet example 39 Packets may be repeated • Problem: Packets may be repeated • Solution: Receiver ignores sequence numbers it has seen before • Why would a packet be repeated? • ACK is dropped • Packet is slow • Let''s look at an example of a slow packet 40 Repeated packet example 41 Repeated packet example 42 Repeated packet example 43 Repeated packet example 44 TCP summary • Problem: IP is not reliable • Solution: TCP along with IP (TCP/IP) • Problem: Packets may arrive out of order • Solution: TCP buffers reassemble packets using sequence numbers • Problem: Packets may disappear • Solution: TCP resends lost packets • Problem: Packets may be repeated • Solution: TCP receiver ignores duplicate sequence numbers 45 Agenda • Motivation • IP: Internet Protocol • TCP: Transmission Control Protocol • Flow control and congestion control • UDP: User Datagram Protocol • Sockets • Summary 46 Fast sender, slow receiver • Problem: Fast sender overloads a slow receiver • For example, sender is an AWS datacenter server and receiver is a smart watch 47 Flow control • Problem: Fast sender overloads a slow receiver • Solution: Flow control is about the receiver • Receiver tells the sender how many empty buffer spots it has • Sender can only send that much data on the network at one time • This is called the sliding window 48 Flow control example 49 Flow control example 50 Flow control example 51 Exercise • If the sender has lots of data to send, which of these situations will occur when the sliding window is working properly? A. The receiver''s queue will usually be almost full B. The receiver''s queue will usually be about half full C. The receiver''s queue will usually be almost empty 52 Exercise • If the sender has lots of data to send, which of these situations will occur when the sliding window is working properly? A. The receiver''s queue will usually be almost full B. The receiver''s queue will usually be about half full C. The receiver''s queue will usually be almost empty • Goal is to maximize use of resources (receiver buffer) without overloading it 53 Congestion control • Problem: Many senders overload a network router • Routers have buffers • Router drop packets when its buffer is full 54 Congestion control example 55 TCP congestion window • Sender maintains a congestion');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Networking', 'has lots of data to send, which of these situations will occur when the sliding window is working properly? A. The receiver''s queue will usually be almost full B. The receiver''s queue will usually be about half full C. The receiver''s queue will usually be almost empty 52 Exercise • If the sender has lots of data to send, which of these situations will occur when the sliding window is working properly? A. The receiver''s queue will usually be almost full B. The receiver''s queue will usually be about half full C. The receiver''s queue will usually be almost empty • Goal is to maximize use of resources (receiver buffer) without overloading it 53 Congestion control • Problem: Many senders overload a network router • Routers have buffers • Router drop packets when its buffer is full 54 Congestion control example 55 TCP congestion window • Sender maintains a congestion window • Maximum packets awaiting acknowledgments • Sometimes called CWND • Packet loss -> network likely congested -> decrease CWND • Successful ACKs –> network likely healthy -> increase CWND 56 Flow control and congestion control • Flow control (AKA sliding window) • Keep a fast sender from overloading a slow receiver • Congestion control • Keep a set of senders from overloading the network • We need both! • TCP flow control: receiver window (RWND) • TCP congestion control: congestion window (CWND) • TCP window: min(congestion_window, receiver_window) 57 TCP summary • Problem: Packets may arrive out of order • Solution: TCP buffers reassemble packets using sequence numbers • Problem: Packets may disappear • Solution: TCP resends lost packets • Problem: Packets may be repeated • Solution: TCP receiver ignores duplicate sequence numbers 58 TCP flow and congestion control summary • Problem: Fast sender overloads a slow receiver • Solution: Flow control AKA sliding window • Sender limits number of packets • Problem: Many senders overload a network router • Solution: Congestion control • Sender limits number of packets 59 Agenda • Motivation • IP: Internet Protocol • TCP: Transmission Control Protocol • Flow control and congestion control • UDP: User Datagram Protocol • Sockets • Summary 60 TCP isn''t good for real-time applications • TCP guarantees in-order delivery. • If a packet is missing, later packets cannot be delivered • What will happen in a video chat app that uses TCP if packets 0 and 2-100 have been received but packet 1 has not? • Application must wait for packet 1. 61 Receiver buffer What happens in a video call using TCP? • What will happen in a video chat app that uses TCP if packets 0 and 2-100 have been received but packet 1 has not? • TCP waits for packet 1 • Packets 2-100 cannot be delivered and application waits for packets. • Video freezes/Lag 62 Receiver buffer Sometimes “Never” Is Better than “Late” • TCP is "Better late than never" • Real time application: “Better never that late” • Example: • Voice chat ("Voice over IP"');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Networking', 'User Datagram Protocol • Sockets • Summary 60 TCP isn''t good for real-time applications • TCP guarantees in-order delivery. • If a packet is missing, later packets cannot be delivered • What will happen in a video chat app that uses TCP if packets 0 and 2-100 have been received but packet 1 has not? • Application must wait for packet 1. 61 Receiver buffer What happens in a video call using TCP? • What will happen in a video chat app that uses TCP if packets 0 and 2-100 have been received but packet 1 has not? • TCP waits for packet 1 • Packets 2-100 cannot be delivered and application waits for packets. • Video freezes/Lag 62 Receiver buffer Sometimes “Never” Is Better than “Late” • TCP is "Better late than never" • Real time application: “Better never that late” • Example: • Voice chat ("Voice over IP" AKA VOIP) • Video chat • Video games, e.g., the locations of other players • Heartbeat messages from Workers to Main in GFS or MapReduce • Anything real-time 63 UDP: No Waiting • UDP does not guarantee • Packet order • Packet delivery • Packet retransmission • No delay caused by missing packets, and let application decide what to do. • Better for real-time applications like video chat. 64 Agenda • Motivation • IP: Internet Protocol • TCP: Transmission Control Protocol • Flow control and congestion control • UDP: User Datagram Protocol • Sockets • Summary 65 Recall: TCP buffer 66 Socket API • How does an application use TCP or UDP? • Socket API: OS functions that let applications use the network • Applications use sockets to: • Send data • Receive data • The operating system handles: • TCP/UDP protocols • Buffers for packets • Flow control • Application → Socket → OS → Network 67 Two programs share the network • Problem: Two programs use the network at the same time • Solution: Two sockets, each with its own buffer 68 Ports • Problem: How to tell two sockets apart? • Solution: Each socket gets a unique port number 69 Example ports • One server (host) runs two programs (processes) that use the network • Nginx listens for incoming HTTP requests on port 80 • SSHD listens for incoming SSH connections on port 22 • Both processes run on the same host using different ports 70 Agenda • Motivation • IP: Internet Protocol • TCP: Transmission Control Protocol • Flow control and congestion control • UDP: User Datagram Protocol • Sockets • Summary 71 Networking summary • Networking is how computers communicate • In a distributed system, the network connects cooperating machines • MapReduce Manager assigns task to Worker • Google File System chunkserver tells Main server "I''m alive" 72 IP summary • How to get a message from one computer to another computer? • Internet Protocol (IP) • How to tell computers connected to the internet apart? • IP Address • How are computers connected? •');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Networking', 'port number 69 Example ports • One server (host) runs two programs (processes) that use the network • Nginx listens for incoming HTTP requests on port 80 • SSHD listens for incoming SSH connections on port 22 • Both processes run on the same host using different ports 70 Agenda • Motivation • IP: Internet Protocol • TCP: Transmission Control Protocol • Flow control and congestion control • UDP: User Datagram Protocol • Sockets • Summary 71 Networking summary • Networking is how computers communicate • In a distributed system, the network connects cooperating machines • MapReduce Manager assigns task to Worker • Google File System chunkserver tells Main server "I''m alive" 72 IP summary • How to get a message from one computer to another computer? • Internet Protocol (IP) • How to tell computers connected to the internet apart? • IP Address • How are computers connected? • Routers • How are long messages broken up? How do multiple computers share one network link? • Packets 73 TCP summary • Problem: Packets may arrive out of order • Solution: TCP buffers reassemble packets using sequence numbers • Problem: Packets may disappear • Solution: TCP resends lost packets • Problem: Packets may be repeated • Solution: TCP receiver ignores duplicate sequence numbers 74 TCP flow and congestion control summary • Problem: Fast sender overloads a slow receiver • Solution: Flow control AKA sliding window • Sender limits number of packets • Problem: Many senders overload a network router • Solution: Congestion control • Sender limits number of packets 75 UDP summary • Problem: Sometimes never is better than late • Solution: UDP "User Datagram Protocol" • UDP lets the application decide what to do about • Packets out of order • Dropped packets • Better for real-time applications like video chat 76 Sockets and ports summary • Socket API provided by the operating system • Functions that let applications use the network • A port is a number that identifies a socket on one host • Two applications on one host can both use the network on different ports 77');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Text Analysis for Web Search', 'Text Analysis for Web Search Slides by Raed Almomani, Andrew DeOrio, Raghavan et al. Agenda • Web search introduction • Boolean retrieval • Vector space model • tf-idf 2 Web search • Web search: find web pages relevant to user query • Example of Information Retrieval (IR) 3 Anatomy of a web search • Query: user input • Hits: returned web pages • Rank: order of results by relevance 4 Anatomy of a web search • Document: one web page • Collection: all documents • Term: one word in a document • Or query 4 How search works • Ahead of time (offline) • Download every web page • Build an index • Query time • Read index • Rank results • Problem: How do we rank results? 6 Ranking results • Ranking is important • About 33% of users click the first result • Text analysis: Rank using words in document • Today • Link analysis: Rank using links between documents • Next time 4 Agenda • What is search? • Boolean retrieval • Vector space model • tf-idf 8 Boolean retrieval • For each document, a query returns one of two outcomes • TRUE (document matches) • FALSE (document does not match) 9 Boolean retrieval Kangaroo live in Australia and jump. Cows live all over the world. Unlike kangaroo, they cannot jump. Aluminum foil is shiny. 2 Index for Boolean retrieval • Inverted index: map words to documents for efficient search. Doc0 Kangaroo can jump. Doc 1 Cows can not jump. 4 Term Doc ID kangaroo 0 can 0, 1 jump 0, 1 cow 1 not 1 Boolean search using inverted index Term Doc ID kangaroo 0 can 0, 1 jump 0, 1 cow 1 not 1 5 Ranking search results • Boolean queries only include or exclude documens from results • When many documents match, we need to sort (rank) them 16 Agenda • What is search? • Boolean retrieval • Vector space model • tf-idf 17 Documents as vectors • A document is a vector • Each dimension represents a word • # of dimensions: # of unique words in all documents 4 Boolean index to vectors Term Documents kangaroo 0 can 0, 1 jump 0, 1 cow 1 not 1 2 Documents in n-D space • Documents that are "close together" in space are close in meaning. 22 Documents in 3D space • Term weights indicate length of document vector along a dimension 23 Vector space query model 1. Treat a query as a short document 2. Sort documents by increasing distance (decreasing similarity) to the query document 3. Easy to compute, both query and doc are vectors 24 Vector magnitude • With Boolean search, the values in a vector (one for each term) are 0 or 1 • Next, we''ll consider values [0, 1] 25 Q: Vector space dimensionality • How many dimensions? • Are vectors sparse or dense? Why? 26 A: Vector space dimensionality • How many dimensions? • Dimension for every possible');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Text Analysis for Web Search', 'of unique words in all documents 4 Boolean index to vectors Term Documents kangaroo 0 can 0, 1 jump 0, 1 cow 1 not 1 2 Documents in n-D space • Documents that are "close together" in space are close in meaning. 22 Documents in 3D space • Term weights indicate length of document vector along a dimension 23 Vector space query model 1. Treat a query as a short document 2. Sort documents by increasing distance (decreasing similarity) to the query document 3. Easy to compute, both query and doc are vectors 24 Vector magnitude • With Boolean search, the values in a vector (one for each term) are 0 or 1 • Next, we''ll consider values [0, 1] 25 Q: Vector space dimensionality • How many dimensions? • Are vectors sparse or dense? Why? 26 A: Vector space dimensionality • How many dimensions? • Dimension for every possible term (word) • Are vectors sparse or dense? Why? • Sparse. Most documents do not use most words. 27 Agenda • What is search? • Boolean retrieval • Vector space model • tf-idf 28 Term frequency (tf) • Which doc is a better match for the query "kangaroo”? • One with a single mention of "kangaroo", or that mentions it 10 times? 29 Term frequency (tf) • Which doc is a better match for the query "kangaroo", one with a single mention of "kangaroo", or a doc that mentions it 10 times? • The doc that mentions it 10 times • Term frequency (TF): the number of times the word appears in the document • Higher is better 30 Term frequency (tf) Kangaroo can jump. Kangaroo live in Australia. Australia is in the southern hemisphere. One of the longest flights is from London to Sydney, Australia. Document frequency (DF) • Document Frequency (DF) is the count of documents containing a specific term. • In a collection of 100 documents, if 5 documents contain the term ‘AI’, then DF(AI) = 5 33 Document frequency (DF) • Common terms with high DF (e.g., "data") appear in many documents and provide less unique value. • Rare terms with low DF (e.g., "neural network") are more informative and distinctive. • Lower is better 34 Inverse document frequency (idf) • Inverse Document Frequency (IDF) provides high values for rare words, low values for common words • IDF(t) = N / DF(t) • N = total # docs in collection C • DT(t) = # docs in C that contain t Example • If DF = 5 in a collection of 100 documents, IDF = 100/5 = 20. 35 Document frequency (df) Kangaroo can jump. Kangaroo live in Australia. Australia is in the southern hemisphere. One of the longest flights is from London to Sydney, Australia. Log inverse document frequency • Query “AI book" • What if “AI" appears 10 out of 10 million documents and "book" appears in 1 million out of 10 million? • Is the term "book" 100,000 times less informative than “AI"?');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Text Analysis for Web Search', 'value. • Rare terms with low DF (e.g., "neural network") are more informative and distinctive. • Lower is better 34 Inverse document frequency (idf) • Inverse Document Frequency (IDF) provides high values for rare words, low values for common words • IDF(t) = N / DF(t) • N = total # docs in collection C • DT(t) = # docs in C that contain t Example • If DF = 5 in a collection of 100 documents, IDF = 100/5 = 20. 35 Document frequency (df) Kangaroo can jump. Kangaroo live in Australia. Australia is in the southern hemisphere. One of the longest flights is from London to Sydney, Australia. Log inverse document frequency • Query “AI book" • What if “AI" appears 10 out of 10 million documents and "book" appears in 1 million out of 10 million? • Is the term "book" 100,000 times less informative than “AI"? 38 Log inverse document frequency • Query “AI book" • What if “AI" appears 10 out of 10 million documents and "book" appears in 1 million out of 10 million? • Is the term "book" 100,000 times less informative than “AI"? • Probably not. • Solution: log(N / nk) • Sublinear function decreases the weight of “AI" compared to "book" • Still monotonically increasing, so order is preserved 39 TF x IDF • Term frequency high for common word in one document • Inverse Document Frequency high for rare word in collection • Term-Frequency x Inverse-Document-Frequency high for common word in one document that is rare in the collection • Wik = tfik * log(N / df(t)) • Tk = term k in document Di • tfik = freq of term Tk in doc Di • N = total # docs in collection C • DT(t) = # docs in C that contain t 40 TF-IDF normalization • Imagine two documents about kangaroos • Document 1 mentions "kangaroo" 100 times. Total length 1000 words. • Document 2 mentions "kangaroo" 200 times. Total length 10,000 words. • Which document should have the greater weight? • Avoid giving longer doc higher weight just because they are long • Need to normalize 41 TF-IDF normalization • Normalize term weights • Normalize to vector length • Some references use non-normalized tf-idf • wik = tfiklog(N/nk) wik = tf ik log(N /nk ) (tf ik )2 k=1 t å [log(N /nk )]2 42 Vector space similarity • Boolean vectors contain only 0 or 1 depending on whether they contain a word doc1 = [1, 1, 1, 0, 0] • Now, use entire range [0, 1] to give more information doc1 = [0.2, 0.1, 0.5, 0, 0] 2 TF-IDF and the vector space • Vector lengths are now TF-IDF values • Vectors that are "close" are still similar in meaning 44 Vector space similarity • Vector space similarity is also called the cosine, or normalized inner product • Cosine similarity measures the angle between two vectors. If the angle is small → documents are similar. 45');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Text Analysis for Web Search', 'just because they are long • Need to normalize 41 TF-IDF normalization • Normalize term weights • Normalize to vector length • Some references use non-normalized tf-idf • wik = tfiklog(N/nk) wik = tf ik log(N /nk ) (tf ik )2 k=1 t å [log(N /nk )]2 42 Vector space similarity • Boolean vectors contain only 0 or 1 depending on whether they contain a word doc1 = [1, 1, 1, 0, 0] • Now, use entire range [0, 1] to give more information doc1 = [0.2, 0.1, 0.5, 0, 0] 2 TF-IDF and the vector space • Vector lengths are now TF-IDF values • Vectors that are "close" are still similar in meaning 44 Vector space similarity • Vector space similarity is also called the cosine, or normalized inner product • Cosine similarity measures the angle between two vectors. If the angle is small → documents are similar. 45 Vector space similarity • Similarity of two docs is: Sim(Di,Dj) = wik * w jk k=1 t å 46 Normalized ahead of time, when computing term weights. Not normalized ahead of time Vector space similarity • Euclidean dot product formula 47 Already "baked" into weight Sim(Di,Dj) = wik * w jk k=1 t å Vector space summary • User''s query treated as short document • Query is in same space as docs • Easy to measure a doc''s distance to query • Extension of Boolean retrieval 48 TF-IDF strengths and weaknesses • TF-IDF works great when • Topics are disjoint • Pages are high quality (ex. focused on specific topic) • Fine for Wikipedia search • Likely used by Amazon product search • General web search requires additional technique • Many relevant results • Many low-quality results 49 Summary • Boolean retrieval includes or excludes results • Vector space model: each document is a vector with one component for each term • Vector space similarity • Documents that are close together are close in meaning • Query is a short document 50 Summary • Term frequency (TF): high value for common words in one document • Inverse Document Frequency (IDF): high value for rare words, low value for common words in collection of docs • tf-idf: Combine TF and IDF to form the magnitude of components in vector 51');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Text Analysis for Web Search', 'high value for rare words, low value for common words in collection of docs • tf-idf: Combine TF and IDF to form the magnitude of components in vector 51');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Link Analysis for Web Search', 'Link Analysis for Web Search Slides by Raed Almomani and Andrew DeOrio Review • Last time: ranked pages using page content (words) • Based on what appears in the document • Today: improve page rank using links between web pages • Based on document importnace 2 Agenda • Document importance • Link-based ranking algorithms • PageRank algorithm • HITS algorithm • Search engine optimization 3 Importance in the real world • How do people indicate something is important? • Talk about it • Cite it (academic papers) • Upvote it (Reddit) • Link to it 4 Humans indicate importance • Humans know better than computers which web pages are important • On the web, humans indicate importance using links • Similar to citations in academic papers 5 Link graph • Web as a graph (AKA network) • Each web page is a node • Each hyperlink is a directed edge 6 umich.edu eecs485.org docs.python.org en.wikipedia.org Using the link graph for importance • If many pages link to a page, it is likely important • If an important page links to a page, that page also is important 7 Web search history • Search in the 1990s was pretty bad • Hand-curated list (e.g. Yahoo) • Search engines used only page content (e.g. AltaVista) • Late 1990s: improve search using hyperlink graph • PageRank, Page & Brin • HITS, Kleinberg 8More on the Wikipedia Timeline of web search engines Page importance and search results Goal: 1. Make the web as graph 2. Compute important scores for pages 3. Use those scores to rank search results higher 9 Agenda • Document importance • Link-based ranking algorithms • PageRank algorithm • HITS algorithm • Search engine optimization 10 PageRank • Algorithm that made Google famous 11 PageRank model • Assume someone starts on a random web page • Click a random link on that page • Over and over • Web pages with more visits are more important 12 Random surfer example 13 en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thread_(computing) python.org/3/library/threading.html pythoncentral.io/how-to-create-a-thread-in-python/ eecs485staff.github.io/ p4-mapreduce/threads-sockets.html PageRank • A node with C outgoing links contributes 1/C of its PageRank to each linked node • Damping factor d is usually 0.85 14 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PageRank example • Total PR = 1, so initialize each node to 0.25 • Set d = 0.85 • PR(A) = (1 - 0.85)/4 + 0.85 * (0.25/1 + 0.25/1 + 0.25/1) • PR(A) = 0.675 15 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PageRank example • Again, initialize all nodes to 0.25 and d=0.85 • PR(A) = compute this 16 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PageRank example • Again, initialize all nodes to 0.25 and d=0.85 • PR(A) = (1 - 0.85)/4 + 0.85 * (0.25/2 + 0.25/1 + 0.25/3) = .0375+ .85*(0.125 + 0.25 + 0.083) = 0.4268 17 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å Example A B C D 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25 PR(A) =');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Link Analysis for Web Search', 'linked node • Damping factor d is usually 0.85 14 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PageRank example • Total PR = 1, so initialize each node to 0.25 • Set d = 0.85 • PR(A) = (1 - 0.85)/4 + 0.85 * (0.25/1 + 0.25/1 + 0.25/1) • PR(A) = 0.675 15 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PageRank example • Again, initialize all nodes to 0.25 and d=0.85 • PR(A) = compute this 16 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PageRank example • Again, initialize all nodes to 0.25 and d=0.85 • PR(A) = (1 - 0.85)/4 + 0.85 * (0.25/2 + 0.25/1 + 0.25/3) = .0375+ .85*(0.125 + 0.25 + 0.083) = 0.4268 17 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å Example A B C D 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å 18 Example A B C D 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.428 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PR(A) = 0.0375 + 0.85(0.25/2 + 0.25/1 + 0.25/3) 19 Example A B C D 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.428 0.109 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PR(B) = 0.0375 + 0.85(0.25/3) 20 Example A B C D 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.428 0.109 0.215 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PR(C) = 0.0375 + 0.85(0.25/2 + 0.25/3) 21 Example (normalization) A B C D 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.428 0.109 0.215 0.25 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å 22 Example A B C D 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.427 0.108 0.215 0.25 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å PR(D) = 0.0375 + 0.85(0.25/1) 23 Example A B C D 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.25 0.427 0.108 0.215 0.25 0.337 0.108 0.154 0.401 0.328 0.151 0.197 0.324 0.361 0.129 0.193 0.317 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å 24 Sink regions • What happens after many iterations? • Ignore damping factor (1-d)/N • PageRank “drains” into sink node (page with no outgoing links) 25 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å Damping factor to solve sink region • Must have non-zero probability of reaching every node from every other node • Solution: Add prob(1-d)/N of jumping to any page 26 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å Damping factor intuition • Probability of the user randomly jump to any page in the network rather than following a link. 27 Adding PageRank to a search engine • Weighted sum of page importance and query- similarity • Score(query, doc)= • w*sim(q, p) + (1-w) * PR(p) • If sim(q, p) > 0 • Otherwise, 0 • Where: • 0 < w < 1 • Values sim(q,p) and PR(p) are normalized 28 Agenda • Document importance • Link-based ranking algorithms • PageRank algorithm • HITS algorithm • Search engine optimization');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Link Analysis for Web Search', 'PageRank “drains” into sink node (page with no outgoing links) 25 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å Damping factor to solve sink region • Must have non-zero probability of reaching every node from every other node • Solution: Add prob(1-d)/N of jumping to any page 26 PR(A) = (1- d) N + d PR(Ii) C(Ii)i å Damping factor intuition • Probability of the user randomly jump to any page in the network rather than following a link. 27 Adding PageRank to a search engine • Weighted sum of page importance and query- similarity • Score(query, doc)= • w*sim(q, p) + (1-w) * PR(p) • If sim(q, p) > 0 • Otherwise, 0 • Where: • 0 < w < 1 • Values sim(q,p) and PR(p) are normalized 28 Agenda • Document importance • Link-based ranking algorithms • PageRank algorithm • HITS algorithm • Search engine optimization 29 Hubs and authorities • Unlike PageRank, HITS is query-dependent • A page is a good authority if it is pointed-to by many good hubs • A page is a good hub if it points to many good authorities • Good hubs and authorities reinforce each other 30 HITS algorithm 1. Obtain root set using input query 2. Expand the root set by radius 1. This is called the base set 3. Iteratively compute hub and authority scores for each node in graph auth( p) = hub(i) i=1 n å hub( p) = auth(i) i=1 n å 31 More HITS 1. Initialize all auth and hub scores to 1 2. For all nodes, update authority scores 3. For all nodes, update hub scores 4. Normalize scores • Divide each auth by sqrt(sum(auth2)) • Divide each hub by sqrt(sum(hub 2)) 5. If converges, terminate; else goto 2 32 HITS example 33 I love pizza I love EECS 485 I love the projects in EECS 485 I wonder which EECS classes I should take next semester This is not a PageRank question I love, love, love final exams I remember when I took EECS 485 query: "love 485" HITS example • Build root set using input query 34 I love pizza I love EECS 485 I love the projects in EECS 485 I wonder which EECS classes I should take next semester This is not a PageRank question I love, love, love final exams I remember when I took EECS 485 query: "love 485" HITS example • Build base set. Expand root set by radius 1. 35 I love pizza I love EECS 485 I love the projects in EECS 485 I wonder which EECS classes I should take next semester This is not a PageRank question I love, love, love final exams I remember when I took EECS 485 query: "love 485" HITS example • Initialize all hub and authority scores to 1 36 I love pizza I love EECS 485 I love the projects in EECS 485 I wonder which EECS classes I should take next semester This is not');
