INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Web Search', 'Scaling Web Search Review: How search works • Ahead of time • Download every web page • Build an index • Just-in-time (query time) • Read index • Rank results 2 Review: Ranking results • Problem: How do we rank results? • Text analysis: Rank using words on page • Link analysis: Rank using links on page 3 Where we are • How do we download every web page? • How do we build an index? • How do we make it fast? 4 A few numbers • 5 B - 100 B web pages • Let’s say 10 Billion for concreteness • Assume 10 KB per compressed page • 100 TB data to index • 1 minute - 1 month freshness • 3-5 B queries per day on Google alone 5 Agenda • Crawlers • Deduplication • Inverted index construction • Distributed search architecture 6 Crawlers •To search the web, we need to build an index and link graphs •Problem: We need a copy of the entire web •Solution: Download the entire web •Web Robots AKA Web Wanderers, Crawlers, or Spiders •Example: googlebot • •Problem: no list of all web pages 7 Web crawling • Problem: No list of all web pages • Solution: Traversal of the link graph 8 Web crawling: graph traversal • Have a list of "seed pages", follow all links like a BFS/DFS •Most of the Internet is a connected component 9 Problem1:Password protected content • Problem: Password-protected content • Bank records, Facebook, SnapChat, Dropbox, Google products, there''s a lot • Crawler can''t download it • No solution. Can''t index these pages. 10 Problem2: Deep web • Surface web: content indexed by search engines • Deep web: content not indexed by search engines • Size of deep web likely several orders of magnitude larger than surface web 11 12 Problem3: Client-side dynamic pages • Problem: How to download client -side dynamic pages? • Solution 1: Skip those pages • Solution 2: JS interpreter in crawler <html> <body> <div id="reactEntry>Loading...</div> <script src="..."></script> </body> </html> 13 Problem4: Crawlers "not nice" to servers • Problem: Crawlers generate a lot of traffic • CPU and bandwidth costs money • Website owners don''t like if you crawl too fast and will block you • Solution: Limit # requests per site per second 14 Problem5: Not all sites want to be indexed • Problem: Some websites don''t want to be indexed • Reasons not to index: • Personal creations: e.g. artwork on Google Images • Parts of dynamic websites: e.g. search engines • Solution: robots.txt 15 robots.txt User-agent: Googlebot Disallow: /*/download Disallow: /*/revisions Disallow: /*/*/issues/new Disallow: /*/*/issues/search Disallow: /*/*/commits/*/* Disallow: /*/*/commits/*?author Disallow: /*/*/commits/*?path ... 16 Problem 6: Deduplication • Many web pages are exact copies of other web pages • Only create index once • We''ll learn how to solve this in the next segments 17 Agenda • Crawlers • Deduplication • Inverted index construction • Distributed search architecture 18 Deduplication in Web Search • Many web pages are identical or');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Web Search', 'lot of traffic • CPU and bandwidth costs money • Website owners don''t like if you crawl too fast and will block you • Solution: Limit # requests per site per second 14 Problem5: Not all sites want to be indexed • Problem: Some websites don''t want to be indexed • Reasons not to index: • Personal creations: e.g. artwork on Google Images • Parts of dynamic websites: e.g. search engines • Solution: robots.txt 15 robots.txt User-agent: Googlebot Disallow: /*/download Disallow: /*/revisions Disallow: /*/*/issues/new Disallow: /*/*/issues/search Disallow: /*/*/commits/*/* Disallow: /*/*/commits/*?author Disallow: /*/*/commits/*?path ... 16 Problem 6: Deduplication • Many web pages are exact copies of other web pages • Only create index once • We''ll learn how to solve this in the next segments 17 Agenda • Crawlers • Deduplication • Inverted index construction • Distributed search architecture 18 Deduplication in Web Search • Many web pages are identical or nearly identical • News websites: many have the same articles • Storing duplicates wastes space and slow search • Goal: detect and remove duplicate or near -duplicate pages efficiently • Key idea: avoid storing or ranking the same content multiple times. 19 20 Exact Duplicate Detection (Hashing) • Compute a hash for each document • Hash("It grows in dry places...") = 8d2f908... • If two documents have the same hash; they are identical • Very fast and scalable • Ex: hash(doc1) == hash(doc2) => duplicate • With small doc change; completely different hash 21 Limitation of Hashing • Every small edits change the hash completely different • Example: • “best pizza in town” • “best pizza in town!” • These are nearly identical, but hashes differ • Need away to detect near duplicates, not just exact matches 22 Why not compare entire document? • Documents can be similar but not exactly the same 23 Measuring Similarity with Jaccard • Represent each document as a set of words • Compare overlap between sets • 1 = identical; 0 = completely different • Measures how similar two document are 24 Jaccard Example • Doc A = {cooking, dinner, recipe} • Doc B = {cooking, dinner, meal} • Intersection = {cooking, dinner} -> 2 • Union = {cooking, dinner, recipe, meal} -> 4 • Similarity = J(A, B) = 2/4 = 0.5 • Higher overlap -> higher similarity 25 Why this Doesn’t Scale • Comparing all pairs is too expensive • For N documents → ~ N² comparisons • Web-scale data makes this infeasible • Need a faster approximation method 26 String comparison • Problem: Comparing strings is slow, even short strings • A = {cooking, dinner, recipe} • B = {cooking, dinner, meal} • J(A, B) = 2/4 = 1/2 27 Numeric comparison • Problem: Comparing strings is slow, even short strings • A = {cooking, dinner, recipe} • B = {cooking, dinner, meal} • J(A, B) = 2/4 = 1/2 • Solution: Hash each word and compare the numbers • A_hashes = {0x1a4, 0x2b5, 0x3c6} • B_hashes = {0x1a4, 0x2b5, 0x4d7}');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Web Search', '= {cooking, dinner, meal} • Intersection = {cooking, dinner} -> 2 • Union = {cooking, dinner, recipe, meal} -> 4 • Similarity = J(A, B) = 2/4 = 0.5 • Higher overlap -> higher similarity 25 Why this Doesn’t Scale • Comparing all pairs is too expensive • For N documents → ~ N² comparisons • Web-scale data makes this infeasible • Need a faster approximation method 26 String comparison • Problem: Comparing strings is slow, even short strings • A = {cooking, dinner, recipe} • B = {cooking, dinner, meal} • J(A, B) = 2/4 = 1/2 27 Numeric comparison • Problem: Comparing strings is slow, even short strings • A = {cooking, dinner, recipe} • B = {cooking, dinner, meal} • J(A, B) = 2/4 = 1/2 • Solution: Hash each word and compare the numbers • A_hashes = {0x1a4, 0x2b5, 0x3c6} • B_hashes = {0x1a4, 0x2b5, 0x4d7} • J(A_hashes, B_hashes) = 2/4 = 1/2 28 Word Hash cooking 0x1a4 dinner 0x2b5 recipe 0x3c6 meal 0x4d7 Sampling • Problem: Set comparison is still too slow • Solution: Compare a sample of the set • Randomly select k values from A and k values from B • Example k=2 • A_hashes = {0x1a4, 0x2b5, 0x3c6, ...} • B_hashes = {0x1a4, 0x2b5, 0x4d7, ...} • A_sample = {0x1a4, 0x2b5} • B_sample = {0x1a4, 0x2b5} • J(A_sample, B_sample) = 2/2 = 1 29 Word Hash cooking 0x1a4 dinner 0x2b5 recipe 0x3c6 meal 0x4d7 Hashing and random values • Problem: How to select a random hash value? • Solution 1: Select the element at a random index • What if container doesn''t support random access? • Must store all the values first • Solution 2: Select the min hashed value • The hash function maps inputs uniformly over the output • Selecting the min(h(x)) is the same as selecting a random item x! • This is called MinHash 30 MinHash • Use multiple hash functions • For each document: • Hash all elements • Keep only the minimum hash value • Repeat with different hash functions • Each document -> small signature 31 MinHash example • Doc A = “cooking dinner recipe” • Doc B = “cooking dinner meal” • MinHash with k=2 • A_sample = {0x1a4, 0x2b5} • B_sample = {0x1a4, 0x2b5} • Key idea: Compress large sets into small comparable signatures. 32 Word Hash cooking 0x1a4 dinner 0x2b5 recipe 0x3c6 meal 0x4d7 Why MinHash works • Probability that two documents have same min hash = their Jaccard similarity • So: • More matches -> more similar • Fewer matches -> less similar • MinHash approximates similarity without full comparison 33 Shingling • Break document into sequences of words (k -grams) • Example (k=2): • “web search engine” -> {web search, search engine”} • Captures word order • Improve similarity accuracy • Preserves structure, not just word presence 34 MinHash with shingles • Apply MinHash to shingles instead of words • Example • doc = "this is some text” • 2-shingles');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Web Search', '31 MinHash example • Doc A = “cooking dinner recipe” • Doc B = “cooking dinner meal” • MinHash with k=2 • A_sample = {0x1a4, 0x2b5} • B_sample = {0x1a4, 0x2b5} • Key idea: Compress large sets into small comparable signatures. 32 Word Hash cooking 0x1a4 dinner 0x2b5 recipe 0x3c6 meal 0x4d7 Why MinHash works • Probability that two documents have same min hash = their Jaccard similarity • So: • More matches -> more similar • Fewer matches -> less similar • MinHash approximates similarity without full comparison 33 Shingling • Break document into sequences of words (k -grams) • Example (k=2): • “web search engine” -> {web search, search engine”} • Captures word order • Improve similarity accuracy • Preserves structure, not just word presence 34 MinHash with shingles • Apply MinHash to shingles instead of words • Example • doc = "this is some text” • 2-shingles • k=2 • Shingles = {0x1aa, 0x2bb} 35 Shingle Hash this is 0x1aa is some 0x2bb some text 0x3cc MinHash with shingles advantages • Comparing numbers is faster • Compare hash values (numbers) instead of strings • Approximation is faster • Compare k shingles instead of n • Fast random shingle selection • Select k shingles using minimum hash value 36 Agenda • Crawlers • Deduplication • Inverted index construction • Distributed search architecture 37 Serving search results • After crawling is finished, we have a big database of documents • Now we need to build an index 38 Inverted index • A forward index is a list of words in each document • Doc -> words • An inverted index maps words to docs that contain those words • Word -> docs • For each word, list all the documents where that word can be found • Key to fast query processing 39 as billy cities friendly give mayors nancy seattle such words #docs docid0 docid1 #docs docid0 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 #docs docid0 docid1 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid3 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… Inverted index 40 as billy cities friendly give mayors nancy seattle such words #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… Inverted index exercise 41 Describe an algorithm that finds a list of docs for the search: such as as billy cities friendly give mayors nancy seattle such words #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… 104 21 150 322 2501 15 99 322 426 1309 1.Test for equality 2.Advance smaller pointer 3.Abort when a list is exhausted Returned docs: 322 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… Solution: merge intersection 42 Agenda • Crawlers • Inverted index construction • Deduplication • Distributed search architecture 43 Distributed search • Problem: Inverted index is too big for one machine • Billions of docs • Problem: Query load is too big for one machine • Billions queries • Problem: A machine could fail • Solution: Parallel query processing • Segment by');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Web Search', 'docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… Inverted index 40 as billy cities friendly give mayors nancy seattle such words #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… Inverted index exercise 41 Describe an algorithm that finds a list of docs for the search: such as as billy cities friendly give mayors nancy seattle such words #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… 104 21 150 322 2501 15 99 322 426 1309 1.Test for equality 2.Advance smaller pointer 3.Abort when a list is exhausted Returned docs: 322 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… Solution: merge intersection 42 Agenda • Crawlers • Inverted index construction • Deduplication • Distributed search architecture 43 Distributed search • Problem: Inverted index is too big for one machine • Billions of docs • Problem: Query load is too big for one machine • Billions queries • Problem: A machine could fail • Solution: Parallel query processing • Segment by term • Segment by document 44 as britney cities friendly give mayors nancy seattle such words #docs docid0 docid1 #docs docid0 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 #docs docid0 docid1 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid3 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… Segment by term (divide rows) 45 “britney” Docs 0-5M Docs 0-5M Docs 0-5M Docs 0-5M Docs 0-5M 1.2M, 4.4M, 29, … A-B C-D E-F G-H H-I Segment by term 46 as britney cities friendly give mayors nancy seattle such words #docs docid0 docid1 #docs docid0 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 #docs docid0 docid1 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid3 #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… #docs docid0 docid1 docid2 docid#docs-1… Segment by document (divide cols) 47 “britney” Docs 0-1M Docs 1-2M Docs 2-3M Docs 3-4M Docs 4-5M Ds 2.3M, 2.9M 1.2M, 4.4M, 29, … Segment by document 48 Segmentation • What are the tradeoffs of segment -by-term vs. segment- by-document? • What happens if a machine dies? 49 Segmentation • Segment by document • Easy to partition (docid % num_segments) • Easy to add new documents • If a machine fails, quality decreases, but queries don’t die • Segment by term • Harder to partition (terms uneven) • Trickier to add a new document (need to touch many machines) • If machine fails, search term might disappear, but not critical pages (e.g., cnn.com/index.html) 50 Summary: Crawlers • Problem: Need to build index and link graphs • Solution: Download the web with a crawler • Problem: No list of all web pages • Solution: Traversal of the link graph • Surface web: content indexed by search engines 51 Summary: Deduplication • Deduplication: filter out duplicate web pages • Shingle: sequence of words • Hash of shingle: numeric representation of sequence of words • Min hash: random shingle selection • Compare 2 set-of-random-hashes with Jaccard similarity coefficient 52 Summary: Inverted Index • Inverted index: map words to docs that contain words • Problem: Inverted index is too big');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Web Search', '• If a machine fails, quality decreases, but queries don’t die • Segment by term • Harder to partition (terms uneven) • Trickier to add a new document (need to touch many machines) • If machine fails, search term might disappear, but not critical pages (e.g., cnn.com/index.html) 50 Summary: Crawlers • Problem: Need to build index and link graphs • Solution: Download the web with a crawler • Problem: No list of all web pages • Solution: Traversal of the link graph • Surface web: content indexed by search engines 51 Summary: Deduplication • Deduplication: filter out duplicate web pages • Shingle: sequence of words • Hash of shingle: numeric representation of sequence of words • Min hash: random shingle selection • Compare 2 set-of-random-hashes with Jaccard similarity coefficient 52 Summary: Inverted Index • Inverted index: map words to docs that contain words • Problem: Inverted index is too big • Problem: Query load is too big • Solution: Parallel query processing • Segment by term: different terms on different machines • Segment by document: different documents on different machines 53');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Static Pages', 'Scaling Static Pages Slides by Andrew DeOrio Scaling road map • Today: Scaling static pages • Next: Scaling dynamic pages • Later: Scaling storage • Database • Media 2 Agenda • Cloud • Scaling static pages • Domain name system (DNS) • Resolution • Scaling and security • Content delivery networks (CDNs) 3 Motivation • You built a web app that works for one user • Runs locally on your laptop • Question: How do we support millions of users? • Answer: Move to a scalable production environment 4 Development vs. production • Development • For building and debugging • Runs on one machine • Example: flask run • Production • For real users • Runs on many machines • Specialized and scalable • Problem: Where do these computers live? • Solution: Buy servers 5 On-premises servers • Buy your own servers • Build your own datacenter • AKA "private cloud" • AKA "on-premises" 6 Datacenter • Large facility with thousands of servers • Requires: • Power • Colling • High bandwidth • Lots of computers means lots of computer failures 7 On-premises to IaaS • Problem: • Managing physical servers is difficult • Power, cooling, failures, maintenance • Solution: • Rent computers instead of owning them 8 Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) • Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) • Rent a computer in somebody else''s datacenter • Benefits • No hardware management • Built-in scaling • High availability • Examples: • AWS EC2 • Google Compute Engine • Microsoft Azure Virtual Machines 9 IaaS to PaaS • Problem: Managing software on many rented computers is complex • Security updates, complex configuration • Solution: Rent computers with software already installed and configured 10 Platform as a Service (PaaS) • Platform as a Service (PaaS): Rent a computer in somebody else''s data center • They manage and configure the software • You manage your application • Example: servers with database already installed • AWS Relational Database Service (RDS) • Google Cloud SQL • Microsoft Azure SQL 11 PaaS to SaaS • Problem: Sometimes you don’t want to build or mangage an app. • Solution: Rent a fully managed web application running on somebody else''s computers 12 Software as a Service (SaaS) • Software as a Service (SaaS): Fully managed applications • Zero effort • No infrastructure of maintenance • Ready to use • Examples: • Gmail • Dropbox • GitHub 13 IaaS vs. PaaS vs. SaaS 14 Cloud memes 15 Web apps in the cloud • Problem: How do I run my web app in the cloud? • Scale one thing at time • Static pages • Server-side dynamic pages • Client-side dynamic pages • Database storage • Media uploads storage 16 Agenda • Cloud • Scaling static pages • Domain name system (DNS) • Resolution • Scaling and security • Content delivery networks (CDNs) 17 Static pages • Static pages: a request returns a copy of a file • Problem: How do we serve copies to many clients at the');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Static Pages', 'app. • Solution: Rent a fully managed web application running on somebody else''s computers 12 Software as a Service (SaaS) • Software as a Service (SaaS): Fully managed applications • Zero effort • No infrastructure of maintenance • Ready to use • Examples: • Gmail • Dropbox • GitHub 13 IaaS vs. PaaS vs. SaaS 14 Cloud memes 15 Web apps in the cloud • Problem: How do I run my web app in the cloud? • Scale one thing at time • Static pages • Server-side dynamic pages • Client-side dynamic pages • Database storage • Media uploads storage 16 Agenda • Cloud • Scaling static pages • Domain name system (DNS) • Resolution • Scaling and security • Content delivery networks (CDNs) 17 Static pages • Static pages: a request returns a copy of a file • Problem: How do we serve copies to many clients at the same time? • Solution: many servers • Problem: It takes a long time for a request/response to traverse the global internet • Solution: servers in different geographic locations 18 Review: IP Address • Every device on the Internet has an IP address • 172.217.5.14 • But humans use domain names • Example: umich.edu • DNS translates domain names to IP addresses 19 DNS directs to different regions • Deploy servers in different geographic regions • Use DNS to route users to nearby servers • Question: How does DNS work? 20 Agenda • Scaling static pages intro • Domain name system (DNS) • Namespace • Resolution • Scaling and security • Content delivery networks (CDNs) 21 Domain Name System (DNS) • Domain Name System (DNS) Translates domain names to IP addresses • Example: umich.edu -> 141.211.243.251 • Basically a database of (hostname, IP) pairs 22 DNS example 23 Nameserver provides IP of umich.edu nameserver umich.edu web server Client 1 2 Agenda • Cloud • Scaling static pages intro • Domain name system (DNS) • Resolution • Scaling and security • Content delivery networks (CDNs) 24 DNS Resolution • Content of DNS consists of resource records • Host -> IP • Most DNS activity • Client requests to authority servers • Server responds with resource record 25 Where do I get a DNS server? • IP addresses are commonly assigned automatically • When you connect to a WIFI or wired network • DHCP: Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol • Assigns an IP • Provides DNS servers 26 Resolution with more detail • In the previous example, our DNS server had a cached copy of the IP address for umich.edu • What if it didn''t have a cached copy? • Ask the authority servers 27 DNS Resolution Steps • DNS resolution steps to open umich.edu • Ask root server where is .edu • Ask .edu server where is umich.edu • Ask umich.edu server to get IP • Result: Client receives IP of umich.edu 28 Resolution 29 local nameserver provides IP of root nameserver root nameserver provides IP of edu nameserver edu nameserver provides IP');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Static Pages', 'DNS activity • Client requests to authority servers • Server responds with resource record 25 Where do I get a DNS server? • IP addresses are commonly assigned automatically • When you connect to a WIFI or wired network • DHCP: Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol • Assigns an IP • Provides DNS servers 26 Resolution with more detail • In the previous example, our DNS server had a cached copy of the IP address for umich.edu • What if it didn''t have a cached copy? • Ask the authority servers 27 DNS Resolution Steps • DNS resolution steps to open umich.edu • Ask root server where is .edu • Ask .edu server where is umich.edu • Ask umich.edu server to get IP • Result: Client receives IP of umich.edu 28 Resolution 29 local nameserver provides IP of root nameserver root nameserver provides IP of edu nameserver edu nameserver provides IP of umich.edu nameserver umich.edu nameserver provides IP of umich.edu web server . root nameserver edu nameserver umich.edu nameserver local nameserver umich.edu web server Client 1 2 3 4 5 Resolution with caching 30 local nameserver provides IP of umich.edu web server because it''s in the cache local nameserver umich.edu web server Client 1 2 DNS Caching • DNS Caching: DNS results are cached for speed • Great! But when data changes? • TTL (Time-To-Live): How long a record stays valid 31 Root nameservers • Responsible for locating the top level domain name servers (.com, .net, .org, …) • 13 root name servers in world • Their locations are hard-coded in resolving DNS servers • Due to caching, involved in few queries 32 Agenda • Scaling static pages intro • Domain name system (DNS) • Namespace • Resolution • Scaling and security • Content delivery networks (CDNs) 33 DNS scale • DNS operates at massive scale • Used in nearly every internet request • Impacts • Computers • Phones • Internet of Things (IoT) devices • Backend services 34 DNS as a security vulnerability • DNS is an extreme security vulnerability • What if someone can remap google.com? • What about just denial-of-service? • Terrorism 35 What if someone can remap google.com? • Domain name registrations have an expiration date • Google''s expired one time • Registrar reversed it 36 DNS cache poisoning • Bad info is inserted into a DNS server and cached • Both inadvertent and malicious • How could one attach CSE’s DNS server? 37 DNS cache poisoning • DNS cache poisoning is one of the ways that China’s Great Firewall works • Just direct requests to twitter.com to the wrong IP 38 DNS security remedies • If you use HTTPS/SSL/TSL, problem mitigated • DNSSEC is a security extension to DNS • Cryptographically signed DNS entries • Asymmetric cryptography 39 Agenda • Scaling static pages intro • Domain name system (DNS) • Namespace • Resolution • Scaling and security • Content delivery networks (CDNs) 40 Scaling static pages solution • So far, we''ve talked about how to convert');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Static Pages', 'just denial-of-service? • Terrorism 35 What if someone can remap google.com? • Domain name registrations have an expiration date • Google''s expired one time • Registrar reversed it 36 DNS cache poisoning • Bad info is inserted into a DNS server and cached • Both inadvertent and malicious • How could one attach CSE’s DNS server? 37 DNS cache poisoning • DNS cache poisoning is one of the ways that China’s Great Firewall works • Just direct requests to twitter.com to the wrong IP 38 DNS security remedies • If you use HTTPS/SSL/TSL, problem mitigated • DNSSEC is a security extension to DNS • Cryptographically signed DNS entries • Asymmetric cryptography 39 Agenda • Scaling static pages intro • Domain name system (DNS) • Namespace • Resolution • Scaling and security • Content delivery networks (CDNs) 40 Scaling static pages solution • So far, we''ve talked about how to convert a hostname into the IP address of a server • How do we return the IP address of a nearby server? 41 Content delivery networks • A content delivery network (CDN) stores static files at many locations throughout the world and serves nearby clients • Static files: HTML, images, videos • Large read-only data stored close to client • Reduce latency to faraway datacenter • Reduce bandwidth costs by sending data only a short distance 42 Akamai • The first content-delivery network • You might think the image is from CNN, but Akamai is serving it • CNN pays Akamai to do so • Built on top of a giant DNS hack 43 How it works: step 1 • Akamai places servers across the world 44 How it works: step 2 • Akamai gets client data • Especially images, videos • Copies to all nodes in network 45 How it works: step 3 • How does client find nearby data? • Network conditions can change 46 How it works: step 3 • Website rewrites their URLs to uses CDN URLs • => 47 How it works: step 3 • URL contains Akamai-controlled name • Specialized Akamai DNS server resolves name to nearby server; tiny TTL 48 How it works: step 3 • Resolution strongly dependent on • Location of client; network conditions; load on Akamai servers; traffic estimation errors 49 Akamai''s scale • Akamai has 170k servers • Serves ~15%-30% of all web traffic 50 CDN summary • Custom DNS servers dynamically direct clients to best caching servers • Static content • Reduces latency for clients fetching content • Reduces load on datacenter servers 51 Summary • Cloud: "Where do we put all the computers" • Domain name system (DNS): Distributed system for translating hostname to IP • Resolve a domain name to an IP address •umich.edu -> 141.211.243.251 • Content delivery network (CDN): Distributed system for serving static pages • Duplicate static data • Direct clients to nearby servers • Use modified DNS 52 Scaling road map • Today: Scaling static pages • Next time: Scaling dynamic pages •');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Static Pages', 'to nearby server; tiny TTL 48 How it works: step 3 • Resolution strongly dependent on • Location of client; network conditions; load on Akamai servers; traffic estimation errors 49 Akamai''s scale • Akamai has 170k servers • Serves ~15%-30% of all web traffic 50 CDN summary • Custom DNS servers dynamically direct clients to best caching servers • Static content • Reduces latency for clients fetching content • Reduces load on datacenter servers 51 Summary • Cloud: "Where do we put all the computers" • Domain name system (DNS): Distributed system for translating hostname to IP • Resolve a domain name to an IP address •umich.edu -> 141.211.243.251 • Content delivery network (CDN): Distributed system for serving static pages • Duplicate static data • Direct clients to nearby servers • Use modified DNS 52 Scaling road map • Today: Scaling static pages • Next time: Scaling dynamic pages • After that: Scaling storage • Database • Media uploads 53');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Dynamic Pages', 'Scaling Dynamic Pages Slides by Raed Almomani and Andrew DeOrio Scaling road map • Last time: scaling static pages • Today: scaling dynamic pages • Next time: scaling storage • Database • Media uploads 2 Agenda • Multi-process, multi-thread, and asynchronous • Round robin DNS and load balancing • Hardware virtualization • Containerization 3 Server-side dynamic pages • Server-side dynamic pages: Server response is the output of a function. • What happens when two clients make two requests at the same time? • What about many clients? 4 1 server, 1 process, 1 request • One server runs one process with one thread • Example: Flask development server • One response at a time 5 1 server, 1 process, 2 requests • One server runs one process with one thread 7 Limitations of 1 process, 1 thread, 1 CPU • Problem: simultaneous requests go one at a time • Solution 1: Asynchronous programming • Limited solution • Illusion of parallelism, still runs on one CPU core • Solution 1: Multiple threads on one CPU core • Limited solution • Illusion of parallelism, still runs on one CPU core • Solution 3: Multiple processes on one CPU core • Limited solution • Illusion of parallelism, still runs on one CPU core 9 1 server, 2 processes, 2 requests • Problem: simultaneous requests go one at a time • Solution 4: multiple processes or threads on a multicore CPU 10 Multiprocessing with multithreading or asynchronous programming • Can we combine multiprocessing with multithreading? • Yes • Example: Apache with mod_wsgi • Can we combine multiprocessing with asynchronous programming? • Yes • Example: Gunicorn • Can we combine multiprocessing with multithreading and asynchronous programming? • Yes • Example: Gunicorn 12 Many servers • Problem: one multicore server is not enough • Solution: buy or rent more servers 13 Agenda • Multi-process, multi-thread, and asynchronous • Round robin DNS and load balancing • Hardware virtualization • Containerization 15 Problems with many servers • Problem: Two users make a request. Which server should respond? • Option 1: Round robin DNS 16 Round Robin DNS diagram 17 Round Robin DNS description • Modified DNS server responds with different IPs to different dynamic pages web servers • Rotating list of IPs • Usually in the same datacenter 18 Problem with Round Robin DNS • Problem: round robin DNS doesn’t consider server load. One request might be more time consuming than another • Solution: Load balancer 19 Load balancer diagram 20 Load balancer description • Load balancer, AKA proxy server • "Middleman" forwards requests to backend servers • End user doesn''t need to know about them 21 Problem with load balancer • Problem: Load balancer is a single point of failure • Solution: Round robin DNS to multiple load balancers 22 Load balancer with Round Robin DNS 23 Agenda • Multi-process, multi-thread, and asynchronous • Round robin DNS and load balancing • Hardware virtualization • Containerization 24 Scaling servers • Many servers running our server-side dynamic pages code');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Dynamic Pages', '17 Round Robin DNS description • Modified DNS server responds with different IPs to different dynamic pages web servers • Rotating list of IPs • Usually in the same datacenter 18 Problem with Round Robin DNS • Problem: round robin DNS doesn’t consider server load. One request might be more time consuming than another • Solution: Load balancer 19 Load balancer diagram 20 Load balancer description • Load balancer, AKA proxy server • "Middleman" forwards requests to backend servers • End user doesn''t need to know about them 21 Problem with load balancer • Problem: Load balancer is a single point of failure • Solution: Round robin DNS to multiple load balancers 22 Load balancer with Round Robin DNS 23 Agenda • Multi-process, multi-thread, and asynchronous • Round robin DNS and load balancing • Hardware virtualization • Containerization 24 Scaling servers • Many servers running our server-side dynamic pages code • Example: Python/Flask via Gunicorn • Rented from an IaaS provider (Data Center) 25 Datacenter problems: aggregation • IaaS provider has many different computers • Different CPUs, memory, etc. • Difficult to customize the program for different server configurations • E.g. more threads on more powerful computers • How can we aggregate workloads together on machines? 26 Datacenter problems: isolation • IaaS provider has many different customers • Customer programs have different requirements • Linux kernel versions, installed libraries, etc. • How to securely isolate different programs from each other? 27 Datacenter problems: migration • Sometimes many users visit our site, sometimes few • Sometimes machines fail • How to add more machines when load is high? • How to migrate running server programs when a machine fails? 28 Hardware virtualization • Problem 1: Workload Aggregration • Problem 2: Workload Isolation • Problem 3: Workload Migration • Solution: Hardware Virtualization 29 Not hardware virtualization • Without hardware virtualization, one physical computer runs one operating system 30 Hardware virtualization • With hardware virtualization, one physical computer runs multiple operating systems 31 HW Virtualization vs. virtual environment • Hardware virtualization and Python virtual environments have nothing to do with each other • HW virtualization: one physical computer runs multiple operating systems • Python virtual environment: one operating system runs multiple Python and third-party library versions 32 Hardware virtualization • With hardware virtualization, one physical computer runs multiple operating systems 33 Hardware virtualization terminology • Host: physical computer running OS and virtualization software • Guest: operating system(s) being run as “programs”, not on dedicated physical hardware • Hypervisor: virtualization software runs guests on host • VirtualBox, VMWare, et al. • Hardware emulation • Host shares physical resources like network, disk, etc. with guests via virtual hardware 34 Tangent: WSL2 • Another use for hardware virtualization: Windows Subsystem for Linux 2 (WSL2) • Run Linux operating system on top of windows • Better compatibility with Linux programs 35 Images from Hardware virtualization advantages • Workload Aggregation • Run multiple workloads on each physical machine • Run every physical machine at maximum efficiency • Workload');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Dynamic Pages', 'HW virtualization: one physical computer runs multiple operating systems • Python virtual environment: one operating system runs multiple Python and third-party library versions 32 Hardware virtualization • With hardware virtualization, one physical computer runs multiple operating systems 33 Hardware virtualization terminology • Host: physical computer running OS and virtualization software • Guest: operating system(s) being run as “programs”, not on dedicated physical hardware • Hypervisor: virtualization software runs guests on host • VirtualBox, VMWare, et al. • Hardware emulation • Host shares physical resources like network, disk, etc. with guests via virtual hardware 34 Tangent: WSL2 • Another use for hardware virtualization: Windows Subsystem for Linux 2 (WSL2) • Run Linux operating system on top of windows • Better compatibility with Linux programs 35 Images from Hardware virtualization advantages • Workload Aggregation • Run multiple workloads on each physical machine • Run every physical machine at maximum efficiency • Workload Isolation • Each service gets its own preferred OS, libraries, etc. • Compromised guest OS won’t affect other guest VMs • Workload Migration • Add more VMs as more users hit your site • If there’s a power failure at your East data center, replicate VMs to your Midwest data center 36 Hardware virtualization disadvantages • Memory • Guest includes a complete OS including drivers, binaries, and libraries • Slow start • 10s ~ 100s to boot a VM 37 Hardware virtualization disadvantages • Memory • Guest includes a complete OS including drivers, binaries, and libraries • Slow start • 10s ~ 100s to boot a VM 38 Agenda • Multi-process, multi-thread, and asynchronous • Round robin DNS and load balancing • Hardware virtualization • Containerization 39 Containerization • Problem: Virtualization has high overhead • Memory • Slow start • Solution: Containerization • Docker is popular • Key idea: share OS, with its binaries and libraries 40 Containerization • Container includes application code and dependencies • Container does not include OS 41 Example: Virtual machine • Install virtualization manager, e.g., VirtualBox • Create guest virtual machine • Install OS on guest VM • Install Python and Gunicorn on guest VM • Copy Flask program insta485 from host to guest • SSH into guest • Run program on guest $ gunicorn insta485:app • Stop guest VM 42 Example: container • Install container runtime (Docker) • Create Docker image • Copy Flask program insta485 into container • Configure container to execute server • $ docker build • Run Docker container from host •$ docker run insta485 43 44 Containers, round robin DNS and load balancing Containerization advantages • Lower memory footprint • Faster start-up time 0.1 ~ 1 s 45 Containerization disadvantages • All containers that run on a Linux host must be designed to run on Linux • Can’t run Windows containers on a Linux host • A security vulnerability in the OS will impact every container on that host machine 46 Virtualization vs. containerization Virtualization • Run multiple OSs on a single physical machine • Abstraction of hardware • Replication');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Dynamic Pages', '• Copy Flask program insta485 from host to guest • SSH into guest • Run program on guest $ gunicorn insta485:app • Stop guest VM 42 Example: container • Install container runtime (Docker) • Create Docker image • Copy Flask program insta485 into container • Configure container to execute server • $ docker build • Run Docker container from host •$ docker run insta485 43 44 Containers, round robin DNS and load balancing Containerization advantages • Lower memory footprint • Faster start-up time 0.1 ~ 1 s 45 Containerization disadvantages • All containers that run on a Linux host must be designed to run on Linux • Can’t run Windows containers on a Linux host • A security vulnerability in the OS will impact every container on that host machine 46 Virtualization vs. containerization Virtualization • Run multiple OSs on a single physical machine • Abstraction of hardware • Replication • Isolation • High mem overhead • Slow startup • Stateful Containerization • Run multiple apps on a single virtual or physical machine • Abstraction of OS • Replication • Isolation • Low mem overhead • Fast startup • Stateless 47 Stateful vs. stateless • Example server-side dynamic pages app that logs to /var/log/insta485.log 127.0.0.1 - [06/May/2021 16:50:09] "GET / HTTP/1.1" 200 – 127.0.0.1 - [06/May/2021 16:50:09] "GET /static/js/bundle.js HTTP/1.1" 200 – 127.0.0.1 - [06/May/2021 16:50:09] "GET /api/v1/posts/ HTTP/1.1" 200 – • Run it, make a few requests, restart • What happens to the log in a virtual machine? • What happens to the log in a container? 48 Stateful virtual machine example • VMs have a virtual, persistent hard drive • Hard drive is a file on the host computer • VM writes to the HDD -> file modified • Restart VM, file is restored, including changes 49 Stateful virtual machine example • VMs have a virtual, persistent hard drive • Hard drive is a file on the host computer • VM writes to the HDD -> file modified • Restart VM, file is restored, including changes 50 Stateless container example • Container software layer emulates hard disk drive • Hard drive is a data structure in the container runtime • Container writes to the HDD -> data structure modified • Restart container, changes are lost • This is a feature! Separation of storage and compute. 51 Service-oriented architecture (SOA) • Service-oriented architecture (SOA) • Not SOA: run entire web app on one machine • SOA: Break up web app into services that communicate over a network • Run different services on different machines • Static pages servers • Server-side dynamic pages servers • Database servers • Log storage servers • Etc. 52 Microservice architecture • Microservice architecture is a service-oriented architecture with "smaller pieces" • Common with containerization 53 Check your understanding • We talked about scaling server-side dynamic pages today • How do we scale a client-side dynamic pages application? 54 Check your understanding • How do we scale a client-side dynamic pages application? • Scale the');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Dynamic Pages', '• Hard drive is a data structure in the container runtime • Container writes to the HDD -> data structure modified • Restart container, changes are lost • This is a feature! Separation of storage and compute. 51 Service-oriented architecture (SOA) • Service-oriented architecture (SOA) • Not SOA: run entire web app on one machine • SOA: Break up web app into services that communicate over a network • Run different services on different machines • Static pages servers • Server-side dynamic pages servers • Database servers • Log storage servers • Etc. 52 Microservice architecture • Microservice architecture is a service-oriented architecture with "smaller pieces" • Common with containerization 53 Check your understanding • We talked about scaling server-side dynamic pages today • How do we scale a client-side dynamic pages application? 54 Check your understanding • How do we scale a client-side dynamic pages application? • Scale the JavaScript distribution with same techniques as static pages • bundle.js via CDN • Scale the REST API using same techniques as server-side dynamic pages • REST API server code in a container on PaaS 55 Scaling road map • Last time: scaling static pages • Today: scaling dynamic pages • Next time: scaling storage • Database • Media uploads 56');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Storage', 'Scaling Storage Slides by Raed Almomani and Andrew DeOrio Scaling road map • Previously: Scaling static pages • DNS, CDNs • Last Lecture: Scaling server-side dynamic pages • Round robin DNS, load balancing, hardware virtualization, containerization • Today: Scaling storage • Database • Media uploads 2 Agenda • Distributed network database • Sharding vs replication • CAP Theorem • Practical database examples • Media storage 3 Review: Scaling dynamic pages • Dynamic pages servers run in servers • AKA "Front end server" AKA "FE” • Requests routed to servers via round robin DNS and load balancing 4 Review: Round Robin DNS diagram 5 Problem with many servers • 2 clients connect to 2 servers, access the same data • E.g., one likes a post, and the other loads the same post 6 Many dynamic pages servers • Different dynamic pages servers on every request • Physical machines, virtual machines, or containers • AKA "Front end servers” • Problem: How to synchronize dynamic pages servers? • Solution: Dynamic pages servers are stateless, store everything in the database 7 Network database • Many dynamic pages servers make network requests to one network database • Network database: Database software runs on a different server on the network • PostgreSQL, MongoDB, et al. • Centralized network database: One server 8 Centralized network database • Centralized network database: Single network database server 9 Centralized network database write 10 Centralized network database read 11 Centralized network database • Data consistency is easy • Problem: Performance bottleneck • Solution: More database servers 12 Distributed network database • Distributed network database: Many network database servers • Problem: How to keep database servers in sync? • Solution: Data consistency is hard, depends on which servers contain which data • Problem: Which servers contain which data? • Solution 1: Sharding by content • Solution 2: Database replication 13 Agenda • Distributed network database • Sharding vs replication • CAP Theorem • Practical database examples • Distributed file system for media uploads 14 Sharding and replication • Problem: Which servers contain which data? • Solution 1: Sharding by content • Solution 2: Database replication 15 Sharding by content • Different rows or tables on different DB servers 16 Sharding by content write • A write modifies the only copy 17 Sharding by content read • A read accesses the only copy 18 Sharding by content pros and cons • Different rows or tables on different DB servers • Strengths • Scalable because data is split among servers • Consistency is easier because no copies • Weaknesses • Throughput: Single copy could be a bottleneck for frequently accessed data 19 Database replication • Multiple copies of the entire database 20 Database replication write • A write can access any copy and must be synchronized to other copies 21 Database replication read • A read can access any copy 22 Database replication pros and cons • Multiple copies of the entire database • Strengths • Throughput: Avoid bottlenecks through multiple copies • Weaknesses');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Storage', '2: Database replication 15 Sharding by content • Different rows or tables on different DB servers 16 Sharding by content write • A write modifies the only copy 17 Sharding by content read • A read accesses the only copy 18 Sharding by content pros and cons • Different rows or tables on different DB servers • Strengths • Scalable because data is split among servers • Consistency is easier because no copies • Weaknesses • Throughput: Single copy could be a bottleneck for frequently accessed data 19 Database replication • Multiple copies of the entire database 20 Database replication write • A write can access any copy and must be synchronized to other copies 21 Database replication read • A read can access any copy 22 Database replication pros and cons • Multiple copies of the entire database • Strengths • Throughput: Avoid bottlenecks through multiple copies • Weaknesses • Less scalable: Data might be too big to store on all servers • Consistency: Hard to keep copies in sync • Write to one needs to propagate to all the others • Moments of inconsistency, post shows up for some users and not others 23 Agenda • Distributed network database • Sharding by content, database replication • CAP Theorem • Practical database examples • Distributed file system for media uploads 24 CAP theorem overview • CAP theorem describes distributed database tradeoffs 25 CAP theorem: 3 properties • Consistency: Every read see latest write or an error • Availability: Every request gets a (non-error) response, without the guarantee that it contains the most recent write • Partition-tolerance: The system works despite network failure • CAP Theorem: Pick 2 of 3 26 Network with no failures • When the network is working correctly, you get Consistency and Availability • Database servers can synchronize • There is no partition 27 Network failure AKA partition 28 • When a network failure occurs, database servers cannot synchronize • This is a partition Network failure AKA partition • When a network failure occurs, database servers cannot synchronize • This is a partition • We have a choice • Return an incorrect value • Return an error 29 Available but not Consistent • Return an incorrect value when network is partitioned • Available but not Consistent 30 Consistent but not Available • Return an error when network is partitioned • Consistent but not Available 31 Which to choose? • Prioritize consistency over availability • Relational databases, AKA RDBMS or SQL • PostgreSQL: Synchronous replication • Banking • Prioritize availability over consistency • NoSQL databases • MongoDB: Primary is consistent, secondaries may be stale • Social media • Avoid the problem • Buy a giant server for your DB so there''s only one • Centralized network database 32 Agenda • Distributed network database • Sharding by content, database replication • CAP Theorem • Practical database examples • Distributed file system for media uploads 33 PostgreSQL • Traditional relational database • AKA "SQL" • AKA "RDMBS" • Good');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Storage', 'a choice • Return an incorrect value • Return an error 29 Available but not Consistent • Return an incorrect value when network is partitioned • Available but not Consistent 30 Consistent but not Available • Return an error when network is partitioned • Consistent but not Available 31 Which to choose? • Prioritize consistency over availability • Relational databases, AKA RDBMS or SQL • PostgreSQL: Synchronous replication • Banking • Prioritize availability over consistency • NoSQL databases • MongoDB: Primary is consistent, secondaries may be stale • Social media • Avoid the problem • Buy a giant server for your DB so there''s only one • Centralized network database 32 Agenda • Distributed network database • Sharding by content, database replication • CAP Theorem • Practical database examples • Distributed file system for media uploads 33 PostgreSQL • Traditional relational database • AKA "SQL" • AKA "RDMBS" • Good for consistency • Good for structured data 34 MongoDB • NoSQL database • Good for availability • Good for unstructured data 35 Agenda • Distributed network database • Sharding by content, database replication • CAP Theorem • Practical database examples • Distributed file system for media uploads 36 Media uploads and the database • Media uploads: Instagram photos, TikTok videos, etc. • Problem: Media uploads are expensive to store in a database • Solution: Store to disk • Write once, read many times. Don''t need a database to maintain consistency. 37 Scaling media uploads • Different dynamic pages servers on every request • Physical machines, virtual machines, containers • Problem: How do dynamic pages server disks stay in sync? • Solution: Dynamic pages servers are stateless. Store media uploads on network storage 38 Media storage implementation • Two subproblems for media storage • Problem 1: Store the files • Many files • Large size • Exabytes of data (10^18) • Problem 2: Serve the files • Many requests • Permissions control per-user 39 Store the files • Problem 1: Store files • Solution 1: Network file system • Solution 2: Distributed file system 40 Network file system • Network file system: Access files over the network much like local storage (hard drive) 41 Network file system PaaS • PaaS managed network file systems • AWS Elastic File System (EFS) • Google Filestore • Microsoft File Storage 42 Network file system pros and cons • Network file system acts like a local file system • Near zero client code changes • Problem 1: Speed and scalability • Problem 2: Fault tolerance. What happens when network file system server goes down? 43 Distributed file system • Distributed file system: Access files over the network, often with a special API • Reliable, scalable file storage implemented with commodity hardware • Google File System is an historical example 44 Distributed file system PaaS • PaaS managed distributed file systems • AWS S3 • Google Cloud Storage • Microsoft Blob Storage 45 Distributed file system pros and cons • Distributed file systems are more scalable');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Storage', 'system: Access files over the network much like local storage (hard drive) 41 Network file system PaaS • PaaS managed network file systems • AWS Elastic File System (EFS) • Google Filestore • Microsoft File Storage 42 Network file system pros and cons • Network file system acts like a local file system • Near zero client code changes • Problem 1: Speed and scalability • Problem 2: Fault tolerance. What happens when network file system server goes down? 43 Distributed file system • Distributed file system: Access files over the network, often with a special API • Reliable, scalable file storage implemented with commodity hardware • Google File System is an historical example 44 Distributed file system PaaS • PaaS managed distributed file systems • AWS S3 • Google Cloud Storage • Microsoft Blob Storage 45 Distributed file system pros and cons • Distributed file systems are more scalable and fault tolerant than network file systems • Distributed file systems often use a special API • Requires client code changes 46 Network FS vs. distributed FS • Technically, both are distributed systems • Optimized for different things • Network file system is optimized to be as similar as possible to traditional file system • Distributed file system is optimized for scale and reliability on unreliable hardware 47 Connecting dynamic pages servers to distributed file system • Our data is now stored in a distributed file system • User connects to dynamic pages web server • Problem: How do we upload and download? • Solution 1: Dynamic pages server is a middleman between client and distributed file system • Solution 2: Client connects directly to distributed file system 48 Media uploads proxy • Client sends upload to to dynamic pages server • Dynamic pages server sends upload to distributed file system • Example: AWS S3 • Dynamic pages server is "Middleman" or "proxy" 49 Media uploads proxy pros and cons • Easy to implement • Problem: Large file transfer goes through multiple servers. Higher latency, higher bandwidth • Solution: Direct upload 50 Direct upload • Direct upload from client to distributed file system • Dynamic pages server generates signed URL for client • Client uploads large file directly to distributed file system 51');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Scaling Storage', 'distributed file system • Dynamic pages server generates signed URL for client • Client uploads large file directly to distributed file system 51');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Recommender Systems', 'Recommender Systems Agenda • Introduction • User-based collaborative filtering • Content-based filtering • Historical examples 2 Introduction • Recommender Systems (e.g., Amazon, YouTube, Home Depot, etc.) predict what you''ll like • Put another way: they predict your preferences • What are some examples? 3 Example: Movies, shows • Netflix, Amazon, Hulu, et al. 4 Example: Music • Spotify, Apple Music, et al. 5 Example: Products • Amazon, Home Depot, et al. 6 Example: Videos • TikTok, YouTube, et al. 7 Recommendation challenges • Millions of users • Millions of items • Sparse data (most ratings missing) • Must run in real-time 8 Data collection • Explicit data collection • Ask users to rate movies, products, whatever • Ask users for demographic information • Implicit data collection • Web logs of past user activity • Timing information, e.g., how long you paused on a post before scrolling • Accounts you follow • Language and country settings 9 Agenda • Introduction • User-based collaborative filtering • Content-based filtering • Historical examples 10 Collaborative filtering • Problem: How to recommend movies without knowing anything about movies? • Solution: Recommend items liked by similar users. • People who agreed in the past will agree in the future 11 Averaging • Filling missing ratings using average of all users. 12 Averaging example 13 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob ? 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 ? Donna 3 ? 5 1 Averaging example 14 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob 3.66 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 2 Donna 3 2 5 1 Averaging problem • Problem: Averaging ignores uniqueness of a user • Terrible when there is large variation in interest • Movies, music are a few examples • Solution: Nearest neighbor algorithm 15 Nearest neighbor algorithm • Find another user with similar rating patterns • Movie ratings in this example • Use other user''s rating to "fill in the blank" • People who agreed in the past will agree in the future 16 Nearest neighbor example • Who are the nearest neighbors? 17 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob ? 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 ? Donna 3 ? 5 1 Nearest neighbor example • Bob''s nearest neighbor is Donna 18 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob ? 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 ? Donna 3 ? 5 1 Nearest neighbor example • Use Donna''s rating to fill in Bob''s 19 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob 3 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 ? Donna 3 ? 5 1 Nearest neighbor example • Chris''s nearest neighbor is Alice 20 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob 3 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 4 Donna 3 ? 5 1 Nearest neighbor example • Donna''s nearest neighbor is Bob 21 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob 3');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Recommender Systems', '17 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob ? 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 ? Donna 3 ? 5 1 Nearest neighbor example • Bob''s nearest neighbor is Donna 18 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob ? 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 ? Donna 3 ? 5 1 Nearest neighbor example • Use Donna''s rating to fill in Bob''s 19 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob 3 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 ? Donna 3 ? 5 1 Nearest neighbor example • Chris''s nearest neighbor is Alice 20 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob 3 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 4 Donna 3 ? 5 1 Nearest neighbor example • Donna''s nearest neighbor is Bob 21 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob 3 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 4 Donna 3 2 5 1 Distance metric • How to measure distance between neighbors? • Many possibilities, including • Euclidean - distance • Cosine – angle similarity • Pearson correlation coefficient • A lot in common with document vector model 22 K-nearest neighbors (k-NN) • Can we do better than selecting just one nearest neighbor? • Select several. 1. Find the k similar users instead of 1 2. Select the most frequent score (mode) 23 k-NN problems 1. Find the k similar users instead of 1 2. Select the most frequent score (mode) • How would a really popular film affect recommendations? 24 k-NN problems 1. Find the k closest users 2. Select the most frequent score • How would a really popular film affect recommendations? • The popular film will be recommended most of the time because it will often be the most frequent score • The popular choice might not always be the best choice for a user 25 k-NN problems • How would a "cult classic" film affect recommendations? • Enjoyed by a few, who REALLY like it • What could you do about this? 26 k-NN problems • How would a "cult classic" film affect recommendations? • Enjoyed by few, but they REALLY like it • Rare film less likely to be predicted by k-NN • Can use inverse-user-frequency • Similar to TFxIDF''s inverse document frequency • Rarely seen movies are more influential 27 User-based collaborative filtering weaknesses • Cold start • Need user data before you can start making accurate recommendations • Scalability • Millions of users • Large amount of computation power • Sparsity • Most users will only have rated a small subset of the overall database • Even the most popular items have very few ratings 28 Agenda • Introduction • User-based collaborative filtering • Content-based filtering • Historical examples 29 Motivation • Problems with user-based collaborative filtering • Cold start, scalability, sparsity • Solution: focus on content instead of users • Avoid nearest-neighbor operations on users 30 Content-based filtering • Content-based filtering: Recommend');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Recommender Systems', 'How would a "cult classic" film affect recommendations? • Enjoyed by few, but they REALLY like it • Rare film less likely to be predicted by k-NN • Can use inverse-user-frequency • Similar to TFxIDF''s inverse document frequency • Rarely seen movies are more influential 27 User-based collaborative filtering weaknesses • Cold start • Need user data before you can start making accurate recommendations • Scalability • Millions of users • Large amount of computation power • Sparsity • Most users will only have rated a small subset of the overall database • Even the most popular items have very few ratings 28 Agenda • Introduction • User-based collaborative filtering • Content-based filtering • Historical examples 29 Motivation • Problems with user-based collaborative filtering • Cold start, scalability, sparsity • Solution: focus on content instead of users • Avoid nearest-neighbor operations on users 30 Content-based filtering • Content-based filtering: Recommend items similar to items the user has liked in the past • People will like the same things in the future that they liked in the past 31 Content-based filtering synonyms • Content-based filtering • AKA Content-based collaborative filtering • AKA Item-based collaborative filtering • AKA "Users who bought x also bought y" 32 Content-based filtering • How can we compute item similarity? • Similar techniques to user-based collaborative filtering • Euclidean distance, cosine similarity, correlation, tf-idf • User-based filtering finds similar rows (users) • Content-based filtering finds similar columns (items) 33 Content-based filtering example • W. is most similar to Youngblood • Use likes W.? Recommend Youngblood 34 W. Panda Youngblood Zorro Alice 4 2 4 4 Bob 3 2 5 1 Chris 4 2 4 4 Donna 3 2 5 1 Content-based filtering weaknesses • Problem: Website doesn''t know all your preferences • You''ve rated horror movies on Netflix, but you also like comedies • Problem: Lost opportunity to introduce you to new content • Solution: Hybrid filtering 35 Hybrid filtering • Hybrid filtering: Combine user-based and content-based filtering • Netflix Example: • Recommendations based on similar users; AND • Recommendations based on shows user has rated highly 36 Agenda • Introduction • User-based collaborative filtering • Content-based filtering • Historical examples 37 Target and pregnancy prediction 1. Predict pregnancy 2. Recommend pregnancy related products 3. Father angry when teen daughter receives ads 4. Father finds out daughter is pregnant 38 Target and pregnancy prediction • Features were products • Unscented lotion, calcium, magnesium and zinc supplements • Sent ads through the mail • Story from 2012 39 Netflix prize • Announced October 2, 2006 • $1M to whoever could improve NetFlix''s own recommender by 10% • Data from Netflix in the form: • <user , movie, date, grade> • Where grade is 1...5 (today it''s just thumbs up/down) • That''s it • Training data: 100M examples from ~500k users on ~18k movies • Ideas for how you might do this? 40 Netflix prize • How did they do it? • Among many ideas: • Use IMDB for');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Recommender Systems', '36 Agenda • Introduction • User-based collaborative filtering • Content-based filtering • Historical examples 37 Target and pregnancy prediction 1. Predict pregnancy 2. Recommend pregnancy related products 3. Father angry when teen daughter receives ads 4. Father finds out daughter is pregnant 38 Target and pregnancy prediction • Features were products • Unscented lotion, calcium, magnesium and zinc supplements • Sent ads through the mail • Story from 2012 39 Netflix prize • Announced October 2, 2006 • $1M to whoever could improve NetFlix''s own recommender by 10% • Data from Netflix in the form: • <user , movie, date, grade> • Where grade is 1...5 (today it''s just thumbs up/down) • That''s it • Training data: 100M examples from ~500k users on ~18k movies • Ideas for how you might do this? 40 Netflix prize • How did they do it? • Among many ideas: • Use IMDB for director , genre, etc. • Some movies'' grades change when reviewers grade them in a clump, suggesting a long time has passed since the movie was viewed • User grades depend on day of week 41 Netflix prize • Dan Tillberg''s progress… • Dropped out in 2008 while in 5th place 42 Netflix prize • Won on September 21, 2009 43 Summary • User-based collaborative filtering: recommend items enjoyed by users who are similar to you • Content-based filtering: recommend items similar to items you have enjoyed in the past • Hybrid filtering: use both user- and content-based filtering at the same time 44');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Ads and Auctions', 'Ads and Auctions Slides by Raed Almomani and Andrew DeOrio Motivation • Ads are the business model behind most of the web • Google sponsored links, Facebook, Snapchat, Instagram, YouTube, etc 2 Selling ads before the web • Newspaper ads sold by size and placement • Bigger ads cost more • Different sections cost different $ • TV ads sold by time slot and show popularity • Different shows and different time of day cost different $ • Upfront season – a few months before fall when new shows are announced and advertisers can buy air time 3 Selling ads on the Web Before the Web: • Content known in advance • Ada bought ahead of time On the Web: • Content not known in advance • Ads are sold “just in time” • E.g., before every search on Google! • Use automated auctions to select the ad and price 4 Pay per click Before the Web: • Estimated audience size • Number of newspaper subscribers, TV viewers, etc. On the Web: • Measure audience more accurately • Record when a user clicks on the ad • Pay per click 5 Search engine advertising • Search engine advertising • AKA search engine marketing • Pay to be the top link 6 Display advertising • Display advertising • AKA Banner ads • Common in websites, apps, and social feeds • Can include images, text, or video 7 YouTube ads in action • 8 Agenda • Auctions in the real world • Auction types and terminology • Auction mathematical analysis • Auctions for selling ads 9 Real world auctions in action • • Cattle auction in Kansas • Bidding on the price in dollars per 100lb live weight 10 Real world auction observations • Auctions help many participants discover a price • No single actor needs to manually set that price • The same idea make auctions useful for web 11 Real world auction observations • Expensive to run an auction and get the attention of multiple potential buyers in a short window • Used for • Commodities, livestock • Art, antiques, rare items • Auctions become much cheaper to run online • Particularly if there is no human in loop 12 Agenda • Auctions in the real world • Auction types and terminology • Auction mathematical analysis • Auctions for selling ads 13 Auction mechanisms • Different auctions rules lead to different outcomes • Designing auction rules is called Mechanism design • Players AKA agents in an auction have different motives and strategies • Game theory helps us predict bidder behaviour 14 The players • A seller • Multiple bidders • An item being sold • Each bidder has a private valuation • Each bidder wants to win while paying as little as possible 15 The players: who knows what • Seller does not know the bidders'' valuations of the thing • Bidders do not know each others'' valuations • Yet the auction must still determine a price 16 Many kinds');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Ads and Auctions', 'rare items • Auctions become much cheaper to run online • Particularly if there is no human in loop 12 Agenda • Auctions in the real world • Auction types and terminology • Auction mathematical analysis • Auctions for selling ads 13 Auction mechanisms • Different auctions rules lead to different outcomes • Designing auction rules is called Mechanism design • Players AKA agents in an auction have different motives and strategies • Game theory helps us predict bidder behaviour 14 The players • A seller • Multiple bidders • An item being sold • Each bidder has a private valuation • Each bidder wants to win while paying as little as possible 15 The players: who knows what • Seller does not know the bidders'' valuations of the thing • Bidders do not know each others'' valuations • Yet the auction must still determine a price 16 Many kinds of auctions • Open auction: Everybody sees the bids • Ascending-price ("English" auction) • Descending-price ("Dutch" auction) • Sealed-bid auction: Bids are secret • First-price • Second-price (AKA "Vickrey" auction) 17 English auctions • Open, ascending-price auction • Price goes up and up, until only one bidder left • Winner pays the final standing price • Best-known type 18 Dutch auctions • Open, descending price auction • Price starts high and drops, until someone accepts • Common in flower auctions 19 Dutch auctions • Dutch Flower Auction • 20 Sealed bid auctions • Sealed-bid, first-price • Everyone bids silently, at once • Highest bid wins, and pays own bid • Sealed-bid, second-price ("Vickrey") • Everyone bids silently, at once • Highest bid wins, pays 2nd-highest bid 21 Agenda • Auctions in the real world • Auction types and terminology • Auction mathematical analysis • Auctions for selling ads 22 Analysis • Open, ascending-price (English) • Who wins? What does the winner pay? • What is the bidder’s likely strategy? • Sealed-bid second-price auction (Vickrey) • Who wins? What does the winner pay? • What is the bidder’s likely strategy? 23 Analysis • Open, ascending-price (English) • Who wins? What does the winner pay? • Bidder with highest value, pays about 2nd-highest value • What is the bidder’s likely strategy? • Bidder stays in until price is higher than bidder’s value • Sealed-bid second-price auction (Vickrey) • Who wins? What does the winner pay? • Bidder with highest value, pays 2nd-highest value • What is the bidder’s likely strategy? • Bidder bids true value • In both cases, winner is the bidder with highest value, pays 2nd-highest value • Technically, English auction winner pays 2nd-highest + minimum bid increment, assuming optimal strategy 24 Sealed-bid, second-price analysis • Sealed-Bid, 2nd-Price auctions (Vickrey) • How much should you bid? • True value? More? Less? 25 Sealed-bid, second-price analysis • If you bid above your value, you risk overpaying • If you bid below your value, your risk losing when you should have won • Therefor, bidding your true value is best 26 Sealed-bid,');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Ads and Auctions', 'the winner pay? • Bidder with highest value, pays about 2nd-highest value • What is the bidder’s likely strategy? • Bidder stays in until price is higher than bidder’s value • Sealed-bid second-price auction (Vickrey) • Who wins? What does the winner pay? • Bidder with highest value, pays 2nd-highest value • What is the bidder’s likely strategy? • Bidder bids true value • In both cases, winner is the bidder with highest value, pays 2nd-highest value • Technically, English auction winner pays 2nd-highest + minimum bid increment, assuming optimal strategy 24 Sealed-bid, second-price analysis • Sealed-Bid, 2nd-Price auctions (Vickrey) • How much should you bid? • True value? More? Less? 25 Sealed-bid, second-price analysis • If you bid above your value, you risk overpaying • If you bid below your value, your risk losing when you should have won • Therefor, bidding your true value is best 26 Sealed-bid, second-price analysis • Bid does not determine the price you pay • Bid determines whether you get to pay • 2nd-price auction bidders are "truthful” • Same with an open/ascending (English) auction • Assuming you follow the optimal strategy 27 Proxy bidding • eBay uses proxy bidding; Open auction • 1st-place bidder pays 2nd-place price • You submit a maximum bid • The system automatically bids just enough to keep you ahead 28 Proxy bidding example • Ru Paul the seller lists a backpack for sale on eBay with a minimum starting bid of $1 and a 5 day duration 29 Proxy bidding example Day 1 Current (public) bid: n/a; Minimum next bid: $1; Max: n/a. • The first bid is from Jack, who bids $10 even though the minimum is $1. Since there are no other bidders, eBay bids the minimum of $1 on Jack''s behalf and changes the minimum for any new bids to $1.25—the current bid of $1 plus the increment of $0.25. 30 Proxy bidding example Day 2 Current bid: $1; Minimum next bid: $1.25; Max: Jack, up to $10. • The second bid is from Jill, who bids $1.25. Because Jack''s $10 maximum was higher, eBay immediately bids $1.50 on Jack''s behalf ($1.25 plus one increment) and resets the minimum to $1.75 ($1.50 plus one increment). 31 Proxy bidding example Day 3 • Current bid: $1.50; Minimum next bid: $1.75; Max: Jack, up to $10. • Jill tries again, bidding $1.75. Jack''s maximum is still higher, so eBay immediately bids on his behalf again and adjusts the minimum accordingly. 32 Proxy bidding example Day 4 • Current bid: $2; Minimum next bid: $2.25; Max: Jack, up to $10. • Frustrated, Jill tries a fourth time, bidding $16.50. This is higher than Jack''s maximum, so eBay sets the current bid to $10.50 (Jack''s maximum plus one increment). Jill is now the high bidder and eBay is bidding automatically on her behalf. 33 Proxy bidding example Day 5 • Current bid: $10.50; Minimum next bid: $11; Max: Jill, up to $16.50. • During the final moments of');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Ads and Auctions', 'eBay immediately bids $1.50 on Jack''s behalf ($1.25 plus one increment) and resets the minimum to $1.75 ($1.50 plus one increment). 31 Proxy bidding example Day 3 • Current bid: $1.50; Minimum next bid: $1.75; Max: Jack, up to $10. • Jill tries again, bidding $1.75. Jack''s maximum is still higher, so eBay immediately bids on his behalf again and adjusts the minimum accordingly. 32 Proxy bidding example Day 4 • Current bid: $2; Minimum next bid: $2.25; Max: Jack, up to $10. • Frustrated, Jill tries a fourth time, bidding $16.50. This is higher than Jack''s maximum, so eBay sets the current bid to $10.50 (Jack''s maximum plus one increment). Jill is now the high bidder and eBay is bidding automatically on her behalf. 33 Proxy bidding example Day 5 • Current bid: $10.50; Minimum next bid: $11; Max: Jill, up to $16.50. • During the final moments of the auction, a new bidder named Tim bids the minimum of $11. eBay automatically bids on Jill''s behalf, outbidding Tim by one increment at $11.50. 34 Proxy bidding example End • Winning bid: $11.50; Winner: Jill. • The auction ends after exactly five days. Jill is the highest bidder and wins, not for $16.50 (her maximum bid), but for $11.50 (one increment higher than her nearest competitor''s bid). 35 Sniping • Sniping uses software to bid • Sniping places a bid at the last possible moment; avoid giving competitors time to respond. • What would happen if everyone sniped? 36 Sniping analysis • What would happen if everyone sniped? • If everyone waits until the end, bids become effectively sealed. • Sniping effectively turns a Proxy Bidding auction into a Vickrey Auction, because it "seals" the bids 37 Sealed-bid, first-price analysis • Sealed-Bid, 1st-Price Analysis • What is the bidder’s likely strategy? 38 Sealed-bid, first-price analysis • Sealed-Bid, 1st-Price Analysis • What is the bidder’s likely strategy? • In a first-price auction, your bid determines your payment. • Bidding your full value may leave little or no benefit • So bidders usually bid below their true value. 39 Agenda • Auctions in the real world • Auction types and terminology • Auction mathematical analysis • Auctions for selling ads 40 Pay-per-click (PPC) auctions • Auctions determine which ads you see 41 Overture pay-per-click auctions • Overture was the first company to do text search ads, even before Google! • Bought by Yahoo in 2003 • Bidders purchase "keywords" • Ads displayed in order, highest first • If the user clicks the ad, high bidder pays bid price • User can click on many, or no, ads • Bids are visible to other bidders • First-price, open auction 42 Overture example • Three parties bid on the keyword "eecs485" 43 $1 $2 $3 Overture example • R2D2 is pos #1 • He bids $3, pays $3 upon user click • Neytiri is pos #2 • She bids $2, pays $2 upon user click • ET is pos #3 • He bids');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Ads and Auctions', 'Auctions in the real world • Auction types and terminology • Auction mathematical analysis • Auctions for selling ads 40 Pay-per-click (PPC) auctions • Auctions determine which ads you see 41 Overture pay-per-click auctions • Overture was the first company to do text search ads, even before Google! • Bought by Yahoo in 2003 • Bidders purchase "keywords" • Ads displayed in order, highest first • If the user clicks the ad, high bidder pays bid price • User can click on many, or no, ads • Bids are visible to other bidders • First-price, open auction 42 Overture example • Three parties bid on the keyword "eecs485" 43 $1 $2 $3 Overture example • R2D2 is pos #1 • He bids $3, pays $3 upon user click • Neytiri is pos #2 • She bids $2, pays $2 upon user click • ET is pos #3 • He bids $1, pays $1 upon user click • What should R2D2 do? 44 Overture example • R2D2 is pos #1 • He bids $3, pays $3 upon user click • Neytiri is pos #2 • She bids $2, pays $2 upon user click • ET is pos #3 • He bids $1, pays $1 upon user click • What should R2D2 do? • Decrease bid to $2.01, and save $0.99 per click 45 Overture example • R2D2 is pos #1 • He bids $2.01, pays $2.01 upon user click • Neytiri is pos #2 • She bids $2, pays $2 upon user click • ET is pos #3 • He bids $1, pays $1 upon user click • What should Neytiri do? • Increase bid to $2.02: with just $0.02 more per click, she can get first position!! 46 Overture example • Neytiri is pos #1 • She bids $2.02, pays $2.02 upon user click • R2D2 is pos #2 • He bids $2.01, pays $2.01 upon user click • ET is pos #3 • He bids $1, pays $1 upon user click • What happens next? 47 Overture example • It’s advantageous to change your bid rapidly • Pay enough to be on top, but no more • Has some bad social effects: lots of time/money spent on bidding 48 Google Ads for search • A few critical differences: • Sealed-bid • 2nd-price payment • Competitors'' bids are hidden 49 Google Ads example • Neytiri is pos #1 • She bids $3.00, but pays $2.01 upon click • R2D2 is pos #2 • He bids $2.00, pays $1.01 upon click • ET is pos #3 • He bids $1, pays minimum • Great! But… 50 Google Ads example • Unlike Overture, Google auction prices are kept secret. You don’t know what other people bid. • But you can guess. What if R2D2 changes his bid to $2.75? 51 Google Ads example • Neytiri is pos #1 • She bids $3.00, but pays $2.76 upon click. • Her cost increased due to R2D2! • R2D2 is pos #2 • He bids');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Ads and Auctions', 'to be on top, but no more • Has some bad social effects: lots of time/money spent on bidding 48 Google Ads for search • A few critical differences: • Sealed-bid • 2nd-price payment • Competitors'' bids are hidden 49 Google Ads example • Neytiri is pos #1 • She bids $3.00, but pays $2.01 upon click • R2D2 is pos #2 • He bids $2.00, pays $1.01 upon click • ET is pos #3 • He bids $1, pays minimum • Great! But… 50 Google Ads example • Unlike Overture, Google auction prices are kept secret. You don’t know what other people bid. • But you can guess. What if R2D2 changes his bid to $2.75? 51 Google Ads example • Neytiri is pos #1 • She bids $3.00, but pays $2.76 upon click. • Her cost increased due to R2D2! • R2D2 is pos #2 • He bids $2.75, still pays $1.01 upon click • ET is pos #3 • He bids $1, pays minimum 52 Google Ads example • More differences: • Displayed ads ranked depends on both: • Bid amount • Ad-quality • Click-through rates (CTR): how often people click your ad • Google was originally the "cheap competitor" to Overture, then overtook 53 Google Ads caveats • Google AdWords is not exactly Vickrey auction • Standard Vickrey auctions sell one item • Google sells multiple items • This is called Generalized Second Price auction • What if you want two items, but if you can''t get them both, you want neither? • E.g., cotton candy machine + 32 tons of raw cotton candy 54 Summary • Auctions are automated on the web • Primarily used to sell ads • Sellers with ad platforms like Google, Facebook, etc. • Buyers who want to advertise • Enable just-in-time ad sales customized to users 55');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Blockchain', 'Blockchain Slides by Andrew DeOrio and Mike Cafarella, with some slides from Joseph Bonneau and Eric Wustrow. Some technical content from “The Economics of Bitcoin, or Bitcoin in the Presence of Adversaries”. Blockchain • Blockchain is a shared database with no central owner. Everyone keeps a copy and updates requires agreement. • Many uses for a blockchain • Bitcoin cryptocurrency was the first • 2 Agenda • Background: currency crash course • Bitcoin • Blockchain • Mining • Altcoins • Summary 3 Traditional currency • What is money? • Currency is a medium of exchange • A convenient way to buy and sell stuff • Easier than bartering "I''ll fix your laptop if you give me one dozen eggs." • Easier than carting around Gold bullion 4 Fiat currency • Fiat money is a currency without intrinsic value • Often created by government regulation • It''s valuable because two parties agree it has value 5 Digital currency • Digital currency is currency available in digital form • Example: Bank deposit • After deposit, the money exists only as a number on the bank''s balance sheet • You can spend it by transferring it, e.g., to pay a credit card bill 6 Central bank • In the U.S., the central bank is the Federal Reserve • "Fed" for short • Decides how much money exists, e.g., when to print money • Bank used by banks • Lends money to banks • Another digital currency example: central bank reserve • Money exists as a number on the central bank''s balance sheet 7 Central bank • A central bank is centrally controlled • Example: the U.S. controls how much U.S. Dollars are worth AKA how many there are • If the Fed wants more dollars, the Fed can print more • Print more dollars. Don''t even need to print them. Just increase the number on the balance sheet. • Quantitative easing 8 Agenda • Background: currency crash course • Bitcoin • Blockchain • Mining • Altcoins • Summary 9 Bitcoin • First decentralized digital currency • First cryptocurrency • No central authority • Solves “double spending” problem • Uses cryptography and distributed systems 10 Bitcoin Bitcoin is also ... • A get-rich-quick scheme • A fiat currency without a government behind it • A handy resource for criminals • The future of money… maybe? 11 Satoshi Nakamoto • Created in 2008 under pseudonym Satoshi Nakamoto • 2008: Nakamoto posted: “Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System” to a cryptography mailing list • Code released 2009 • Identity unknown • 2010 Nakamoto disappears after mining about 1,000,000 BTC 12 Gov''t backed currency vs. Bitcoin Government backed • Analog and digital • Fiat currency • Centralized • Controlled by a central bank • Represented by a single bank ledger Bitcoin • Digital • Fiat currency • Decentralized • Controlled by a distributed algorithm • Represented by shared ledger 13 Bitcoin basics • A bitcoin is a digital asset • A Bitcoin address is a public key');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Blockchain', 'Solves “double spending” problem • Uses cryptography and distributed systems 10 Bitcoin Bitcoin is also ... • A get-rich-quick scheme • A fiat currency without a government behind it • A handy resource for criminals • The future of money… maybe? 11 Satoshi Nakamoto • Created in 2008 under pseudonym Satoshi Nakamoto • 2008: Nakamoto posted: “Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System” to a cryptography mailing list • Code released 2009 • Identity unknown • 2010 Nakamoto disappears after mining about 1,000,000 BTC 12 Gov''t backed currency vs. Bitcoin Government backed • Analog and digital • Fiat currency • Centralized • Controlled by a central bank • Represented by a single bank ledger Bitcoin • Digital • Fiat currency • Decentralized • Controlled by a distributed algorithm • Represented by shared ledger 13 Bitcoin basics • A bitcoin is a digital asset • A Bitcoin address is a public key (AKA Bitcoin Wallet) • Whoever has the matching private key controls that bitcoin • To send bitcoin, the owner signs a transaction transferring it to another address • Ownership is tracked through a chain of digitally signed transactions 14 Spending Bitcoin • Alice pays Bob • Alice signs transaction and broadcasts it to all Bitcoin nodes • All nodes must agree on a sequence of transactions • Added to Blockchain • Sequence is Blockchain • Process of agreement is Bitcoin mining Pay to pkBob : H( ) signed by Alice 15 Bitcoin and anonymity • Bitcoin is NOT anonymous • Everyone can see every Bitcoin transaction • It''s a distributed public ledger • No one can see who owns each public key • Unless you tell them • This is called pseudo anonymous 16 Blockchain tracing • If I find out John Doe’s public key, what can I learn? • If I know the Bitcoin wallet public key of a Darknet market vendor selling illegal goods, what can I learn? 17 Blockchain tracing • If I find out John Doe’s public key, what can I learn? • Every transaction he’s ever done • Other party’s Bitcoin wallet public key • Bitcoin public key for markets are well known • E.g., if he bought something from a Darknet Market • If I know the Bitcoin wallet public key of a Darknet market vendor selling illegal goods, what can I learn? • All their customers, ever • Other party’s Bitcoin wallet public key • Blockchain tracing AKA blockchain analysis 18 Agenda • Background: currency crash course • Bitcoin • Blockchain • Mining • Altcoins • Summary 19 Double spending • Double spending: Same money spent twice. • In US, ACH system prevents double spending BANKAlice Bob Charlie Redeem X? Redeem X? Somebody else 20 Double spending • With traditional banking, avoid double spending by checking the account''s balance • Centralized balance sheet • ACH system for transferring money • Verify identity of the sender and recipient bank • Verify account amounts • Federal Reserve runs network 21 Double spending • If you');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Blockchain', 'Bitcoin public key for markets are well known • E.g., if he bought something from a Darknet Market • If I know the Bitcoin wallet public key of a Darknet market vendor selling illegal goods, what can I learn? • All their customers, ever • Other party’s Bitcoin wallet public key • Blockchain tracing AKA blockchain analysis 18 Agenda • Background: currency crash course • Bitcoin • Blockchain • Mining • Altcoins • Summary 19 Double spending • Double spending: Same money spent twice. • In US, ACH system prevents double spending BANKAlice Bob Charlie Redeem X? Redeem X? Somebody else 20 Double spending • With traditional banking, avoid double spending by checking the account''s balance • Centralized balance sheet • ACH system for transferring money • Verify identity of the sender and recipient bank • Verify account amounts • Federal Reserve runs network 21 Double spending • If you receive a Bitcoin, you can cryptographically verify the signatures • But how can you verify that no double-spending took place? Alice BobSignA(Transfer X to B) CharlieSignA(Transfer X to C) SignZ(Transfer X to A) Redeem X? Redeem X? 22 Distributed ledger • Distributed alternative to bank''s centralized balance sheet • Bitcoin participants engage in peer-to-peer protocol that shares transaction history • They collectively build a log of every Bitcoin transaction, ever • The log is built from blocks • Everyone keeps a copy • Append-only (no delete/edit) 23 Distributed ledger • Blockchain is essentially a shared database • Multiple writers • No trust required 24 Blocks • Transactions grouped into blocks • Each block has: • A sequence id • A timestamp • A nonce • Cryptographic hash of the previous block • Various metadata fields • Some actual transactions! 25 Blockchain • Blocks connected in a blockchain • There’s always a backward hash link; eventually you can traverse it all the way back to the “genesis block” • The set of blocks form a tree, with the genesis block at the root; possibly multiple branches 26 The blockchain in action • Suppose Alice wants to give Bitcoins to Bob • Alice creates and signs a transaction object that transfers the Bitcoin from herself to Bob • She sends it to all peers in a peer-to-peer network • The peers rebroadcast it, so soon, everyone knows about the transaction • Any participant who also mines on the blockchain can now attempt to create a block that contains all the transactions known (including Alice’s transfer) • If this works, then the Alice-> Bob transfer is added to the global shared log of transactions 27 Agenda • Background: currency crash course • Bitcoin • Blockchain • Mining • Altcoins • Summary 28 Motivating Bitcoin miners • Who runs the distributed ledger? • Bitcoin miners are paid to operate the blockchain • Run servers • Block creator is allowed to insert some reward Bitcoin transactions • This is how miners earn Bitcoins, and how Bitcoins are created 29 Blockchain • Bitcoin design decisions focus');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Blockchain', 'Alice creates and signs a transaction object that transfers the Bitcoin from herself to Bob • She sends it to all peers in a peer-to-peer network • The peers rebroadcast it, so soon, everyone knows about the transaction • Any participant who also mines on the blockchain can now attempt to create a block that contains all the transactions known (including Alice’s transfer) • If this works, then the Alice-> Bob transfer is added to the global shared log of transactions 27 Agenda • Background: currency crash course • Bitcoin • Blockchain • Mining • Altcoins • Summary 28 Motivating Bitcoin miners • Who runs the distributed ledger? • Bitcoin miners are paid to operate the blockchain • Run servers • Block creator is allowed to insert some reward Bitcoin transactions • This is how miners earn Bitcoins, and how Bitcoins are created 29 Blockchain • Bitcoin design decisions focus on building and maintaining a blockchain that is agreed-upon • Rewards keep system honest • Encourages consensus 30 Proof-of-work • Goal: reject fake blocks • Whoever solves a proof-of-work puzzle adds new block • Gets reward • Proof-of-work is to compute, easy to validate 31 Proof-of-stake • Goal: reject fake blocks • Whoever has the largest proof-of-stake adds new block • Gets reward • Miners must hold and stake tokens for the privilege of earning transaction fees • Fake transactions and lose your staked coin • Ethereum et al. 32 Blockchain • Why give miners such strong incentives to formulate blocks? • Bring more mining power online • Reduces anyone’s ability to forge an alternate history blockchain • You can start to ignore transactions if you control 51% of the hashing power 33 Bitcoin reward function • Block reward halves every ~4 years 34 Energy consumption • Current estimates: ~70 TWh / yr • Enough to power ~7 million households • Hardware is changing • Mining equipment: anything from normal CPU -> dedicated ASIC datacenter • Power generation is changing • Coal, natural gas, wind, solar , hydroelectric 35 Source: Energy consumption • Why make the task so hard? Why proof-of-work? • It caps the rate at which new Bitcoins can be added • In other words, prevents runaway inflation 36 Agenda • Background: currency crash course • Bitcoin • Blockchain • Mining • Altcoins • Summary 37 Altcoins • Altcoins are alternative cryptocurrencies, launched after Bitcoin • Different blockchains offering different features 38 /coins/altcoin retrieved 12/03/2024 Cryptocurrency exchange • A cryptocurrency exchange allows customers to • Bus/sell crypto • Convert to cash • Examples: Poloniex, Bitfinex, Coinbase, Binance 39 Decentralized currency, centralized exchange • Crypto exchanges are centralized • Example: exchanging Bitcoin for Ethereum 1. Alice sends Bitcoin to Bitfinex 2. Bob sends Ethererum to Bitfinex 3. Bitfinex makes the trade and takes a cut 4. Bitfinex send Ethereum to Alice 5. Bitfinex sends Bitcoin to Bob • Both parties must trust Bitfinex • What could possibly go wrong? 40 41 Wall Street Journal, Nov. 2, 2023 Different blockchain');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Blockchain', 'proof-of-work? • It caps the rate at which new Bitcoins can be added • In other words, prevents runaway inflation 36 Agenda • Background: currency crash course • Bitcoin • Blockchain • Mining • Altcoins • Summary 37 Altcoins • Altcoins are alternative cryptocurrencies, launched after Bitcoin • Different blockchains offering different features 38 /coins/altcoin retrieved 12/03/2024 Cryptocurrency exchange • A cryptocurrency exchange allows customers to • Bus/sell crypto • Convert to cash • Examples: Poloniex, Bitfinex, Coinbase, Binance 39 Decentralized currency, centralized exchange • Crypto exchanges are centralized • Example: exchanging Bitcoin for Ethereum 1. Alice sends Bitcoin to Bitfinex 2. Bob sends Ethererum to Bitfinex 3. Bitfinex makes the trade and takes a cut 4. Bitfinex send Ethereum to Alice 5. Bitfinex sends Bitcoin to Bob • Both parties must trust Bitfinex • What could possibly go wrong? 40 41 Wall Street Journal, Nov. 2, 2023 Different blockchain features • One reason to create a different cryptocurrency: different blockchain with different features • Alternative proof of work • Faster block times / larger block sizes • Alternative transaction types • Computable “smart contract” transactions • Anonymous / Private transactions 42 Ethereum – Smart Contracts • Altcoin (ETH) • Smart contract is a computer program stored on the blockchain • Cannot be changed once deployed • Automatically executes based on its code 43 NFTs • Non-Fungible T oken (NFT): individually unique and provably scarce digital signature • Used to validate ownership • Analogous to a deed for digital goods • Implemented with Ethereum smart contracts • Uses Ethereum blockchain • E.g., a digital signature that says you own the JPG that hashes to 0x123ABC 44 Agenda • Background: currency crash course • Bitcoin • Blockchain • Mining • Altcoins • Summary 45 Reasons for cryptocurrencies • Distrust in centralized banks or governments • Predictable policy • Code and protocols instead of malleable laws • Removing financial gatekeepers 46 Reasons against cryptocurrencies • Should we trust anonymous people on the Internet? • What about bugs in code? • Does replacing financial gatekeepers with code mean that things will never change? • Large power consumption causes environmental concerns • Maybe proof-of-stake will help? 47 Blockchain summary • A distributed database with a shared protocol for multiple writers who don’t trust each other or a central authority • Blockchain useful when • Database is shared with multiple writers • Users don’t trust each other • Users don’t trust a central authority • Cryptocurrency is just one way to use a blockchain 48');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'Blockchain', '• Large power consumption causes environmental concerns • Maybe proof-of-stake will help? 47 Blockchain summary • A distributed database with a shared protocol for multiple writers who don’t trust each other or a central authority • Blockchain useful when • Database is shared with multiple writers • Users don’t trust each other • Users don’t trust a central authority • Cryptocurrency is just one way to use a blockchain 48');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'DarkWeb', 'Dark Web Slides by Andrew DeOrio Agenda • Introduction • Review • VPN proxies • Tor • Tor services • Tor browser • Tor history 2 The dark web • Part of the Web accessible only through anonymous tools (e.g. Tor Browser) 3 4 Dark web vs. deep web • Deep web: pages that search engines can''t find • Pages behind paywalls, e.g., Wall Street Journal • Pages behind passwords, e.g., Gmail, Facebook, online banking • Dark web: pages accessible only through anonymous tools • The deep web includes the dark web 5 Anonymity online • Is anonymous browsing mode enough for anonymity online? • Private browsing mode, incognito mode, etc. • What about HTTPS? • Is that enough? Why? 6 Anonymity online 7 Agenda • Introduction • Review • VPN proxies • Tor • Tor services • Tor browser • Tor history 8 Review: Network communication • Two parties communicate over the internet • Example: client visits amazon.com 9 Review: Example message from client to server 10 Review: IP Address • There are lots of computers connected to the internet • Problem: How to tell them apart? • Solution: IP Address • Every computer on the Internet has an address • Google 172.217.5.14 • Amazon 205.251.242.103 • My laptop 35.7.33.89 11 Review: Internet routers 12 Neither sender nor receiver control the routers in the middle! Reivew: Eavesdropping • Someone else listens to what you send • HTTPS means they can''t understand it, but... • NSA data center near SLC: "An article by Forbes estimates the storage capacity as between 3 and 12 exabytes in the near term, based on analysis of unclassified blueprints" (Wikipedia) 13 14 January 25, 2024 Review: Network security • Two parties communicate over a network • Assume powerful adversary • Can read (eavesdrop on) all data transmitted • Can modify or delete any data • Can inject new data • Communication: What properties would you like? 15 Review: Desirable properties • Confidentiality • Adversary should not understand message • Solved with symmetric encryption • Sender authenticity • Message is really from the purported sender • Solved with asymmetric encryption and public key infrastructure (PKI) • Message integrity • Message not modified between send and receive • Solved with symmetric encryption 16 Review: Desirable properties • Freshness • Message was sent “recently” • Solved with symmetric encryption and timestamp, sequence number or nonce • Anonymity • Attacker should not know that we are communicating • Solved with VPN (weak) or Tor (strong) 17 Motivation • We’ve already solved the problem of private message content • Symmetric and asymmetric encryption • Today we’ll solve the problem of private message metadata • Source IP and destination IP 18 Agenda • Introduction • Review • VPN proxies • Tor • Tor services • Tor browser • Tor history 19 Review: Packets • Message broken down into packets by sender • ~1kB – 1.5kB 20 Packet inspection • Each packet has source IP & destination IP • If you change');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'DarkWeb', 'Solved with asymmetric encryption and public key infrastructure (PKI) • Message integrity • Message not modified between send and receive • Solved with symmetric encryption 16 Review: Desirable properties • Freshness • Message was sent “recently” • Solved with symmetric encryption and timestamp, sequence number or nonce • Anonymity • Attacker should not know that we are communicating • Solved with VPN (weak) or Tor (strong) 17 Motivation • We’ve already solved the problem of private message content • Symmetric and asymmetric encryption • Today we’ll solve the problem of private message metadata • Source IP and destination IP 18 Agenda • Introduction • Review • VPN proxies • Tor • Tor services • Tor browser • Tor history 19 Review: Packets • Message broken down into packets by sender • ~1kB – 1.5kB 20 Packet inspection • Each packet has source IP & destination IP • If you change destination, routers won’t deliver it to the right place • Can sometimes change source (spoofing) but not always 21 Packet inspection • Packet source and destination are visible to anyone observing the network 22 Image: HTTP or HTTPS Metadata • Packet source and destination are visible to anyone observing the network • Your ISP • Destination web site • Any intermediate router • Network eavesdropper • Simply knowing two parties are communicating reveals info • Metadata 23 Metadata • They know you rang a phone sex line at 2:24 am and spoke for 18 minutes. But they don''t know what you talked about. • They know you called the suicide prevention hotline from the Golden Gate Bridge. But the topic of the call remains a secret. • They know you got an email from an HIV testing service, then called your doctor, then visited an HIV support group website in the same hour. But they don''t know what was in the email or what you talked about on the phone. • They know you received an email from a digital rights activist group with the subject line “Let’s Tell Congress: Stop SESTA/FOSTA” and then called your elected representative immediately after. But the content of those communications remains safe from government intrusion. • They know you called a gynecologist, spoke for a half hour, and then called the local abortion clinic’s number later that day. 24 -metadata-matters Proxy server • Proxy server is a middleman • Makes your internet traffic appear to come from somewhere else • Hides your IP address 25 VPN proxy server • VPN proxy server hides your IP address and encrypts your traffic 26 Any application on your computer Source IP: Your IP Dest. IP: Proxy Server IP Final Dest.: encrypted. Source IP: Proxy Server IP Dest. IP: Final Server IP VPN proxy server • Eavesdropper can see client communicate with VPN proxy • Eavesdropper can see VPN communicate with Web site 27 Any application on your computer VPN proxy server vulnerabilities • Single point of failure: VPN knows all • VPN proxy servers vulnerable to subpoenas');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'DarkWeb', 'But the content of those communications remains safe from government intrusion. • They know you called a gynecologist, spoke for a half hour, and then called the local abortion clinic’s number later that day. 24 -metadata-matters Proxy server • Proxy server is a middleman • Makes your internet traffic appear to come from somewhere else • Hides your IP address 25 VPN proxy server • VPN proxy server hides your IP address and encrypts your traffic 26 Any application on your computer Source IP: Your IP Dest. IP: Proxy Server IP Final Dest.: encrypted. Source IP: Proxy Server IP Dest. IP: Final Server IP VPN proxy server • Eavesdropper can see client communicate with VPN proxy • Eavesdropper can see VPN communicate with Web site 27 Any application on your computer VPN proxy server vulnerabilities • Single point of failure: VPN knows all • VPN proxy servers vulnerable to subpoenas • Court asks proxy server admin for server logs • Some VPNs have a "destroy logs" policy • You''d have to trust your VPN 28 VPN proxy server vulnerabilities • VPN proxy servers vulnerable to misconfiguration • It''s easy to screw up VPN server configuration • Out-of-date software with security vulnerabilities leads to exfiltrating data • Doesn''t support IPv6, and IPv6 requests are leaked • ... and many others 29 VPNalyzer • Tool from UM to evaluate VPN security • Only 4 recommended vendors! • Mullvad • PIA • IVPN • Mozilla VPN 30 -lab-wp.consumerreports.org/wp -content/uploads/2021/12/VPN -White-Paper.pdf VPN proxy server vulnerabilities • VPN proxy servers are vulnerable to traffic analysis • Even if you can trust your VPN and it''s configured correctly! • What if every time client transmits, web site soon gets data? • Your ISP or other eavesdroppers can use traffic analysis even with a VPN and SSL 31 Traffic analysis • Every time you transmit, VPN transmits • Gather a bunch of data • Only need to monitor two points on the network • Correlate these two 32 Tor vs. VPN details: Agenda • Introduction • Review • VPN proxies • Tor • Tor services • Tor browser • Tor history 33 Tor • The Onion Router • Used to fight traffic analysis 34 35 More detail: 36 More detail: 37 More detail: Tor • Tor encrypts outgoing data multiple times, like layers of an onion • One encryption layer for each step in the relay • Each layer of encryption is peeled off by a relay node in the network. At each layer: • Decrypt the current layer • Forward to the next destination 38 Tor vulnerabilities • Only the first relay node knows the source IP • Only the last relay node knows the destination IP • To break anonymity, you need to surveil many nodes in the Tor circuit 39 -is-running-hundreds-of-malicious-servers-on-the-1848156630 Statistical correlation attack • Let’s say that Elmo and Abby use Tor regularly • You control their ISP and collect frequent traffic logs with timestamps • Also control the ISP for ILoveBigBird.com and');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'DarkWeb', 'browser • Tor history 33 Tor • The Onion Router • Used to fight traffic analysis 34 35 More detail: 36 More detail: 37 More detail: Tor • Tor encrypts outgoing data multiple times, like layers of an onion • One encryption layer for each step in the relay • Each layer of encryption is peeled off by a relay node in the network. At each layer: • Decrypt the current layer • Forward to the next destination 38 Tor vulnerabilities • Only the first relay node knows the source IP • Only the last relay node knows the destination IP • To break anonymity, you need to surveil many nodes in the Tor circuit 39 -is-running-hundreds-of-malicious-servers-on-the-1848156630 Statistical correlation attack • Let’s say that Elmo and Abby use Tor regularly • You control their ISP and collect frequent traffic logs with timestamps • Also control the ISP for ILoveBigBird.com and DownWithBigBird.org • You also collect frequent traffic logs with timestamps • How can you tell who is pro-BigBird vs anti-BigBird? • With enough log data, you can perform statistical correlation attack 40 Statistical correlation attack • How to prevent statistical correlation attack? • Elmo and Abby always transmit data to Tor once per second • If no data to send, just send NULL or random data • More Tor users conducting more activity on Tor reduces vulnerability 41 Agenda • Introduction • Review • VPN proxies • Tor • Tor browser • Tor services • Tor history 42 Missing link • Client can browse anonymously with Tor connection • Server can publish anonymously with Tor services • Is that enough? • Session cookies, including third party trackers are ubiquitous • Your browser reveal you 43 Cookies 44 Third-party cookies • Page may contain objects from many sources • Scripts, images, etc. • These 3rd-party objects set and get cookies • Example: nytimes.com <html> <head> <script src="https:// tags.bluekai.com/site/50550?ret=js&limit=1" type="text/javascript" > </script> </head> <body> <img src=" /newsgraphics/2018/01/18/shutdown-deal- factions/assets/images/lindsey-graham.png"> </body> </html> 45 Example: Google third party cookies 46 Example: Google third party cookies 47 Example: Google third party cookies 48 Example: Google third party cookies 49 Avoiding trackers • Add-ons like uBlock Origin, Privacy Badger, Brave, Disconnect or ScriptNo block trackers • Monitors embedded links and blacklists trackers 50 Tor browser • Routes all traffic via Tor • Modified Firefox • Essential privacy plugins • NoScript and HTTPS Everywhere • Non-tracking search engine • DuckDuckGo • Alternative: Brave Browser ships with Tor integration 51 Browser fingerprinting • Torbrowser avoids browser fingerprinting • Browser fingerprinting: collect enough information from a client, you can (probably) identify them uniquely • User-Agent string • Screen size • Browser plugin details • Language • Platform • Etc. 52 Not anonymous browsing • We''ve talked about more anonymous browsing • Tor Browser and Duck Duck Go are a good start • What about less anonymous browsing? • Google Chrome tracks you, even in incognito mode • Google search engine tracks you with Google login, third party cookies and Chrome!');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'DarkWeb', 'party cookies 49 Avoiding trackers • Add-ons like uBlock Origin, Privacy Badger, Brave, Disconnect or ScriptNo block trackers • Monitors embedded links and blacklists trackers 50 Tor browser • Routes all traffic via Tor • Modified Firefox • Essential privacy plugins • NoScript and HTTPS Everywhere • Non-tracking search engine • DuckDuckGo • Alternative: Brave Browser ships with Tor integration 51 Browser fingerprinting • Torbrowser avoids browser fingerprinting • Browser fingerprinting: collect enough information from a client, you can (probably) identify them uniquely • User-Agent string • Screen size • Browser plugin details • Language • Platform • Etc. 52 Not anonymous browsing • We''ve talked about more anonymous browsing • Tor Browser and Duck Duck Go are a good start • What about less anonymous browsing? • Google Chrome tracks you, even in incognito mode • Google search engine tracks you with Google login, third party cookies and Chrome! • Middle ground: • Brave Browser or Firefox • Duck Duck Go instead of Google 53 • Brave • Firefox • Safari • Duck Duck Go search engine • Better privacy protections, even without Tor Browser recommendations 54 Agenda • Introduction • Review • VPN proxies • Tor • Tor browser • Tor services • Tor history 55 Anonymous servers • So far, we''ve talked about a client can browse anonymously • Problem: How do you run a server anonymously? • Solution: Tor services 56 Tor services • Tor allows users to anonymously publish services • E.g., web pages, or a chat server • Service locations (rendezvous points) must be known to clients • Even though censors may want to locate, take down services • Key idea: layer of indirection • Introduction points are Tor nodes that relay traffic from clients to services 57 More detail: Finding Tor services • Curated lists • Reddit • Hidden Wiki • ... and many others • Hidden service search engines • Ahmia • Torch • Not Evil • ... and many others • Search engine crawlers on dark web • Conventional crawlers can''t reach dark web • Route crawler GET requests to .onion sites through Tor 58 Agenda • Introduction • Review • VPN proxies • Tor • Tor services • Tor browser • Tor history 59 Tor history • Developed by US Naval Research Laboratory • Goal: protect US intelligence communications online • Now a nonprofit • US Government is a major funder 60 More uses for Tor • Break censorship barriers • E.g., in places that censor web content • Political activism • E.g., in places that discourage free speech • Net neutrality • E.g., ISP speeds up some traffic, slows down other traffic • Reporting abuse or corruption • E.g., whistleblower concerned for safety, Tor enables anonymous communication 61 Summary • Tor enables anonymity online • Not perfect, but vastly more anonymous than traditional browsing 62');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'lecture', 'DarkWeb', 'sites through Tor 58 Agenda • Introduction • Review • VPN proxies • Tor • Tor services • Tor browser • Tor history 59 Tor history • Developed by US Naval Research Laboratory • Goal: protect US intelligence communications online • Now a nonprofit • US Government is a major funder 60 More uses for Tor • Break censorship barriers • E.g., in places that censor web content • Political activism • E.g., in places that discourage free speech • Net neutrality • E.g., ISP speeds up some traffic, slows down other traffic • Reporting abuse or corruption • E.g., whistleblower concerned for safety, Tor enables anonymous communication 61 Summary • Tor enables anonymity online • Not perfect, but vastly more anonymous than traditional browsing 62');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'EECS 485 Final Exam Fall 2025 SOLUTION This is a 120 minute, closed-book exam. You may use one cheat sheet, 8.5”x11”, double-sided. No other notes or use of any computing or communication hardware (e.g., calculators, cell phones, smart glasses, etc.) is allowed. For multiple-choice questions, indicate your response by filling in the appropriate bubble. Fill in the bubble completely, and make sure to erase completely if you change your answer. For free response questions, write your answers clearly in the space provided in each problem. Collaboration or assistance is prohibited ● You are NOT allowed to collaborate with anyone else to answer these questions. ● You are NOT allowed to solicit assistance from anyone to answer these questions. You are to abide by the University of Michigan/Engineering Honor Code. To receive a grade, please sign below to signify that you have kept the honor code pledge. I have neither given nor received aid on this exam, nor have I concealed any violations of the Honor Code. Signature: _________________________________________ Name: _________________________________________ Uniqname: _________________________________________ UMID: _________________________________________ Page 1 of 22 Make sure to write your uniqname at the top of every page of the exam. This page is intentionally left blank Multiple Choice (40 points) Demo Question: How should I fill in my responses for a Multiple Choice question? ⬤ A. Fill in the chosen bubble completely and only select ONE per question! 1. A client is streaming data from a server over TCP, and suddenly packets are dropped due to network congestion. Which outcome is most consistent with how TCP behaves? ◯ A. Some data may be permanently lost ◯ B. The number of ACK packets will increase compared to the number of data packets ◯ C. The number of ACK packets will stay the same as before the congestion ◯ D. The sender''s congestion window will grow ◯ E. The sender’s congestion window will shrink Solution: E. When congestion increases, TCP’s congestion control algorithm reacts by shrinking the congestion window, which reduces the sender’s sending rate. The connection still stays alive. Choices A, C, and D are wrong since TCP will still guarantee reliable, in-order delivery (no loss, no skipping, no out-of-order delivery) to the application. TCP also never switches protocols, making Choice B wrong as well. 2. An online multiplayer game experiences a problem where player positions appear to "jump" on screen rather than moving smoothly. Investigation reveals that when packet 50 is lost, packets 51-70 arrive but aren''t processed until packet 50 is retransmitted. Which networking concept is the most responsible for this behavior? ◯ A. UDP ◯ B. Congestion control ◯ C. IP ◯ D. TCP ◯ E. Flow Control Solution: D, TCP Enforces ordered delivery so if packet 50 is missing, then later packets are buffered and withheld until 50 is retransmitted. shingle size 𝑘 (e.g., moving from 2-shingles to 10-shingles) affect similarity detection? ◯ A. More documents appear similar ◯ B. Fewer documents appear similar ◯ C. Only affects the speed of computation. ◯ D.');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'will still guarantee reliable, in-order delivery (no loss, no skipping, no out-of-order delivery) to the application. TCP also never switches protocols, making Choice B wrong as well. 2. An online multiplayer game experiences a problem where player positions appear to "jump" on screen rather than moving smoothly. Investigation reveals that when packet 50 is lost, packets 51-70 arrive but aren''t processed until packet 50 is retransmitted. Which networking concept is the most responsible for this behavior? ◯ A. UDP ◯ B. Congestion control ◯ C. IP ◯ D. TCP ◯ E. Flow Control Solution: D, TCP Enforces ordered delivery so if packet 50 is missing, then later packets are buffered and withheld until 50 is retransmitted. shingle size 𝑘 (e.g., moving from 2-shingles to 10-shingles) affect similarity detection? ◯ A. More documents appear similar ◯ B. Fewer documents appear similar ◯ C. Only affects the speed of computation. ◯ D. Increases the probability of hash collisions in MinHash ◯ E. Allows the detection of duplicates even if the words are in a different order. Solution:B. Increasing (k) makes each shingle a longer exact phrase, so small edits affect many shingles and the similarity drops. In other words, a larger shingle size means documents must contain larger sections that match exactly. 4. You are calculating the TF-IDF weight for the term "kangaroo." In which scenario does this term receive the highest weight in a specific document D? ◯ A. "Kangaroo" appears once in D and appears in all other documents in the collection. ◯ B. "Kangaroo" appears frequently in D and appears in all other documents in the collection. ◯ C. "Kangaroo" appears once in D and is very rare in the rest of the collection. ◯ D. "Kangaroo" appears frequently in D and is very rare in the rest of the collection. ◯ E. "Kangaroo" does not appear in D Solution:D. TF-IDF is biggest when the term shows up many times in D (high TF) but is rare across the whole collection (high IDF). 5. Suppose a new website links to every other website but receives no incoming links. What will most likely happen after recomputing PageRank to convergence? ◯ A. Every other page gets a large PageRank boost ◯ B. PageRank values of existing pages barely change ◯ C. The new page accumulates high PageRank ◯ D. Pages with many incoming links will gain significantly more PageRank than pages with few ◯ E. The dampening factor will change to compensate links, so it has almost no PageRank to give out. Even though it links to every page, it’s spreading a tiny amount of rank across many outgoing edges, so nothing really changes. 6. Why might a programmer choose processes over threads? ◯ A. Processes execute faster than threads ◯ B. Processes can share data more easily ◯ C. Processes provide isolation to limit damage from buggy or untrusted code ◯ D. Processes work better for I/O-bound workloads ◯ E. Processes don''t require synchronization primitives for shared data structures Solution:');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'will most likely happen after recomputing PageRank to convergence? ◯ A. Every other page gets a large PageRank boost ◯ B. PageRank values of existing pages barely change ◯ C. The new page accumulates high PageRank ◯ D. Pages with many incoming links will gain significantly more PageRank than pages with few ◯ E. The dampening factor will change to compensate links, so it has almost no PageRank to give out. Even though it links to every page, it’s spreading a tiny amount of rank across many outgoing edges, so nothing really changes. 6. Why might a programmer choose processes over threads? ◯ A. Processes execute faster than threads ◯ B. Processes can share data more easily ◯ C. Processes provide isolation to limit damage from buggy or untrusted code ◯ D. Processes work better for I/O-bound workloads ◯ E. Processes don''t require synchronization primitives for shared data structures Solution: C. Processes have separate address spaces, so bugs or crashes are contained; threads share memory and can corrupt the whole process without careful synchronization. 7. A user visits example.com. Later, the IP address changes, but their next visit still goes to the old server. Why? ◯ A. The user’s browser always stores DNS permanently ◯ B. DNS resolvers cache TTL records ◯ C. The iterative DNS resolution algorithm stops after a cache hit for an NS record ◯ D. DNS caches only root nameserver data ◯ E. DNS resolvers cache A records until their TTL expires Solution: E. DNS caching respects TTL, so results persist until expiration. 8. Which is a key distinction between HITS and PageRank? ◯ A. PageRank computes two scores (hub & authority), HITS computes one ◯ B. HITS is query-dependent; PageRank is query-independent ◯ C. PageRank requires no normalization; HITS does not normalize ◯ D. HITS uses a damping factor; PageRank does not ◯ E. PageRank looks only at outgoing edges; HITS looks only at incoming edges query-independent. 9. Which Python function is used to prevent busy-waiting? ◯ A. threading.Thread.join() ◯ B. socket.socket.listen() ◯ C. socket.socket.settimeout() ◯ D. socket.socket.setsockopt() ◯ E. time.sleep() Solution: E. time.sleep() is the only function of these that can be used in a loop to yield control to the operating system to switch tasks. 10. Which of the following about the MapReduce framework in Project 4 is FALSE? ◯ A. The manager and workers can be on different computers, so long as they share a file system ◯ B. Reducer executables can be written in C++ ◯ C. The contents of each input file to the reducers must be in sorted order ◯ D. The pipeline produces the same number of output files as the number of mappers ◯ E. If any worker is performing mapping, no other worker can be performing reducing Solution: D. The pipeline produces the same number of output files as the number of reducers , not mappers. C is true, because the mappers are responsible for sorting all their output files, which become the input files to');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'the only function of these that can be used in a loop to yield control to the operating system to switch tasks. 10. Which of the following about the MapReduce framework in Project 4 is FALSE? ◯ A. The manager and workers can be on different computers, so long as they share a file system ◯ B. Reducer executables can be written in C++ ◯ C. The contents of each input file to the reducers must be in sorted order ◯ D. The pipeline produces the same number of output files as the number of mappers ◯ E. If any worker is performing mapping, no other worker can be performing reducing Solution: D. The pipeline produces the same number of output files as the number of reducers , not mappers. C is true, because the mappers are responsible for sorting all their output files, which become the input files to the reducers. See the P4 spec section at 11. You have an inverted index with 1,000 terms and 20,000 documents. You are segmenting this index between 10 servers. Which of the following are TRUE? ◯ A. When segmenting by term, each server will be responsible for 1,000 terms ◯ B. When segmenting by term, each server will be responsible for 2,000 documents ◯ C. When segmenting by document, each server will be responsible for 100 terms documents ◯ E. When segmenting by document, each server will be responsible for 1,000 terms Solution: E. When segmenting by document, each server is responsible for every term, but not every document. 12. A company uses round-robin DNS to distribute requests across three servers. Suddenly, one server becomes overloaded while the others remain idle. Which explanation best accounts for this imbalance? ◯ A. Round-robin DNS changes the HTML structure of responses ◯ B. The DNS system is randomly dropping packets ◯ C. Round-robin DNS does not consider per-request computational load ◯ D. Threads inside the busy server are blocking DNS rotation ◯ E. DNS always sends 90% of traffic to the first IP in its rotation Solution: C. DNS has no way of knowing what a server''s load is. 13. Which scenario best justifies database sharding rather than replication? ◯ A. Data fits easily on a single machine ◯ B. Most queries require consistent reads ◯ C. Reads vastly outnumber writes ◯ D. The dataset is too large to store multiple complete copies ◯ E. The network frequently partitions Solution: D - When the dataset is too large to store full copies, you’re forced to partition it across machines, which is exactly what sharding provides. Replication doesn’t solve storage limits, it only increases redundancy and read throughput. 14. A distributed database is designed so that if a partition occurs, the system returns errors rather than stale data. This design choice implies: ◯ A. The system is sharded rather than replicated ◯ B. The system has both consistency and availability ◯ C. The system is violating the CAP theorem ◯ D. Availability is chosen over');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'what a server''s load is. 13. Which scenario best justifies database sharding rather than replication? ◯ A. Data fits easily on a single machine ◯ B. Most queries require consistent reads ◯ C. Reads vastly outnumber writes ◯ D. The dataset is too large to store multiple complete copies ◯ E. The network frequently partitions Solution: D - When the dataset is too large to store full copies, you’re forced to partition it across machines, which is exactly what sharding provides. Replication doesn’t solve storage limits, it only increases redundancy and read throughput. 14. A distributed database is designed so that if a partition occurs, the system returns errors rather than stale data. This design choice implies: ◯ A. The system is sharded rather than replicated ◯ B. The system has both consistency and availability ◯ C. The system is violating the CAP theorem ◯ D. Availability is chosen over consistency ◯ E. Consistency is chosen over availability communicate) certain nodes are updated while others aren’t. Choosing to return an error instead of potentially stale data enforces consistency. 15. A recommender system uses a nearest-neighbor algorithm with cosine similarity. The developer does not normalize the vectors. What will the difference be compared to an implementation that did normalize the vectors? ◯ A. Users who rate more items will be selected as a nearest neighbor more often ◯ B. Users who rate fewer items will be selected as a nearest neighbor more often ◯ C. Items rated fewer times will be recommended more often ◯ D. Items with more ratings will be recommended more often ◯ E. There will be no difference Solution: E. The operations needed to compute cosine similarity can be simplified by normalizing the vectors, but the result will be the same whether or not they were normalized. See DeOrio-Live lecture 15 slides 36-37, Almomani lecture 15 slides 43-44, Kloosterman lecture 15 slide 44. 16. Why would a recommender system use inverse user frequency in its computations? ◯ A. Users that rate few items give more valuable information ◯ B. Users prefer recommendations that are given to few other users ◯ C. It prevents extreme content from being recommended to too many users ◯ D. It is a fundamental part of content-based filtering ◯ E. It helps recommend items that only a small community of users has rated Solution: E - Inverse user frequency down-weights items that many have rated and up-weights items that a small group have rated. 17. In a sealed-bid, second-price auction, you value an item at $100. Your research suggests other bidders value it between $60-$120. A consultant advises you to bid $85 to "split the difference and maximize expected profit." Why is this advice flawed? ◯ A. You should bid higher ($120) to ensure you win against the strongest competitor ◯ B. The advice ignores that your bid doesn''t affect whether you win, only what you pay item less than you ◯ D. You should randomize your bid to prevent strategic behavior ◯');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'other users ◯ C. It prevents extreme content from being recommended to too many users ◯ D. It is a fundamental part of content-based filtering ◯ E. It helps recommend items that only a small community of users has rated Solution: E - Inverse user frequency down-weights items that many have rated and up-weights items that a small group have rated. 17. In a sealed-bid, second-price auction, you value an item at $100. Your research suggests other bidders value it between $60-$120. A consultant advises you to bid $85 to "split the difference and maximize expected profit." Why is this advice flawed? ◯ A. You should bid higher ($120) to ensure you win against the strongest competitor ◯ B. The advice ignores that your bid doesn''t affect whether you win, only what you pay item less than you ◯ D. You should randomize your bid to prevent strategic behavior ◯ E. The correct strategy is to bid $0.01 below your true value Solution: C - In a sealed-bid second-price auction, the optimal strategy is to bid the item''s value. 18. Which part of the Bitcoin system uses public-key cryptography? ◯ A. Linking blocks to previous blocks in the chain ◯ B. Verifying transfers were authorized by the sender ◯ C. Verifying the same coins were not spent twice ◯ D. Hashing blocks to determine which miner can add a block ◯ E. Encrypting private wallets'' transaction history Solution: B - Senders sign transactions with their private key to show they authorize the transaction. A does not use cryptography. C uses the longest-chain consensus. D uses a cryptographic hash (sha256), but hashes are not public-key cryptography. There is no such thing as a private wallet for option E. 19. The Bitcoin protocol requires miners to perform Proof-of-Work computations. What is the primary security purpose of this mechanism? ◯ A. It encrypts the transaction history to make it impossible to change ◯ B. It increases the transaction throughput of the network by parallelizing the verification process across millions of GPUs ◯ C. It validates the identity of the sender more times ◯ D. It makes it prohibitively expensive to create blocks containing double spends ◯ E. It makes it prohibitively expensive to forge an alternate history of the blockchain Solution: E - To forge an alternate history by adding many blocks, proof-of-work requires an attacker to control a large portion of all the mining power in the system. identifying and blocking all Tor entry nodes. However, even after blocking thousands of known entry nodes, citizens continue accessing Tor. What property of Tor''s design makes this approach difficult? ◯ A. The government needs to block exit nodes instead ◯ B. Tor nodes are constantly being added and removed ◯ C. Any Tor node can act as an exit node ◯ D. Blocking Tor nodes would also block legitimate VPN services, causing economic damage ◯ E. Encryption prevents VPN traffic from being detected Solution: B - Tor nodes are dynamically added and removed. A');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'D. It makes it prohibitively expensive to create blocks containing double spends ◯ E. It makes it prohibitively expensive to forge an alternate history of the blockchain Solution: E - To forge an alternate history by adding many blocks, proof-of-work requires an attacker to control a large portion of all the mining power in the system. identifying and blocking all Tor entry nodes. However, even after blocking thousands of known entry nodes, citizens continue accessing Tor. What property of Tor''s design makes this approach difficult? ◯ A. The government needs to block exit nodes instead ◯ B. Tor nodes are constantly being added and removed ◯ C. Any Tor node can act as an exit node ◯ D. Blocking Tor nodes would also block legitimate VPN services, causing economic damage ◯ E. Encryption prevents VPN traffic from being detected Solution: B - Tor nodes are dynamically added and removed. A and C do not reflect the structure of the Tor network. D is not true because the IPs of Tor entry nodes are published, allowing other VPNs to not be blocked. E is not true because the destination IP of packets must be unencrypted even when the payload is. Free Response 1: Pie-ority Manager 485 (30 points) The Cats of the Grand Pie Consortium have hired you to manage their distributed pie-baking system. Each pie-baking request is a job with priority HIGH or LOW . HIGH-priority pies must always be baked before LOW-priority pies. You will implement a Manager that assigns jobs to Workers while respecting Priority Rules : ● If no Workers are available to process a new HIGH-priority job, the Manager must cancel a running LOW-priority job so that the HIGH-priority job can be processed. ● Cancelled jobs must be restarted later— unless the Worker finishes the job before the cancel request arrives. When this occurs, the manager may still receive a job_completed message for a job it intended to cancel; in that case, treat it as completed and do not restart it . ● You must receive confirmation that a canceled job has been cancelled or completed before launching it again. A worker will ever only send one of job_completed and job_cancelled for a given job. ● A worker cannot be assigned a new job until it has messaged the manager that the current job was completed or cancelled . ● You may not cancel more jobs than the number of HIGH-priority jobs, and you must not cancel a job if there are enough idle workers to run the incoming jobs. Threading Requirements Your Manager must use two threads total (including the main thread): TCP Listening Thread : ● Runs the provided tcp_server function, forwarding received messages to handle_tcp . ● Updates internal state for the main thread to act upon. Main Thread : ● Start the TCP listening thread. ● Continuously assign jobs to Workers as per the Priority Rules . Avoid busy waiting wherever possible. Simplifying Assumptions: ● Jobs of the same priority may be');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'before launching it again. A worker will ever only send one of job_completed and job_cancelled for a given job. ● A worker cannot be assigned a new job until it has messaged the manager that the current job was completed or cancelled . ● You may not cancel more jobs than the number of HIGH-priority jobs, and you must not cancel a job if there are enough idle workers to run the incoming jobs. Threading Requirements Your Manager must use two threads total (including the main thread): TCP Listening Thread : ● Runs the provided tcp_server function, forwarding received messages to handle_tcp . ● Updates internal state for the main thread to act upon. Main Thread : ● Start the TCP listening thread. ● Continuously assign jobs to Workers as per the Priority Rules . Avoid busy waiting wherever possible. Simplifying Assumptions: ● Jobs of the same priority may be executed in any order. ● Workers do not die and will always eventually respond to all messages. All messages will be delivered. ● All messages received are well formatted. class members def tcp_client(host, port, msg): """ Creates a socket connection to (host, port) and sends the msg dictionary. """ def tcp_server(host, port, handler, signals): """ Listens for TCP connections on (host, port) and receives messages until signals["shutdown"] is set to True. When a message is received, handler(msg) is called, where msg is a dictionary. """ Managers can receive the following messages via TCP : From a client: { "type": "launch_job", "priority": “HIGH” | “LOW”, "command": <string> } From worker: { "type": "register", "host": <string>, "port": <int> } From a worker: { "type": "job_completed", "job_id": <int> } From a worker: { "type": "job_cancelled", "job_id": <int> } Managers can send the following messages via TCP: To a worker: { "type": "start_job", "job_id": <int>, "command": <string> } To a worker: { "type": "cancel_job", "job_id": <int> } methods function correctly as specified , regardless of your implementation details. Note that these are class members. You do not need to add member variables that support these functions. def assign_job_to_worker(self, host, port, job_id, command: str): """ Assign a job to a worker and send the start_job message. """ def find_running_low_job(self): """ Returns (worker host, worker port, job_id) for a LOW priority job currently assigned to a worker, or (None, None, None) if none found. A job is still running even if you have sent a cancel message to its worker. """ class Manager: def __init__(self, host: str, port: int): self.signals = {"shutdown": False} self.idle_workers = set() # Set of (host, port) tuples self.next_job_id = 0 self.low_queue = [] # list of job_ids of low priority jobs # Add additional data structures here, if necessary self.high_queue = [] # List of job_ids self.cancelling = set() # Set of job_ids self.job_commands = {} # job_id -> command tcp_thread = threading.Thread( target=tcp_server, args=(host, port, self.handle_tcp, self.signals) ) tcp_thread.start() self.assign_jobs() # Write implementation below tcp_thread.join() while not self.signals["shutdown"]: # if we have HIGH jobs waiting, but no idle workers, cancel');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'Assign a job to a worker and send the start_job message. """ def find_running_low_job(self): """ Returns (worker host, worker port, job_id) for a LOW priority job currently assigned to a worker, or (None, None, None) if none found. A job is still running even if you have sent a cancel message to its worker. """ class Manager: def __init__(self, host: str, port: int): self.signals = {"shutdown": False} self.idle_workers = set() # Set of (host, port) tuples self.next_job_id = 0 self.low_queue = [] # list of job_ids of low priority jobs # Add additional data structures here, if necessary self.high_queue = [] # List of job_ids self.cancelling = set() # Set of job_ids self.job_commands = {} # job_id -> command tcp_thread = threading.Thread( target=tcp_server, args=(host, port, self.handle_tcp, self.signals) ) tcp_thread.start() self.assign_jobs() # Write implementation below tcp_thread.join() while not self.signals["shutdown"]: # if we have HIGH jobs waiting, but no idle workers, cancel a low # priority job and assign it to the worker. if self.high_queue and not self.idle_workers and \ len(self.cancelling) < len(self.high_queue): # We are assuming that self.find_running_low_job() # does not return the same job_id every time. Student solutions # were allowed to make that same assumption. host, port, low_job_id = self.find_running_low_job() if host and (low_job_id not in self.cancelling): self.cancelling.add(low_job_id) tcp_client( host, port, {"type": "cancel_job", "job_id": low_job_id}, ) # Note this solution only cancels one job at a time, but # can cancel additional jobs next time around the while loop. if self.idle_workers and (self.high_queue or self.low_queue): if self.high_queue: job_id = self.high_queue.pop(0) elif self.low_queue: job_id = self.low_queue.pop(0) worker = self.idle_workers.pop() command = self.job_commands[job_id] self.assign_job_to_worker(worker[0], worker[1], job_id, command) time.sleep(0.1) elif message["type"] == "job_cancelled": job_id = message["job_id"] # Add worker back to idle pool. You can assume this member function # is implemented for you and works correctly. worker = self.find_worker_by_job_id(job_id) self.idle_workers.add(worker) # successfully cancelled, remove from cancelling set self.cancelling.remove(job_id) # put job back in queue (restart it) # HIGH jobs can''t be cancelled, so the job must be LOW priority self.low_queue.append(job_id) Free Response 2: Speedy Speedy Robots (30 points) eecs485staff has partnered with a local warehouse robot provider to analyze robot movement efficiency! Write a two-stage MapReduce pipeline that identifies the average transition time between warehouse zones and determines which robots are moving the slowest for each transition path. Input map1.py will receive warehouse log file entries in the following format: <robot_id> <timestamp> <zone> <event> Example input: r2 700.0 produce load r2 800.0 dairy unload r1 100.0 bakery load r2 100.0 freezer load r1 200.0 bakery unload r1 900.0 produce load r1 1005.0 dairy unload r2 600.0 bakery unload robot_id: unique robot identifier represented as the prefix "r" with a number timestamp: timestamp (in minutes since start) zone: the warehouse zone the event is happening in event: "load" or "unload" Stage 1 The first stage must identify all zone transitions for each robot and calculate the duration of each transition . A zone transition occurs when a robot unloads in a different zone than where it loaded. It also occurs when a');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'efficiency! Write a two-stage MapReduce pipeline that identifies the average transition time between warehouse zones and determines which robots are moving the slowest for each transition path. Input map1.py will receive warehouse log file entries in the following format: <robot_id> <timestamp> <zone> <event> Example input: r2 700.0 produce load r2 800.0 dairy unload r1 100.0 bakery load r2 100.0 freezer load r1 200.0 bakery unload r1 900.0 produce load r1 1005.0 dairy unload r2 600.0 bakery unload robot_id: unique robot identifier represented as the prefix "r" with a number timestamp: timestamp (in minutes since start) zone: the warehouse zone the event is happening in event: "load" or "unload" Stage 1 The first stage must identify all zone transitions for each robot and calculate the duration of each transition . A zone transition occurs when a robot unloads in a different zone than where it loaded. It also occurs when a robot moves from a zone it unloaded into a different zone to load. Loading and unloading in the same zone is not a zone transition, nor is loading in the same zone that the robot was unloaded in. The transition duration is calculated as the difference between the timestamp when the robot arrives at the new zone and the timestamp when it was last seen in the previous zone. You may assume loading always happens prior in time to unloading for a given robot, and that every unload is preceded in time by exactly one load. However, the input file may not be sorted by the timestamp. Stage 2 The second stage must calculate the average duration for each unique transition across all robots as well as determine the slowest robot - the robot with the longest time for that path. When the same robot undergoes the same zone transition multiple times, each time counts When determining the slowest robot, you may break ties however you wish. Output For each unique zone transition path, display the transition statistics in the following format based on how many robots have taken the zone transition path. If only one robot has taken the zone transition path, the <avg_duration> and <slowest_duration> fields will be identical. <transition_path> <avg_duration> <slowest_robot> <slowest_duration> Example Output (from the input mentioned above) : bakery->produce 400.0 r1 700.0 freezer->bakery 500.0 r2 500.0 produce->dairy 102.5 r1 105.0 Constraints: Similar to how you implemented the pipeline in Project 5, write your Map and Reduce code in Python3 using the Hadoop Streaming Interface with key-value pairs separated by a tab (\t) character. Read all input from stdin and write all output to stdout. 1. You must meaningfully use all outlined stages to receive credit. You may use the identity function (no transformation) as a Map stage. 2. All Map stages must use O(1) memory to receive credit. 3. All Map stages must produce multiple groups on the sample input to receive credit. Hint: Python lists have a sort() member function. When the elements of the list are tuples, the list is sorted by the');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'zone transition path, the <avg_duration> and <slowest_duration> fields will be identical. <transition_path> <avg_duration> <slowest_robot> <slowest_duration> Example Output (from the input mentioned above) : bakery->produce 400.0 r1 700.0 freezer->bakery 500.0 r2 500.0 produce->dairy 102.5 r1 105.0 Constraints: Similar to how you implemented the pipeline in Project 5, write your Map and Reduce code in Python3 using the Hadoop Streaming Interface with key-value pairs separated by a tab (\t) character. Read all input from stdin and write all output to stdout. 1. You must meaningfully use all outlined stages to receive credit. You may use the identity function (no transformation) as a Map stage. 2. All Map stages must use O(1) memory to receive credit. 3. All Map stages must produce multiple groups on the sample input to receive credit. Hint: Python lists have a sort() member function. When the elements of the list are tuples, the list is sorted by the first element of the tuple, with ties broken by the second element of the tuple, and so on. # Input: [robot_id] [timestamp] [zone] [event] # Output: [robot_id]\t[timestamp] [zone] [event] for line in sys.stdin: robot_id, timestamp, zone, event = line.strip().split() # Emit robot_id as key, timestamp, zone, event as value print(f"{robot_id}\t{timestamp} {zone} {event}") # Input: [robot_id]\t[timestamp] [zone] [event] # Output: [robot_id] [zone_transition_path] [duration] def reduce_1_group(key, group): """Reduce one group for a robot.""" records = [] for line in group: robot_id, value = line.strip().split("\t") timestamp, zone, event = value.split() records.append((float(timestamp), zone, event)) # Sort by timestamp records.sort() prev_zone = None prev_timestamp = None for ts, zone, event in records: if prev_zone is not None: # prev_zone being none means the robot is first seen if prev_zone != zone: print(f"{key} {prev_zone}->{zone} {ts-prev_timestamp}") prev_zone = zone prev_timestamp = ts def keyfunc(line): """Return the key from a TAB-delimited key-value pair.""" return line.partition("\t")[0] def main(): """Divide sorted lines into groups that share a key.""" for key, group in itertools.groupby(sys.stdin, keyfunc): reduce_1_group(key, group) if __name__ == "__main__": main() # Input: [robot_id] [zone_transition_path] [duration] # Output: [zone_transition_path]\t[robot_id] [duration] for line in sys.stdin: robot_id, zone_transition_path, duration = line.strip().split() print(f"{zone_transition_path}\t{robot_id} {duration}") # Input: [zone_transition_path]\t[robot_id] [duration] # Output: [robot_id] [avg_duration] [slowest_robot] [slowest_duration] def reduce_2_group(key, group): """Reduce one group.""" total_duration = 0 num_times_taken = 0 durations = [] for line in group: parts = line.strip().split("\t") transition, temp = parts robot_id, duration = temp.split() duration = float(duration) durations.append((duration, robot_id)) total_duration += duration num_times_taken +=1 avg = total_duration/num_times_taken durations.sort() # sort by duration, with ties broken by robot_id greatest_duration = durations[-1][0] slowest_robot = durations[-1][1] print(key, avg, slowest_robot, greatest_duration) def keyfunc(line): """Return the key from a TAB-delimited key-value pair.""" return line.partition("\t")[0] def main(): """Divide sorted lines into groups that share a key.""" for key, group in itertools.groupby(sys.stdin, keyfunc): reduce_2_group(key, group) if __name__ == "__main__": main()');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, '[slowest_duration] def reduce_2_group(key, group): """Reduce one group.""" total_duration = 0 num_times_taken = 0 durations = [] for line in group: parts = line.strip().split("\t") transition, temp = parts robot_id, duration = temp.split() duration = float(duration) durations.append((duration, robot_id)) total_duration += duration num_times_taken +=1 avg = total_duration/num_times_taken durations.sort() # sort by duration, with ties broken by robot_id greatest_duration = durations[-1][0] slowest_robot = durations[-1][1] print(key, avg, slowest_robot, greatest_duration) def keyfunc(line): """Return the key from a TAB-delimited key-value pair.""" return line.partition("\t")[0] def main(): """Divide sorted lines into groups that share a key.""" for key, group in itertools.groupby(sys.stdin, keyfunc): reduce_2_group(key, group) if __name__ == "__main__": main()');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'EECS 485 Midterm Exam Fall 2025 SOLUTION This is a 120 minute, closed-book exam. You may use one cheat sheet, 8.5”x11”, double-sided. No other notes or use of any computing or communication hardware (e.g., calculators, cell phones, smart glasses, etc.) is allowed. For multiple-choice questions, indicate your response by filling in the appropriate bubble. Fill in the bubble completely, and make sure to erase completely if you change your answer. For free response questions, write your answers clearly in the space provided in each problem. Collaboration or assistance is prohibited ● You are NOT allowed to collaborate with anyone else to answer these questions. ● You are NOT allowed to solicit assistance from anyone to answer these questions. You are to abide by the University of Michigan/Engineering Honor Code. To receive a grade, please sign below to signify that you have kept the honor code pledge. I have neither given nor received aid on this exam, nor have I concealed any violations of the Honor Code. Signature: _________________________________________ Name: _________________________________________ Uniqname: _________________________________________ UMID: _________________________________________ ◯ A. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/review/?target=/dramas/’, methods=[“GET”]) ◯ B. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/review/’, methods=[“POST”]) ◯ C. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/review/?target=/dramas/’, methods=[“POST”]) ◯ D. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/Casablanca/submit_order’, methods=[“POST”]) ◯ E. None of the above Solution: B is the only correct option, as it is performing a POST request as defined by the form “method” parameter and has the endpoint of “/film485/review”, the route pointed to by the action parameter. 5. Which of the following statements about JavaScript is FALSE? ◯ A. Out of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, it is the only programming language ◯ B. It can be used to change the Document Object Model without reloading the page ◯ C. Provides the same functionality as Python for web development ◯ B. {random number} → Number → Done ◯ C. Done → Number → random number ◯ D. Number → Done → {random number} ◯ E. None of the above 1. console.log("Number") runs first → prints Number. 2. fetch(''/api/random/int'') is asynchronous and returns a promise. The .then() callback is scheduled to run after current call stack is empty. 3. console.log("Done") runs immediately after the fetch is called → prints Done. 4. Once the network request completes, the .then() callback executes → prints a random number. Distributed Systems, MapReduce, Google File System 16. Sydney is trying to run a MapReduce program when a reducer crashes midway through processing its input. How does MapReduce ensure correctness? ◯ A. All mappers re-run to regenerate the lost input for the reducer CREATE TABLE players ( player_id INTEGER AUTOINCREMENT, name VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL, filename VARCHAR(64) NOT NULL, position VARCHAR(2) NOT NULL, drafted_manager_id INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY (player_id) FOREIGN KEY(drafted_manager_id) REFERENCES managers(manager_id) ); get_upload(filename): # serve one file in the uploads directory Simplifying assumptions: ● You can assume that the only positions in the players table are ''QB'', ''RB'', ''WR'', ''TE'', ‘K’ find_free_agents Returns a list of dictionaries for undrafted players (player_id, name, filename, position) in positions not already filled by the manager, ordered by descending player_id. def find_free_agents(drafted_manager_id): con = get_db_connection() free_agents = con.execute("""');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'prints Done. 4. Once the network request completes, the .then() callback executes → prints a random number. Distributed Systems, MapReduce, Google File System 16. Sydney is trying to run a MapReduce program when a reducer crashes midway through processing its input. How does MapReduce ensure correctness? ◯ A. All mappers re-run to regenerate the lost input for the reducer CREATE TABLE players ( player_id INTEGER AUTOINCREMENT, name VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL, filename VARCHAR(64) NOT NULL, position VARCHAR(2) NOT NULL, drafted_manager_id INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY (player_id) FOREIGN KEY(drafted_manager_id) REFERENCES managers(manager_id) ); get_upload(filename): # serve one file in the uploads directory Simplifying assumptions: ● You can assume that the only positions in the players table are ''QB'', ''RB'', ''WR'', ''TE'', ‘K’ find_free_agents Returns a list of dictionaries for undrafted players (player_id, name, filename, position) in positions not already filled by the manager, ordered by descending player_id. def find_free_agents(drafted_manager_id): con = get_db_connection() free_agents = con.execute(""" SELECT player_id, name, filename, position FROM players WHERE drafted_manager_id IS NULL AND position NOT IN ( SELECT DISTINCT position FROM players WHERE drafted_manager_id = ? ) ORDER BY player_id DESC """, (drafted_manager_id,)).fetchall() Write the <body> section of a Jinja template for the draft page. It should include: ● The logged-in user’s team name ● The logged-in user’s current drafted team, showing each player’s profile photo, name, and position. Free Response 2: Study485 (30 points) Implement a campus study spot finder, using React functional components that allows students to see availability of study spots and report when seats open or fill up. Implement the Campus and Spot functional components. Implemented for you Campus Component Campus component: ● Declare 3 state variables: ○ spots (list) stores the list of study spots from the API. ○ locationFilter (string) representing "central", "north", or "" for both. ○ availabilityFilter (integer) representing the minimum availability to show. ● On initial render, make a GET request to /api/v1/spots/?location=<string>&minAvailability=<int> and store results in spots. ● When handling the API response: ○ Filter out any spots with availability < 0, indicating the spot is closed. ● Renders a list of Spot components, one for each study spot, with the right props (specifie d in the Spot component section). Spot Spot // compute mostAvailable return ( let mostAvailable = null; for (const s of spots) { if (mostAvailable === null || s.availability > mostAvailable.availability) { mostAvailable = s; } } ); }; export default Spot;');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'right props (specifie d in the Spot component section). Spot Spot // compute mostAvailable return ( let mostAvailable = null; for (const s of spots) { if (mostAvailable === null || s.availability > mostAvailable.availability) { mostAvailable = s; } } ); }; export default Spot;');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'EECS 485 Final Exam Winter 2025 SOLUTION This is a 120 minute, closed-book exam. You may use one cheat sheet, 8.5”x11”, double-sided. No other notes or use of any computing or communication hardware (e.g., calculators, cell phones, etc.) is allowed. For multiple-choice questions, indicate your response by filling in the appropriate bubble. Fill in the bubble completely, and make sure to erase completely if you change your answer. For free response questions, write your answers clearly in the space provided in each problem. Collaboration or assistance is prohibited ● You are NOT allowed to collaborate with anyone else to answer these questions. ● You are NOT allowed to solicit assistance from anyone to answer these questions. You are to abide by the University of Michigan/Engineering Honor Code. To receive a grade, please sign below to signify that you have kept the honor code pledge. I have neither given nor received aid on this exam, nor have I concealed any violations of the Honor Code. Signature: _________________________________________ Name: _________________________________________ Uniqname: _________________________________________ UMID: _________________________________________ Multiple Choice (40 points) Demo Question: How should I fill in my responses for a Multiple Choice question? ⬤ A. Fill in the chosen bubble completely and only select ONE per question! 1. A Worker in a distributed system is sending periodic heartbeats to a Manager process on TCP . The network becomes congested, and some heartbeat messages are delayed. What is the most likely outcome? ◯ A. The Manager receives the heartbeats in the wrong order but still processes them. ◯ B. The Worker automatically switches to UDP. ◯ C. The Manager assumes the Worker is dead. ◯ D. The Worker queues all heartbeats and sends them in bursts. ◯ E. The heartbeats are dropped, and the Worker is disconnected from the network. Solution: A is wrong because TCP guarantees in-order delivery. B is wrong because the Worker can’t just automatically switch to UDP. D is wrong because sending heartbeats in bursts would not help the Manager determine if the Worker is alive at a particular time. E is wrong because TCP is reliable and guarantees packets will be delivered eventually. C is correct because the heartbeats could be dropped due to congestion and by the time the packet is resent, the Manager may have already marked the Worker as dead. TCP’s reliability mechanisms make it slower than UDP. Page 2 of 25 best answer. ◯ A. Switching processes require saving and restoring more state. ◯ B. Threads must always run on separate CPU cores. ◯ C. Context switching only happens when a process explicitly requests it. ◯ D. Threads require more overhead than processes to switch. ◯ E. Processes and threads have identical memory access patterns to shared memory. Solution: B is incorrect because threads can run on the same or different cores, and scheduling is managed by the OS. C is incorrect because context switches can be forced by the OS. D is incorrect because process switches require more overhead than threads, not the other');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'will be delivered eventually. C is correct because the heartbeats could be dropped due to congestion and by the time the packet is resent, the Manager may have already marked the Worker as dead. TCP’s reliability mechanisms make it slower than UDP. Page 2 of 25 best answer. ◯ A. Switching processes require saving and restoring more state. ◯ B. Threads must always run on separate CPU cores. ◯ C. Context switching only happens when a process explicitly requests it. ◯ D. Threads require more overhead than processes to switch. ◯ E. Processes and threads have identical memory access patterns to shared memory. Solution: B is incorrect because threads can run on the same or different cores, and scheduling is managed by the OS. C is incorrect because context switches can be forced by the OS. D is incorrect because process switches require more overhead than threads, not the other way around. E is incorrect because processes have separate memory spaces, while threads share memory. A is correct because process context switches require saving/restoring entire address spaces, whereas threads share memory. 3. Which of the following is TRUE about TCP congestion and flow control? ◯ A. The number of the sender’s packets determines the size of the receiver’s sliding window ◯ B. The TCP congestion window should increase when a packet is dropped ◯ C. The TCP congestion window should increase when the sender receives an ACK ◯ D. If the sliding window is working properly, and the sender has a lot of data to to send, the receiver’s queue will usually be about 65% full ◯ E. Both C and D are correct Solution: C - the congestion window can increase when the sender receives an ACK because if the packet got there safely, there’s room to send more. D is incorrect because the queue should usually be almost full. Page 3 of 25 shutdown = False def main(): t1 = threading.Thread(target=worker1) t1.start() t2 = threading.Thread(target=worker2) t2.start() t1.join() print(“worker1 joined”) t2.join() print(“worker2 joined”) print(counter) if __name__ == “__main__”: main() def worker1(): time.sleep(0.1) global shutdown shutdown = True print(“worker1 done”) def worker2(): while not shutdown: time.sleep(0.1) print(“worker2 done”) ◯ A. worker1 done, worker1 joined, worker2 done, worker2 joined ◯ B. worker1 joined, worker1 done, worker2 joined, worker2 done ◯ C. worker1 done, worker1 joined ◯ D. worker1 done ◯ E. None of the above will print, as the second join will block the program indefinitely Solution: A, the code will run correctly as thread 1 updates shutdown to unblock thread 2 before the main thread joins thread 2. Note: During the exam, we noticed that the variable counter (printed in the last line of main) was never defined. This line was kept in by mistake and it had no effect on the solution. Page 4 of 25 ◯ A. If packets are out of order, UDP allows applications to handle their order ◯ B. If packets disappear, UDP resends lost packets ◯ C. If packets arrive out of order, the');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'def worker2(): while not shutdown: time.sleep(0.1) print(“worker2 done”) ◯ A. worker1 done, worker1 joined, worker2 done, worker2 joined ◯ B. worker1 joined, worker1 done, worker2 joined, worker2 done ◯ C. worker1 done, worker1 joined ◯ D. worker1 done ◯ E. None of the above will print, as the second join will block the program indefinitely Solution: A, the code will run correctly as thread 1 updates shutdown to unblock thread 2 before the main thread joins thread 2. Note: During the exam, we noticed that the variable counter (printed in the last line of main) was never defined. This line was kept in by mistake and it had no effect on the solution. Page 4 of 25 ◯ A. If packets are out of order, UDP allows applications to handle their order ◯ B. If packets disappear, UDP resends lost packets ◯ C. If packets arrive out of order, the TCP buffers reassemble packets using sequence numbers ◯ D. If packets are repeated, the TCP receiver ignores duplicate sequence numbers ◯ E. If a set of senders are overloading the network, the TCP congestion control system uses a congestion window to limit the number of packets Solution: B - UDP follows the better never than late method, and ignores lost packets Page 5 of 25 6. Based on the diagram above and using a typical damping factor of 0.85, which node will have the highest PageRank score after three iterations? ◯ A. W ◯ B. X ◯ C. Y ◯ D. Z ◯ E. None of the above Solution: The damping factor is 0.85, so each node distributes 85% of its PageRank to its outbound links, and 15% is distributed evenly across all nodes. Z receives links from both X and Y and redistributes its PageRank back to W. Since PageRank is iterative, nodes with more incoming links (especially from well-connected nodes) tend to have a higher score. Z gets PageRank from both X and Y, which helps it gain a higher score. Page 6 of 25 7. Using the diagram above, say we know the following ranks after applying the PageRank algorithm: W ranks 2nd, X ranks 1st, Y ranks 3rd, and Z ranks 4th. Which of the following changes would most likely result in X having the lowest PageRank score of any node? ◯ A. Adding a link from X → Y ◯ B. Removing the link from X → Z ◯ C. Adding a link from Z → X ◯ D. Removing the link from W → X ◯ E. Adding a link from X → W Solution: A is incorrect because this would create an additional link from X to Y. Since X is already the highest-ranked node, this would distribute some of X''s score to Y, but it’s unlikely to drastically reduce X''s score to the lowest position. B is incorrect because this would reduce X''s contribution to Z, which would reduce Z''s PageRank. However, X still links to W and Y. C is incorrect');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'the PageRank algorithm: W ranks 2nd, X ranks 1st, Y ranks 3rd, and Z ranks 4th. Which of the following changes would most likely result in X having the lowest PageRank score of any node? ◯ A. Adding a link from X → Y ◯ B. Removing the link from X → Z ◯ C. Adding a link from Z → X ◯ D. Removing the link from W → X ◯ E. Adding a link from X → W Solution: A is incorrect because this would create an additional link from X to Y. Since X is already the highest-ranked node, this would distribute some of X''s score to Y, but it’s unlikely to drastically reduce X''s score to the lowest position. B is incorrect because this would reduce X''s contribution to Z, which would reduce Z''s PageRank. However, X still links to W and Y. C is incorrect because this would directly increase X''s authority score because adding an incoming link from Z would increase the authority flowing into X, increasing X’s PageRank. D is correct because this would decrease X''s PageRank significantly as W is an important node with a high rank, and X benefits from its incoming link. Removing this link would be major in lowering X''s PageRank. E is incorrect because adding an outgoing link from X to W would increase the number of links from X, but W already has a strong rank, so this won''t have much effect on X''s rank. Page 7 of 25 ◯ A. Being linked by many pages can increase the PageRank of a webpage. ◯ B. Repeating the keyword multiple times can increase the PageRank of a webpage. ◯ C. Linking to many pages may not increase the PageRank of a webpage. ◯ D. PageRank can measure the importance of a page. ◯ E. Adding the damping factor can avoid the sink nodes/region situation. Solution: A) True, linked by many pages can increase the pagerank. B) False, term frequency has nothing to do with pagerank. C) True, it needs to be linked by many important pages. D) True, it’s the definition of pagerank. E) True, the damping factor (1/d)/N will avoid the sink node siatuation. 9. Which of the following is FALSE about normalized TF-IDF and Vector Space? ◯ A. TF-IDF is good when documents are disjointed and are of high quality. ◯ B. The more a word occurs in the document, the higher the TF-IDF. ◯ C. Lower document frequency may lead to a higher TF-IDF. ◯ D. In order to not give longer documents more weight, we normalize the TD-IDF. ◯ E. If two documents are similar, the angle between them will be smaller, and the cosine will be larger. Solution: A) True. B) False, there are a lot of counterexamples. For example, the lecture kangaroo example. We can normalize it to vector length to balance the weight. C) True. D) True, the kangaroo example in the lecture. E) True, according to the definition of cosine');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'it’s the definition of pagerank. E) True, the damping factor (1/d)/N will avoid the sink node siatuation. 9. Which of the following is FALSE about normalized TF-IDF and Vector Space? ◯ A. TF-IDF is good when documents are disjointed and are of high quality. ◯ B. The more a word occurs in the document, the higher the TF-IDF. ◯ C. Lower document frequency may lead to a higher TF-IDF. ◯ D. In order to not give longer documents more weight, we normalize the TD-IDF. ◯ E. If two documents are similar, the angle between them will be smaller, and the cosine will be larger. Solution: A) True. B) False, there are a lot of counterexamples. For example, the lecture kangaroo example. We can normalize it to vector length to balance the weight. C) True. D) True, the kangaroo example in the lecture. E) True, according to the definition of cosine similarity. Page 8 of 25 ◯ A. Crawlers are used to build the link graph where each website is a directed edge and each hyperlink is a vertex. ◯ B. Crawlers can crawl all web pages that exist. ◯ C. A surface crawler that has no credentials can crawl the 485 lecture material. ◯ D. If a page links many other web pages, it’s important. ◯ E. When there is a new query, the pagerank score does not need to be recalculated. Solution: A) False, because website is a vertex and hyperlinks are the directed edges. B) False, they can’t crawl those pages that are on robot.txt. C) False, surface crawlers can’t crawl password-protected pages. D) False, page is important if it’s linked by many important pages. E) True, PageRank is not query-dependent. 11. A machine dies in a search engine with a segmented inverted index. Which could be true? ◯ A. Segment-by-term is used: when users search for “Britney Spears,” they receive no results. ◯ B. Segment-by-term is used: when users search for “eecs485,” the eecs485 page is no longer in the results. ◯ C. Segment-by-document is used: when users search for “Britney Spears,” they receive no results. ◯ D. Segment-by-document is used: when users search for “eecs485,” the eecs485 page is no longer in the results. ◯ E. A and D Solution: E. A and D If you use segment-by-term, then you will lose certain queries when a storage machine goes down. Therefore, if you use segment-by-term, A is possible. If you use segment-by-document, then you will lose some search results when a storage machine goes down. Therefore, if you use segment-by-document, D is possible. Page 9 of 25 Document A: “Ellen’s favorite project is Project 4.” Document B: “Hailey’s favorite project is Project 5.” ◯ A. 0 ◯ B. 2/7 ◯ C. 3/7 ◯ D. 4/7 ◯ E. 1 Solution: C. 3/7 Document A Shingles: {“Ellen’s favorite,” “favorite project,” “project is”, “is Project,” “Project 4”} Document B Shingles: {“Hailey’s favorite,” “favorite project,” “project is,” “is Project,” “Project 5”} There are 3 common shingles out of 7 total');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'D. Segment-by-document is used: when users search for “eecs485,” the eecs485 page is no longer in the results. ◯ E. A and D Solution: E. A and D If you use segment-by-term, then you will lose certain queries when a storage machine goes down. Therefore, if you use segment-by-term, A is possible. If you use segment-by-document, then you will lose some search results when a storage machine goes down. Therefore, if you use segment-by-document, D is possible. Page 9 of 25 Document A: “Ellen’s favorite project is Project 4.” Document B: “Hailey’s favorite project is Project 5.” ◯ A. 0 ◯ B. 2/7 ◯ C. 3/7 ◯ D. 4/7 ◯ E. 1 Solution: C. 3/7 Document A Shingles: {“Ellen’s favorite,” “favorite project,” “project is”, “is Project,” “Project 4”} Document B Shingles: {“Hailey’s favorite,” “favorite project,” “project is,” “is Project,” “Project 5”} There are 3 common shingles out of 7 total unique shingles. Therefore, the Jaccard Similarity is 3/7. Page 10 of 25 honorable ticket resellers. In the case of a network database failure, should she prioritize consistency or availability and why? ◯ A. Consistency to ensure that all ticket information presented to a customer is correct. ◯ B. Consistency to ensure that each customer’s ticket payment is authorized by their credit card company. ◯ C. Availability to ensure that the website can always be reached by customers. ◯ D. Availability to ensure that ticket information is always presented to customers even if the information is outdated. ◯ E. None of the explanations are correct. Solution: A A. Correct: You should prioritize consistency because very bad things could happen if stale information is presented to customers (such as multiple customers buying the same tickets). Consistency ensures that all data returned is correct or an error is returned if data is not reachable. B. Wrong: Consistency is not related to authorizing payment methods. C. Wrong: Availability will impact whether the database information is reachable rather than impacting the entire website. D. Wrong: Very bad things could happen if outdated data is presented to customers (such as a customer buying a ticket that is no longer available) E. Wrong: because A is correct 14. Which usage pairing(s) is correct? ◯ A. Containerization: Machine’s capacity should be fully utilized ◯ B. Containerization: Application’s data needs to be saved for later ◯ C. Virtualization: Application’s OS is different ◯ D. Virtualization: Application’s user count fluctuates quickly ◯ E. Both A and C are correct Solution: E. To fully utilize a machine’s capacity, we can run multiple containers (A). Different OSes require virtualization (C). B is incorrect as containerization doesn’t allow for persistent data storage, D is incorrect as virtualization startup is slow and won’t handle fluctuating user counts. Page 11 of 25 an empty starting cache. ◯ A. Immediately reloading the page will require the .umich nameserver to be re-queried ◯ B. The browser will query the .edu nameserver ◯ C. A subsequent access to me.engin.umich.edu will require fewer network requests ◯ D. The .com');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'is no longer available) E. Wrong: because A is correct 14. Which usage pairing(s) is correct? ◯ A. Containerization: Machine’s capacity should be fully utilized ◯ B. Containerization: Application’s data needs to be saved for later ◯ C. Virtualization: Application’s OS is different ◯ D. Virtualization: Application’s user count fluctuates quickly ◯ E. Both A and C are correct Solution: E. To fully utilize a machine’s capacity, we can run multiple containers (A). Different OSes require virtualization (C). B is incorrect as containerization doesn’t allow for persistent data storage, D is incorrect as virtualization startup is slow and won’t handle fluctuating user counts. Page 11 of 25 an empty starting cache. ◯ A. Immediately reloading the page will require the .umich nameserver to be re-queried ◯ B. The browser will query the .edu nameserver ◯ C. A subsequent access to me.engin.umich.edu will require fewer network requests ◯ D. The .com nameserver will be cached ◯ E. Both B and C are true Solution: C A. Since caching is present, cse.engin.umich.edu’s address will be saved in the cache and the .umich nameserver will not need to be re-queried as part of the resolution process B. The browser has an empty cache so the DNS resolution will be passed to the DNS resolver. The DNS resolver will be in charge of querying the .edu nameserver C. The engin.umich.edu nameserver would be saved in cache meaning that umich.edu, .edu and root nameserver would not need to be re-queried D. The .com nameserver is not part of the resolution path so won’t be cached 16. Which of the following best distinguishes content-based collaborative filtering from user-based collaborative filtering in recommendation systems? ◯ A. Content-based needs lots of users; user-based works with few. ◯ B. Content-based is better for popular items; user-based is better for new items. ◯ C. Content-based suggests similar items to what a user liked before; user-based suggests what similar users liked. ◯ D. Content-based suffers from the cold-start problem; user-based does not. ◯ E. Content-based uses other users'' ratings; user-based uses item features. Solution: Content-based filtering focuses on the user''s past behavior and item features ("You liked this, so you’ll like that"). Collaborative filtering relies on similar users ("People like you liked this"). On the exam taken at regular time, options B and D (D is now rewritten) were the same and were graded the same.. Page 12 of 25 cryptocurrency mining? ◯ A. Encourage miners to join mining pools to combine their computational power which increases their chances of successfully mining a block. ◯ B. Encourage miners to relocate to low cost of living areas. ◯ C. Decreasing the reward offered for winning a block. ◯ D. Switching from a proof-of-work model to a proof-of-stake model. ◯ E. None of the above would reduce environmental impact. Solution: A is incorrect because the same level energy is still being consumed by each individual miner in the pool having no net effect on the environmental impact. B is incorrect because it does');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'behavior and item features ("You liked this, so you’ll like that"). Collaborative filtering relies on similar users ("People like you liked this"). On the exam taken at regular time, options B and D (D is now rewritten) were the same and were graded the same.. Page 12 of 25 cryptocurrency mining? ◯ A. Encourage miners to join mining pools to combine their computational power which increases their chances of successfully mining a block. ◯ B. Encourage miners to relocate to low cost of living areas. ◯ C. Decreasing the reward offered for winning a block. ◯ D. Switching from a proof-of-work model to a proof-of-stake model. ◯ E. None of the above would reduce environmental impact. Solution: A is incorrect because the same level energy is still being consumed by each individual miner in the pool having no net effect on the environmental impact. B is incorrect because it does not relate to energy consumption. C is incorrect because decreasing the reward for winning a block could cause miners to leave (thus reducing the environmental impact) but this is not a guarantee, since it could also cause miners to increase their computational power so that they win blocks at a higher rate in order to maintain their prior profits rate. D is correct because Proof-of-work requires miners to solve complex mathematical problems, consuming significant amounts of electricity and contributing to environmental concerns, however proof-of-stake has miners essentially bid to win the block rather than solve a puzzle significantly minimizing energy consumption. 18. What does a single TOR node know? ◯ A. an input node knows the destination ◯ B. an exit node knows the source and destination ◯ C. an input node knows the source and destination ◯ D. an exit node knows the destination ◯ E. Both input and exit nodes know the source and destination Solution: D is correct, in Tor an input node knows the source and an exit node knows the destination. Page 13 of 25 ◯ A. They can be reversed and fixed after release ◯ B. Miners control them and are able to change the contract terms ◯ C. Any vulnerability can be exploited permanently ◯ D. Contracts require permission from a central authority to run ◯ E. Ethereum does not use smart contracts NFTs do Solution: C is true because once the code is released it is cannot be changed. Meaning any existing bugs in the code that can be exploited can be exploited permanently. 20. Akanksha goes to a sealed-bid second-price auction and brings her minion for good luck. Akanksha bids $50, her minion bids $75, and Gru bids $60. What is the possible outcome of this round? ◯ A. Akanksha re-bids $80 ◯ B. Akanksha’s minion wins and pays $75 ◯ C. Gru’s proxy rebids $80 for him ◯ D. Gru wins and pays $60 ◯ E. Akanksha’s minion wins and pays $60 Solution: E is correct in a sealed-bid second-price auction the bidders submit their bids at once and the');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'the contract terms ◯ C. Any vulnerability can be exploited permanently ◯ D. Contracts require permission from a central authority to run ◯ E. Ethereum does not use smart contracts NFTs do Solution: C is true because once the code is released it is cannot be changed. Meaning any existing bugs in the code that can be exploited can be exploited permanently. 20. Akanksha goes to a sealed-bid second-price auction and brings her minion for good luck. Akanksha bids $50, her minion bids $75, and Gru bids $60. What is the possible outcome of this round? ◯ A. Akanksha re-bids $80 ◯ B. Akanksha’s minion wins and pays $75 ◯ C. Gru’s proxy rebids $80 for him ◯ D. Gru wins and pays $60 ◯ E. Akanksha’s minion wins and pays $60 Solution: E is correct in a sealed-bid second-price auction the bidders submit their bids at once and the highest bid wins but pays the second-highest bid price. Page 14 of 25 Free Response 1: Gru(te) Force 485 (30 points) Gru is helping EECS 485 staff crack stolen hashed passwords using a MinionServer that coordinates brute-force password cracking jobs and reports plaintext passwords. Gru communicates with the MinionServer , sending new jobs and shutdown messages. Password cracking can be very CPU intensive – use Minion processes to divide and conquer. Each minion process is created with a hashed password and a subset of possible guesses that it exhaustively checks. MinionServer Process ● Main Thread ○ Starts a thread for TCP listening. ○ Loops until shutdown, periodically checking if there are any new password jobs. ○ Once a new job is started, create the specified number of Minion processes . The job message contains a list of lists, each list corresponds to the guesses to be assigned to a minion. Length of list will always equal the number of minions. ○ Ensure all minions working on previous jobs have terminated before starting a new job, and only process one job at a time. ● TCP Thread ○ Message type " new_job ": Update the job queue with the new job details. ○ Message type "shutdown": Update the relevant variables to terminate the server and notify all minions. ○ Message type " woohoo ": Send the plaintext password to Gru and notify all minions to terminate. ○ Message type " failure ": Update count of number of minion tasks failed. Notify all minions to terminate if all minions failed. Creating a new process Similar to the multithreading library from project 4, we can use the multiprocessing library to spawn new processes: >> p = Process(target=<function>, args=(<arg1>,<arg2>,...)) >> p.start() >> p.join() Assigning minion ports Each process should have the same host (as the MinionServer ), but a different port. For example, MinionServer port = 8000, Minion ports = 8001, 8002, … Once a shutdown message is received, all threads must terminate before the program ends. Avoid busy waiting wherever possible. Simplifying Assumptions ● Don’t need to implement fault tolerance. ● All messages');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'details. ○ Message type "shutdown": Update the relevant variables to terminate the server and notify all minions. ○ Message type " woohoo ": Send the plaintext password to Gru and notify all minions to terminate. ○ Message type " failure ": Update count of number of minion tasks failed. Notify all minions to terminate if all minions failed. Creating a new process Similar to the multithreading library from project 4, we can use the multiprocessing library to spawn new processes: >> p = Process(target=<function>, args=(<arg1>,<arg2>,...)) >> p.start() >> p.join() Assigning minion ports Each process should have the same host (as the MinionServer ), but a different port. For example, MinionServer port = 8000, Minion ports = 8001, 8002, … Once a shutdown message is received, all threads must terminate before the program ends. Avoid busy waiting wherever possible. Simplifying Assumptions ● Don’t need to implement fault tolerance. ● All messages are in the correct form and no TCP errors can occur. ● tcp_client() will retry sending a message until it is received Page 15 of 25 signals["shutdown"] is set to True. When a message is received, handler(msg) is called, where msg is a dictionary. """ def hash(plaintext): """ Takes in a string plaintext and returns the hashed int value. """ Message Descriptions MinionServer receives the following messages using TCP From Gru: { ''type'': "new_job", ''num_minions'': <int>, ''hashed_pw'': <string>, ''guesses'': <list<list<string>>> } From a minion : { ''type'': "woohoo", ''password'': <string> } From Gru (to be forwarded to minions): { ''type'': "shutdown" } From a minion : { ''type'': "failure" } MinionServer sends the following messages using TCP To Gru: { ''password'': <string> } To a minion: { ''type'': "shutdown" } class MinionServer: Page 16 of 25 def __init__(self, host: str, port: int): # Must only use the following data structures self.signals = {“shutdown”: False} # shutdown signal self.minions = {} # {(host, port): process, ...} self.job_queue = [] self.num_failures = 0 self.current_job = {} self.gru_host = ... # already initialized self.gru_port = ... # already initialized tcp_thread = threading.Thread( target=tcp_server, args=[host, port, self.handle_tcp, self.signals]) tcp_thread.start() while not self.signals[“shutdown”]: if len(self.job_queue) > 0: # make sure previous job processes have terminated for process in self.minions.values(): process.join() self.minions = {} self.current_job = self.job_queue.pop(0) self.num_failures = 0 for i in range(self.current_job["num_minions"]): minion_port = port + i + 1 self.minions[(host, minion_port)] = Process(target=self.start_minion, args=[host, minion_port, self.current_job["hashed_pw"], self.current_job["guesses"][i]]) self.minions[(host, minion_port)].start() time.sleep(0.1) tcp_thread.join() for process in self.minions.values(): process.join() Page 17 of 25 def start_minion(self, host, port, hash_password, guesses): # Creates a new instance of the Minion class. Minion(host, port, hash_password, guesses) def handle_tcp(self, msg): Minion Process This process should keep running until a shutdown message is received. ● Main Thread ○ Starts a thread for TCP listening. ○ Loops through all guesses in the minion’s input, comparing each guess’ hash against the hashed target password. ○ If a match is found, sends the correct guess back to the MinionServer . ○ If no match is found in the guesses, sends failure message to the MinionServer .');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, '> 0: # make sure previous job processes have terminated for process in self.minions.values(): process.join() self.minions = {} self.current_job = self.job_queue.pop(0) self.num_failures = 0 for i in range(self.current_job["num_minions"]): minion_port = port + i + 1 self.minions[(host, minion_port)] = Process(target=self.start_minion, args=[host, minion_port, self.current_job["hashed_pw"], self.current_job["guesses"][i]]) self.minions[(host, minion_port)].start() time.sleep(0.1) tcp_thread.join() for process in self.minions.values(): process.join() Page 17 of 25 def start_minion(self, host, port, hash_password, guesses): # Creates a new instance of the Minion class. Minion(host, port, hash_password, guesses) def handle_tcp(self, msg): Minion Process This process should keep running until a shutdown message is received. ● Main Thread ○ Starts a thread for TCP listening. ○ Loops through all guesses in the minion’s input, comparing each guess’ hash against the hashed target password. ○ If a match is found, sends the correct guess back to the MinionServer . ○ If no match is found in the guesses, sends failure message to the MinionServer . ● TCP Thread ○ Message type “shutdown”: Update the relevant variable Page 18 of 25 if msg["type"] == "new_job": self.job_queue.append(msg) return if msg["type"] == "shutdown": self.signals[“shutdown”] = True elif msg["type"] == "woohoo": tcp_client(self.gru_host, self.gru_port, {"password": msg["password"]}) elif msg["type"] == "failure": self.num_failures += 1 if self.num_failures != self.current_job["num_minions"]: return for minion, _ in self.minions.items(): tcp_client(minion[0], minion[1], {"type": "shutdown"}) class Minion: def __init__(self, host: str, port: int, minion_server_host: str, minion_server_port: int, hash_password: str, guesses: list): self.signals = {“shutdown”: False} # shutdown signal tcp_thread = threading.Thread( target=tcp_server, args=[host, port, self.handle_tcp, self.signals]) tcp_thread.start() for guess in guesses: if hash_password == hash(guess): tcp_client(minion_server_host, minion_server_port, {"type": "woohoo", "password": guess}) tcp_thread.join() return tcp_client(minion_server_host, minion_server_port, {"type": "failure"}) tcp_thread.join() def handle_tcp(self, msg): if msg["type"] == "shutdown": self.signals[“shutdown”] = True Page 19 of 25 Free Response 2: LOGGER.info (30 points) eecs485staff have partnered with cloud providers to track service performance! Write a two-stage MapReduce pipeline that identifies error statistics in server log files. Input map1.py will receive log file entries from different services in the following format: <timestamp> <request_id> <service_name> <event_type> Example input: 1742489590 5589 nginx request 1742489590 1729 gunicorn request 1742489595 0443 postgresql response 1742489590 0443 postgresql request 1742489613 1729 gunicorn response 1742489632 5589 nginx response 1742489232 1583 nginx request 1742489732 1583 nginx response timestamp : modified unix timestamp in milliseconds. request_id : unique client request. service_name: only one service can be requested per request_id . event_type : a request indicates a service has begun processing and a response indicates it has finished processing. Stage 1 The first stage must determine if a service call is an error , meaning either the request or response is missing. Calculate the latency between the response and request for each non-error service call (request to response). Hint : Latency is defined as the time between receiving a request and a response Hint : You should pass along whether the service call was missing a request or response so the next stage can distinguish the type of error per service call. Page 20 of 25 The second stage must report all errors and identify any slow non-error service calls, which are defined as');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'request 1742489732 1583 nginx response timestamp : modified unix timestamp in milliseconds. request_id : unique client request. service_name: only one service can be requested per request_id . event_type : a request indicates a service has begun processing and a response indicates it has finished processing. Stage 1 The first stage must determine if a service call is an error , meaning either the request or response is missing. Calculate the latency between the response and request for each non-error service call (request to response). Hint : Latency is defined as the time between receiving a request and a response Hint : You should pass along whether the service call was missing a request or response so the next stage can distinguish the type of error per service call. Page 20 of 25 The second stage must report all errors and identify any slow non-error service calls, which are defined as those with a latency >= 2 * average_latency amongst those calls for that service. Output For each service, display the service_name and the average_latency , followed by a list of errors and slow service calls. If a call is an error, print whether the request or response is missing. <service_name> <avg_latency>ms <request_id_i> – missing <request|response> <request_id_j> - slow … <service_name> <avg_latency> … Example output: mongodb 400ms 0987 - missing request 5678 – slow 1234 - missing response gunicorn 500ms … Constraints Similar to how you implemented the pipeline in Project 5, write your Map and Reduce code in Python3 using the Hadoop Streaming Interface with key-value pairs separated by a tab ( \t ) character. Read all input from stdin and write all output to stdout . 1. You must meaningfully use all outlined stages to receive credit. 2. You must use itertools.groupby to implement the reduce stages. 3. All Map stages must use O(1) memory to receive credit. 4. All Map stages must produce multiple groups to receive credit. Page 21 of 25 #!/usr/bin/env python3 # map1.py # Assume all packages are imported # Input: <timestamp> <request_id> <service_name> <event_type> # Output: <request_id>\t<service_name> <timestamp> <event_type> for line in sys.stdin: timestamp, request_id, service_name, event_type = line.strip().split() print(f"{request_id}\t{service_name} {timestamp} {event_type}") Page 22 of 25 #!/usr/bin/env python3 # reduce1.py # Assume all packages are imported def reduce_1_group(key, group): # Input: <request_id>\t<service_name> <timestamp> <event_type> # Output: <request_id> <service_name> <latency> # Output: <request_id> <service_name> error: <error_type> request_time, response_time, name = None, None, None for line in group: _, parts = line.strip().split(''\t'') service_name, timestamp, event_type = parts.split() name = service_name # record the response and request timestamps if event_type == ''request'': request_time = int(timestamp) else: response_time = int(timestamp) if request_time is None or response_time is None: missing_event = ''request'' if request_time is None else ''response'' print(f''{key} {name} error: {missing_event}'') else: latency = response_time - request_time print(f''{key} {name} {latency}'') def keyfunc(line): return line.partition("\t")[0] def main(): for key, group in itertools.groupby(sys.stdin, keyfunc): reduce_1_group(key, group) if __name__ == "__main__": main() Page 23 of 25 #!/usr/bin/env python3 # map2.py # Assume all packages are imported # Input: <request_id> <service_name> <latency>');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'request_id, service_name, event_type = line.strip().split() print(f"{request_id}\t{service_name} {timestamp} {event_type}") Page 22 of 25 #!/usr/bin/env python3 # reduce1.py # Assume all packages are imported def reduce_1_group(key, group): # Input: <request_id>\t<service_name> <timestamp> <event_type> # Output: <request_id> <service_name> <latency> # Output: <request_id> <service_name> error: <error_type> request_time, response_time, name = None, None, None for line in group: _, parts = line.strip().split(''\t'') service_name, timestamp, event_type = parts.split() name = service_name # record the response and request timestamps if event_type == ''request'': request_time = int(timestamp) else: response_time = int(timestamp) if request_time is None or response_time is None: missing_event = ''request'' if request_time is None else ''response'' print(f''{key} {name} error: {missing_event}'') else: latency = response_time - request_time print(f''{key} {name} {latency}'') def keyfunc(line): return line.partition("\t")[0] def main(): for key, group in itertools.groupby(sys.stdin, keyfunc): reduce_1_group(key, group) if __name__ == "__main__": main() Page 23 of 25 #!/usr/bin/env python3 # map2.py # Assume all packages are imported # Input: <request_id> <service_name> <latency> # Input: <request_id> <service_name> error: <event_type> # Output: <service_name>\t<request_id> <latency> # Output: <service_name>\t<request_id> error: <error_type> for line in sys.stdin: line = line.strip().split() request_id, service_name = line[0], line[1] if len(line) == 3: latency = line[2] print(f''{service_name}\t{request_id} {latency}'') else: error_type = line[3] print(f''{service_name}\t{request_id} error: {error_type}'') Page 24 of 25 #!/usr/bin/env python3 # reduce2.py # Assume all packages are imported def reduce_2_group(key, group): # Input: <service_name>\t<request_id> <latency> # Input: <service_name>\t<request_id> error: <error_type> # Output: <service_name> <avg_latency> <request_id_i> – error: <error_type> <request_id_j> ids, output, latencies = [], [], [] for line in group: _, parts = line.strip().split(''\t'') data = parts.split() if ''error'' in data: error_type = data[-1] output.append(f''{data[0]} - missing {error_type}'') else: ids.append(data[0]) latencies.append(int(data[-1])) avg_latecy = sum(latencies) / len(latencies) for i in range(len(ids)): if latencies[i] >= 2 * avg_latency: output.append(f''{ids[i]} - slow'') print({key} {avg_latency}ms) for call in output: print(f''\t{call}'') def keyfunc(line): return line.partition("\t")[0] def main(): for key, group in itertools.groupby(sys.stdin, keyfunc): reduce_2_group(key, group) if __name__ == "__main__": main() Page 25 of 25');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'EECS 485 Midterm Exam Winter 2025 SOLUTION This is a 120 minute, closed-book exam. You may use one cheat sheet, 8.5”x11”, double-sided. No other notes or use of any computing or communication hardware (e.g., calculators, cell phones, etc.) is allowed. For multiple-choice questions, indicate your response by filling in the appropriate bubble. Fill in the bubble completely, and make sure to erase completely if you change your answer. For free response questions, write your answers clearly in the space provided in each problem. Collaboration or assistance is prohibited ● You are NOT allowed to collaborate with anyone else to answer these questions. ● You are NOT allowed to solicit assistance from anyone to answer these questions. You are to abide by the University of Michigan/Engineering Honor Code. To receive a grade, please sign below to signify that you have kept the honor code pledge. I have neither given nor received aid on this exam, nor have I concealed any violations of the Honor Code. Signature: _________________________________________ Name: _________________________________________ Uniqname: _________________________________________ UMID: _________________________________________ Multiple Choice (40 points) Demo Question: How should I fill in my responses for a Multiple Choice question? ⬤ A. Fill in the chosen bubble completely and only select ONE per question! HTML, CSS, HTTP, Server-Side & Client-Side Dynamic Page 1. Which of the following can be implemented with server-side dynamic pages? ◯ A. Creating a post without a reload ◯ B. Double clicking a post to add a like without a reload ◯ C. Reloading individual parts of a page without a refresh ◯ D. Adding and deleting a comment with a refresh ◯ E. All of the above Solution: A-C require client-side dynamic pages, but you can add and delete comments (with a reload) using server-side dynamic pages 2. For server-side pages, server code can''t modify a rendered page once it has been rendered and sent to the browser. To address this limitation, client-side pages use: ◯ A. Flask to set up routes and functions to refresh templated pages ◯ B. JavaScript to interact with the server and reload the page on DOM changes ◯ C. Jinja to automatically re-render templates as client data is updated ◯ D. HTML event handlers to to handle client actions and modify the web page ◯ E. JavaScript to modify the DOM and update the rendered page Solution: Client-side dynamic pages use code running the client’s web browser (JavaScript in this case), rather than Flask, HTML, or Jinja to modify the dom and change individual pieces in the rendered page. B is incorrect as it does not interact with the server. Page 2 of 23 which of the following functions would run and work as intended? ◯ A. @atlas.app.route(''/course/'', methods=["GET"]) def course(): ◯ B. @atlas.app.route(''/course/<course_id>/'', methods=["GET"]) def course(): ◯ C. @atlas.app.route(''/course/<course_id>/'', methods=["GET"]) def course(course_id): ◯ D. @atlas.app.route(''/course/<course_id>/?type=EECS'', methods=["GET"]) def course(course_id, type): ◯ E. @atlas.app.route(''/course/<course_id>/?type=EECS'', methods=["GET"]) def course(course_id): Course specifies the path, and the ID is a parameter for the function, making C the correct answer. There is no specified type');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'Jinja to automatically re-render templates as client data is updated ◯ D. HTML event handlers to to handle client actions and modify the web page ◯ E. JavaScript to modify the DOM and update the rendered page Solution: Client-side dynamic pages use code running the client’s web browser (JavaScript in this case), rather than Flask, HTML, or Jinja to modify the dom and change individual pieces in the rendered page. B is incorrect as it does not interact with the server. Page 2 of 23 which of the following functions would run and work as intended? ◯ A. @atlas.app.route(''/course/'', methods=["GET"]) def course(): ◯ B. @atlas.app.route(''/course/<course_id>/'', methods=["GET"]) def course(): ◯ C. @atlas.app.route(''/course/<course_id>/'', methods=["GET"]) def course(course_id): ◯ D. @atlas.app.route(''/course/<course_id>/?type=EECS'', methods=["GET"]) def course(course_id, type): ◯ E. @atlas.app.route(''/course/<course_id>/?type=EECS'', methods=["GET"]) def course(course_id): Course specifies the path, and the ID is a parameter for the function, making C the correct answer. There is no specified type in the url provided. 4. Which of the following is TRUE about event-driven programming? ◯ A. The event queue stores event callbacks waiting to execute ◯ B. An event handler runs before an event occurs to catch and respond to it ◯ C. The event table maps events to their location in the event queue ◯ D. The addEventListener() function updates the event queue with new event instances ◯ E. Events in the event queue are executed before completing functions in the stack Solution: A. Correct - The event queue does store event handlers B. Incorrect - the event handler runs after an event occurs C. Incorrect - the event table maps events to the event handler D. Incorrect - the function updates the event table E. Incorrect - the stack functions must all execute before events in the queue are added to the stack and are executed 5. Which of the following is FALSE about HTTP? ◯ A. For static content, HTTP servers are file servers on the server side Page 3 of 23 between the client and server ◯ E The HEAD request can help verify if a page has been changed Solution: A server cannot open a connection to a client Sessions, Encryption, Web Security 1. Which type of attack does the following comment on a social media website demonstrate? Nice picture! <script src=" ◯ A. SQL Injection ◯ B. Man-in-the-middle attack ◯ C. Replay attack ◯ D. Cross-site scripting ◯ E. None of the above Solution D is correct. Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) injects malicious code, like JavaScript, into a web page viewed by other users. A is incorrect because SQL injection involves submitting SQL to forms on a website, B is incorrect because man-in-the-middle attacks involve a malicious party between two parties communicating, C is incorrect because replay attacks involve sending the same message multiple times. 2. Which of the following is FALSE ? ◯ A. Symmetric encryption uses the same key for encryption and decryption ◯ B. Cryptographic hash functions do not use a key. ◯ C. Cryptographic hash functions cannot be reversed. ◯ D.');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'connection to a client Sessions, Encryption, Web Security 1. Which type of attack does the following comment on a social media website demonstrate? Nice picture! <script src=" ◯ A. SQL Injection ◯ B. Man-in-the-middle attack ◯ C. Replay attack ◯ D. Cross-site scripting ◯ E. None of the above Solution D is correct. Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) injects malicious code, like JavaScript, into a web page viewed by other users. A is incorrect because SQL injection involves submitting SQL to forms on a website, B is incorrect because man-in-the-middle attacks involve a malicious party between two parties communicating, C is incorrect because replay attacks involve sending the same message multiple times. 2. Which of the following is FALSE ? ◯ A. Symmetric encryption uses the same key for encryption and decryption ◯ B. Cryptographic hash functions do not use a key. ◯ C. Cryptographic hash functions cannot be reversed. ◯ D. If an attacker intercepts a message and passes it on without modification, it is an example of a man-in-the-middle attack. Page 4 of 23 and random numbers (nonce). 3. Which of the following is TRUE ? ◯ A. If Alice and Bob are communicating with asymmetric encryption, Bob knows Alice’s private key but no one else does, making it private. ◯ B. A certificate authority that signs keys without adequate verification can enable attackers to launch man-in-the-middle attacks. ◯ C. A malicious user resending a previously captured message multiple times is an example of a replay attack. ◯ D. Encrypting a message is the only way to prevent a replay attack. ◯ E. More than one of the above is TRUE Solution: A. Only Alice knows her private key, this is what makes it private. B. B is correct; while an attacker would still need to redirect traffic—such as through DNS poisoning, rogue access points, or compromised routers—the root cause of the MITM vulnerability in this scenario is the improperly issued certificate. C. C is a correct answer because a replay attack involves capturing a legitimate message (e.g., "transfer $100") and resending it multiple times to perform unauthorized actions. D. Sequence numbers for messages can prevent replay attacks. E. B and C are both true 4. What is the primary purpose of a Public Key Infrastructure (PKI)? ◯ A. Encrypts messages using symmetric encryption to ensure confidentiality. ◯ B. Securely distributes certificate authority public keys and verifies their authenticity using certificates. ◯ C. Protects private keys by storing them in a centralized server. ◯ D. Adds salts to password hashes for enhanced security. ◯ E. Serves as a protocol used for brute-force attacks on encrypted data. Page 5 of 23 is performed using the keys themselves. B. PKI ensures secure distribution and verification of public keys through certificates, preventing attackers from using fake keys (Slide 41, 05_Encryption.pdf). C. PKI does not store private keys; private keys remain secret and are managed by their owners. D. PKI is unrelated to password hashing or salting, which are methods for securing stored passwords.');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'Sequence numbers for messages can prevent replay attacks. E. B and C are both true 4. What is the primary purpose of a Public Key Infrastructure (PKI)? ◯ A. Encrypts messages using symmetric encryption to ensure confidentiality. ◯ B. Securely distributes certificate authority public keys and verifies their authenticity using certificates. ◯ C. Protects private keys by storing them in a centralized server. ◯ D. Adds salts to password hashes for enhanced security. ◯ E. Serves as a protocol used for brute-force attacks on encrypted data. Page 5 of 23 is performed using the keys themselves. B. PKI ensures secure distribution and verification of public keys through certificates, preventing attackers from using fake keys (Slide 41, 05_Encryption.pdf). C. PKI does not store private keys; private keys remain secret and are managed by their owners. D. PKI is unrelated to password hashing or salting, which are methods for securing stored passwords. E. PKI is not a protocol for attacks; it is a framework for secure key management and trust establishment. 5. Two people want to send messages bidirectionally with asymmetric encryption without meeting in person. How many keys are needed for this? ◯ A. 1 private key ◯ B. 2 keys: 1 public, 1 private ◯ C. 2 private keys ◯ D. 4 keys: 2 public, 2 private ◯ E. Asymmetric encryption requires prior exchange of private keys Solution: Consider the parties named Alice and Bob. For Bob to send a message to Alice he will encrypt the message with Alice’s public key, when she receives the message she will decrypt with her private key. For Alice to send a message to Bob she will encrypt the message with Bob’s public key and he will decrypt the message with his private key. K_Alice_public, K_Bob_public, K_Alice_private, B_Bob_private is 4 keys total, 2 public 2 private. D is correct REST APIs, JavaScript, Asynchronous Programming 1. Jeff is testing the REST API for a blogging platform. He sent the following requests: Page 6 of 23 A POST request to /posts/ , which returned a 201 response code. A DELETE request to /posts/234/ , which returned a 404 response code. A PUT request to /posts/123/ , which returned a 403 response code. What can be inferred about Jeff’s interaction with the API? ◯ A. Jeff successfully created a new post in the database. ◯ B. Jeff does not have the required permission to update post /123 . ◯ C. The /posts/234/ resource does not exist or cannot be found. ◯ D. Jeff can successfully view the list of posts with a GET request. ◯ E. All of the above Solution: A. Incorrect because option B, C, D are also correct B. Incorrect because option A, C, D are also correct C. Incorrect because option A, B, D are also correct D. Incorrect because option A, B, C are also correct E. A is true because the POST request returned 201, indicating resource creation. B is true because the PUT request to /posts/123/ returned 403, indicating');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'returned a 404 response code. A PUT request to /posts/123/ , which returned a 403 response code. What can be inferred about Jeff’s interaction with the API? ◯ A. Jeff successfully created a new post in the database. ◯ B. Jeff does not have the required permission to update post /123 . ◯ C. The /posts/234/ resource does not exist or cannot be found. ◯ D. Jeff can successfully view the list of posts with a GET request. ◯ E. All of the above Solution: A. Incorrect because option B, C, D are also correct B. Incorrect because option A, C, D are also correct C. Incorrect because option A, B, D are also correct D. Incorrect because option A, B, C are also correct E. A is true because the POST request returned 201, indicating resource creation. B is true because the PUT request to /posts/123/ returned 403, indicating forbidden access. C is true because the DELETE request to /posts/234/ returned 404, indicating the resource doesn’t exist. D is true because the GET request returned 200. 2. Akanksha wrote the following JavaScript function to simulate a weather forecast system: function getWeatherForecast(city) { setTimeout(() => { console.log("Processing..."); fetch(`/api/weather/${city}`) .then(() => { console.log("Updating..."); Page 7 of 23 }, 500); console.log("Ready!"); setTimeout(() => { console.log("Fetching..."); }, 300); } getWeatherForecast("London"); What will the sequence of console log messages be, assuming the fetch call succeeds and console.log() takes less than 200 ms? ◯ A. Ready! Fetching... Processing... Updating… ◯ B. Ready! Processing... Fetching... Updating… ◯ C. Fetching... Ready! Processing… Updating... ◯ D. Ready! Fetching... Updating... Processing… ◯ E. None of the above Solution: A. Correct because "Ready!" runs first, followed by "Fetching..." (300ms timeout), then "Processing..." (500ms timeout), and finally "Updating…!" when the Promise resolves. B. Incorrect because "Fetching..." (300ms) always logs before "Processing..." (500ms). C. Incorrect because "Ready!" always logs first as it is synchronous. D. Incorrect because "Updating…" cannot log before "Processing..." due to Promise resolution order. E. Incorrect because Option A matches the sequence based on the event loop and delays. 3. In an asynchronous messaging app, messages sent from the server to the client may arrive out of order due to network delays (e.g. message 3 might arrive before message 1). What is the most effective way to ensure messages are displayed in the correct order? Page 8 of 23 them only after all preceding messages arrive. ◯ B. Display each message as soon as it arrives, regardless of its order. ◯ C. Add delays to messages to synchronize their arrival times. ◯ D. Use synchronous programming to ensure messages are received in order while maintaining good performance. ◯ E. None of the above Solution: A. Correct because this approach ensures that messages are displayed in the correct order by reserving space for missing packets until they arrive. B. Incorrect this results in out-of-order messages being displayed, leading to a poor user experience. C. Incorrect because this unnecessarily slows down message delivery without guaranteeing correct order. D. Incorrect because synchronous');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'server to the client may arrive out of order due to network delays (e.g. message 3 might arrive before message 1). What is the most effective way to ensure messages are displayed in the correct order? Page 8 of 23 them only after all preceding messages arrive. ◯ B. Display each message as soon as it arrives, regardless of its order. ◯ C. Add delays to messages to synchronize their arrival times. ◯ D. Use synchronous programming to ensure messages are received in order while maintaining good performance. ◯ E. None of the above Solution: A. Correct because this approach ensures that messages are displayed in the correct order by reserving space for missing packets until they arrive. B. Incorrect this results in out-of-order messages being displayed, leading to a poor user experience. C. Incorrect because this unnecessarily slows down message delivery without guaranteeing correct order. D. Incorrect because synchronous programming defeats the benefits of asynchronous systems and can severely degrade performance. E. Incorrect because option A is a.viable solution. 4. Which of the following is TRUE about REST APIs? ◯ A. REST APIs require data to be transferred only in JSON format. ◯ B. PUT requests are used to delete resources on the server. ◯ C. A REST API is stateless, meaning the server does not retain client data between requests. ◯ D. REST APIs are incompatible with the HTTP protocol. ◯ E. REST APIs always return the same status code for successful requests. Solution: A. Incorrect because REST APIs can use multiple data formats like JSON, XML, or plain text, depending on the implementation. B. Incorrect because DELETE requests are used to remove resources, while PUT is generally used to update or create resources. Page 9 of 23 the server between requests. D. Incorrect because REST APIs are built to work seamlessly with the HTTP protocol and its methods. E. Incorrect because REST APIs can return different formats (e.g., JSON, XML) depending on the request headers, such as Accept. 5. Which of the following statements about JavaScript execution in web browsers is TRUE? ◯ A. JavaScript cannot make network requests in the browser. ◯ B. JavaScript code always executes in the order it appears. ◯ C. JavaScript requires explicit compilation before it can run. ◯ D. By default, JavaScript runs in a single-threaded environment in the browser. ◯ E. JavaScript cannot modify or access HTML elements. Solution: A. Incorrect because JavaScript can make network requests using APIs like fetch B. Incorrect because JavaScript supports asynchronous operations. C. Incorrect because JavaScript is interpreted by the browser and does not require explicit compilation. D. Correct because JavaScript operates in a single-threaded environment, though it can handle asynchronous operations using the event loop. E. Incorrect because JavaScript is used to interact with and manipulate HTML elements via the DOM. Distributed Systems, MapReduce, Google File System Refer to the diagrams below of the Google File System for Questions 1 and 2. Use Figure 1 for Question 1 and Figure 2 for Question');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'network requests in the browser. ◯ B. JavaScript code always executes in the order it appears. ◯ C. JavaScript requires explicit compilation before it can run. ◯ D. By default, JavaScript runs in a single-threaded environment in the browser. ◯ E. JavaScript cannot modify or access HTML elements. Solution: A. Incorrect because JavaScript can make network requests using APIs like fetch B. Incorrect because JavaScript supports asynchronous operations. C. Incorrect because JavaScript is interpreted by the browser and does not require explicit compilation. D. Correct because JavaScript operates in a single-threaded environment, though it can handle asynchronous operations using the event loop. E. Incorrect because JavaScript is used to interact with and manipulate HTML elements via the DOM. Distributed Systems, MapReduce, Google File System Refer to the diagrams below of the Google File System for Questions 1 and 2. Use Figure 1 for Question 1 and Figure 2 for Question 2. Page 10 of 23 1. In the system from Figure 1 above, the system is… ◯ A. Inconsistent and undefined ◯ B. Inconsistent and defined ◯ C. Consistent and undefined ◯ D. Consistent and defined ◯ E. Cannot be determined In the end without adding any additional writes, the system is inconsistent and undefined. It remains inconsistent because in CS1, the last version of C100 we have is from Client 1. In CS2, the last version of C100 we have is from Client 2. Because we can’t guarantee the final values of C100 and C101 on all chunkservers come from the same client, we can’t guarantee that the file (sequence of chunks) is defined. 2. In Figure 2 , arrows A-C represent potential writes. Which write from Figure 2 will we need to add to ensure the system is both consistent and defined? ◯ A. Write A ◯ B. Write B ◯ C. Write C ◯ D. The system is already consistent and defined ◯ E. None of the above Client 2 directly writes to C100 in both CS1 and CS2, which does not follow the write forwarding rules. The write forwarding rules guarantee that updates to the same chunk Page 11 of 23 consistency. For Questions 3 and 4, refer to the following scenario. As a bonding activity, EECS 485 Staff decides to process visit logs from eecs485.org which uses a Madoop MapReduce framework. 3. EECS 485 Staff notices that one of the map worker nodes crashed during execution. Which of the following BEST describes how the program handles this? ◯ A. The worker node is temporarily ignored to prevent additional delays ◯ B. The shadow main takes over to complete the failed task ◯ C. The failed task remains unassigned until a worker becomes available to take it ◯ D. The failed task waits for the same worker to recover before being retried ◯ E. The failed task is always immediately reassigned to another worker for completion A is incorrect because the worker node is not removed during fault tolerance (but rather, tasks are reassigned). B is');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'chunk Page 11 of 23 consistency. For Questions 3 and 4, refer to the following scenario. As a bonding activity, EECS 485 Staff decides to process visit logs from eecs485.org which uses a Madoop MapReduce framework. 3. EECS 485 Staff notices that one of the map worker nodes crashed during execution. Which of the following BEST describes how the program handles this? ◯ A. The worker node is temporarily ignored to prevent additional delays ◯ B. The shadow main takes over to complete the failed task ◯ C. The failed task remains unassigned until a worker becomes available to take it ◯ D. The failed task waits for the same worker to recover before being retried ◯ E. The failed task is always immediately reassigned to another worker for completion A is incorrect because the worker node is not removed during fault tolerance (but rather, tasks are reassigned). B is incorrect because the shadow main operates in place of the manager when the manager fails, not the worker node. C is incorrect because the tasks are immediately reassigned to operating workers to ensure task completion. D is incorrect because the MapReduce framework prioritizes reassigning tasks to available workers rather than retrying on the same worker (fault tolerance). 4. Later in the semester, we discover that some analysis logs are still missing, indicating that fault tolerance is not functioning as expected. What is the MOST likely reason? ◯ A. Not enough worker nodes are being used to handle the large load ◯ B. Failed tasks are ignored instead of being reassigned to other workers ◯ C. Task retries failed due to synchronization issues between manager and workers ◯ D. The worker nodes are not reporting task failures to the manager Page 12 of 23 logs–MapReduce jobs will still be completed, even if slow. C is incorrect because synchronization issues can cause delays, but would not cause data loss. D is incorrect because if worker nodes fail to report, the manager node would detect failure through lack of heartbeats and reassign the task. E is incorrect because the shadow main operating in place of the manager would not cause failed tasks to be skipped. 5. Which of the following BEST describes fault tolerance in a distributed storage system like GFS? ◯ A. If the main server fails, the system elects an arbitrary chunkserver to take over ◯ B. If the main server fails, the system creates copies of all data to prevent loss ◯ C. If the main server fails, the system is temporarily unavailable until the main revives ◯ D. If a chunkserver fails, the system can recover its data from other chunkservers ◯ E. If a chunkserver fails, the system can recover its data from the main server A is incorrect because the shadow main will temporarily take over and provide read-only access. B is incorrect because data is replicated across multiple chunkservers in a distributed system. C is incorrect because fault tolerance in a distributed system prevents full system');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'place of the manager would not cause failed tasks to be skipped. 5. Which of the following BEST describes fault tolerance in a distributed storage system like GFS? ◯ A. If the main server fails, the system elects an arbitrary chunkserver to take over ◯ B. If the main server fails, the system creates copies of all data to prevent loss ◯ C. If the main server fails, the system is temporarily unavailable until the main revives ◯ D. If a chunkserver fails, the system can recover its data from other chunkservers ◯ E. If a chunkserver fails, the system can recover its data from the main server A is incorrect because the shadow main will temporarily take over and provide read-only access. B is incorrect because data is replicated across multiple chunkservers in a distributed system. C is incorrect because fault tolerance in a distributed system prevents full system failure from one point. E is incorrect because the main server only stores metadata and coordinates tasks. Page 13 of 23 Free Response 1: FourEightyFile (30 points) EECS 485 staff want to build their own file storage application, FourEightyFile, which displays files similar to Dropbox or Google Drive. Users can browse folders. The contents of a folder are displayed in order of popularity (based on access_count ). We have provided the following database schema: CREATE TABLE items ( item_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, parent VARCHAR(12) DEFAULT "home", item_name VARCHAR(12), type VARCHAR(10) NOT NULL, owner VARCHAR(8) NOT NULL, access_count INTEGER, FOREIGN KEY (owner) REFERENCES users(user) ); CREATE TABLE users ( user VARCHAR(8) PRIMARY KEY, is_staff BOOLEAN ); For each entry in the items table, type can be either file or folder . The following helper function is provided for you: def authenticate(password) # takes in a string containing the password # returns True if the password is correct, False otherwise Simplifying assumptions - access_count is not updated when users go back to the parent directory. - Each folder name is unique. - Users will always make requests for folders that exist. - A user is always logged in. - You may assume all necessary libraries have been imported. NOTE: The username of the logged-in user is stored in a session and is called “ logname ”. GET /<folder>/ This route renders the drive.html template with a context dictionary. The context must include: ● folder : The current folder being accessed. ● parent : The parent folder of the current folder. None if there is no parent directory. ● items : A list of dictionaries, each containing the name and type ( file or folder ) of the direct subfolders or files within this folder in descending order by popularity, indicated by access_count . Page 14 of 23 @app.route(''/<folder>/'') def show_folder(folder): con = get_db_connection() cur = con.execute( "SELECT item_name, type FROM items " "WHERE parent = ? " "ORDER BY access_count DESC", (folder,) ) items = cur.fetchall() cur = con.execute( "SELECT parent FROM items " "WHERE item_name = ? ", (folder,) )');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'assume all necessary libraries have been imported. NOTE: The username of the logged-in user is stored in a session and is called “ logname ”. GET /<folder>/ This route renders the drive.html template with a context dictionary. The context must include: ● folder : The current folder being accessed. ● parent : The parent folder of the current folder. None if there is no parent directory. ● items : A list of dictionaries, each containing the name and type ( file or folder ) of the direct subfolders or files within this folder in descending order by popularity, indicated by access_count . Page 14 of 23 @app.route(''/<folder>/'') def show_folder(folder): con = get_db_connection() cur = con.execute( "SELECT item_name, type FROM items " "WHERE parent = ? " "ORDER BY access_count DESC", (folder,) ) items = cur.fetchall() cur = con.execute( "SELECT parent FROM items " "WHERE item_name = ? ", (folder,) ) parent = cur.fetchone()["parent"] context = { "folder": folder, "items": items, "parent": parent, } return flask.render_template("drive.html", **context) drive.html Write the <body> tag of a Jinja template for the drive. It should include: ● The header for the page “EECS485” ● The name of the current folder being viewed. ● A hyperlink with the name of the immediate parent folder, with the path to the parent folder. Nothing needs to be displayed if there is no parent. ● If the item is a file, display the filename with a hyperlink to /uploads/<filename> ● If the item is a folder, display a form. ○ Upon submission, a POST request is made to /access_folder/ with the target set to the subfolder URL (not including the parent in the path). ○ If the folder name is "eecs485staff", display a text input for the password. Page 15 of 23 and forms as the screenshots. The styling and icons are not necessary. home folder view (no parent dir) agirdhar subfolder view (with parent dir home ) <body> <p>EECS 485</p> {% if parent %} <a href="/{{parent}}/">/{{parent}}/</a> {% endif %} <p>{{folder}}</p> {% for item in items %} {% if item.type == "file" %} <a href="/uploads/{{item.item_name}}">{{item.item_name}}</a> {% else %} <form action="/access_folder/?target=/{{item.item_name}}/" method="post"> <input type="submit" value="{{item.item_name}}"> {% if item.item_name == "eecs485staff" %} <input type="text" name="password" value="Password" /> {% endif %} </form> {% endif %} {% endfor %} </body> Page 16 of 23 POST /access_folder/ This route accepts a POST request which authenticates the password (if there is one), updates the access count for the subfolder, and redirects to the subfolder specified by target. ● The eecs485staff folder is the only folder with a password. If the password is incorrect, abort with response code 403. Use the helper function provided for authentication. ● The user accessing the folder must be either the user who owns the folder or a staff member. Otherwise, abort with response code 403. ● Increment the access count for the folder that has been successfully accessed. ● Redirect to the target page. Hint: The strip function might be useful to get the name of the folder from the');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'action="/access_folder/?target=/{{item.item_name}}/" method="post"> <input type="submit" value="{{item.item_name}}"> {% if item.item_name == "eecs485staff" %} <input type="text" name="password" value="Password" /> {% endif %} </form> {% endif %} {% endfor %} </body> Page 16 of 23 POST /access_folder/ This route accepts a POST request which authenticates the password (if there is one), updates the access count for the subfolder, and redirects to the subfolder specified by target. ● The eecs485staff folder is the only folder with a password. If the password is incorrect, abort with response code 403. Use the helper function provided for authentication. ● The user accessing the folder must be either the user who owns the folder or a staff member. Otherwise, abort with response code 403. ● Increment the access count for the folder that has been successfully accessed. ● Redirect to the target page. Hint: The strip function might be useful to get the name of the folder from the target string. eg. text.strip("#") removes all the # characters from the text string and returns the result. @app.route(''/access_folder/'', methods=["POST"]) def handle_post(): con = get_db_connection() target = flask.request.args["target"] password = flask.request.form.get("password") logname = flask.session["logname"] folder = target.strip("/") if folder == "eecs485staff" and not authenticate(password): flask.abort(403) cur = con.execute( "SELECT * FROM items " "JOIN users " "ON items.owner = users.user " "WHERE (items.item_name = ? AND items.owner = ?) " "OR (users.user = ? AND users.is_staff = 1)", (folder, logname, logname) ) result = cur.fetchone() if not result: flask.abort(403) con.execute( "UPDATE items " "SET access_count = access_count + 1 " "WHERE item_name = ?", (folder, ) ) return flask.redirect(target) Page 17 of 23 Free Response 2: Life485 (30 points) EECS 485 staff wants to design a Life485 App to help people locate their friends! Implement a user interface that can show friends'' locations and speeds on the map. World component: ● Declares 1 state variable: ○ Friends (type list) stores the list of friends from the API ● Renders the list of friends. For each friend: ○ Render a Friend component with their unique id . ○ Pass in the handleDelete function. Friend component: ● Takes 2 props: ○ handleDelete : the handler that deletes the friend. ○ id : the id of the friend. ● Declares 4 state variables: ○ name (string), xLocs (list) , yLocs (list) ○ isFinished (boolean): When false render an empty component; when true, render the friend information. ● Updates friends’ state information every 1 second . ● Stores the 10 most recent x and y positions from API calls to calculate and display speed using the calculateSpeed function. If there are less than 10 data points, “Not enough data” should be displayed, and calculateSpeed should not be called. Page 18 of 23 stored yet. Current speed is found using the calculateSpeed function. ● Positions the Friend component’s HTML at the correct coordinate. API routes: Note: You should correctly handle any errors thrown by API calls to the backend service. You should print a reasonable error message to the console. GET ''/api/v1/friends/<int: friend_id>/'' This API endpoint');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, source, topic_tag, content) VALUES (1, 'exam', NULL, 'the handler that deletes the friend. ○ id : the id of the friend. ● Declares 4 state variables: ○ name (string), xLocs (list) , yLocs (list) ○ isFinished (boolean): When false render an empty component; when true, render the friend information. ● Updates friends’ state information every 1 second . ● Stores the 10 most recent x and y positions from API calls to calculate and display speed using the calculateSpeed function. If there are less than 10 data points, “Not enough data” should be displayed, and calculateSpeed should not be called. Page 18 of 23 stored yet. Current speed is found using the calculateSpeed function. ● Positions the Friend component’s HTML at the correct coordinate. API routes: Note: You should correctly handle any errors thrown by API calls to the backend service. You should print a reasonable error message to the console. GET ''/api/v1/friends/<int: friend_id>/'' This API endpoint accepts GET requests and returns information about a friend using their id. GET /api/v1/friends/<int:friend_id>/ Returns { "name": <string>, "id":<integer>, "x": <integer>, "y": <integer> } Hints: ● const interval = setInterval(func, x) calls func every x milliseconds until clearInterval(interval) is called. The first call is made after x milliseconds. Setting a timer is a side effect , so you should follow best practices for avoiding race conditions with stale effects ● Array elements in Javascript can be accessed using their index. E.g. nums[0] returns the first element of the array. You can get the length of an array using .length , e.g. nums.length . ● You can access part of an array using slice(<int>) . E.g . nums.slice(1) returns an array with all but the first element ● To position the friend at its coordinates, use the top and left style properties on the Friend component’s HTML element. For example, <div style={{ position: "absolute", top: <y>, left: <x> }}></div> “top” should be set to the y coordinate and “left” should be set to the x coordinate. Page 19 of 23 Page 20 of 23 10 //returns the modified or unmodified array const appendAndTrim = (array, data) => { const newArray = [...array, data]; if (newArray.length > 10) { return newArray.slice(1); } else { return newArray; } } Page 21 of 23 }, []); Page 22 of 23 Page 23 of 23');
